<1ST_LINE>u p AM-DebateReaction     10-05 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Debate Reaction,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reaction Typically Partisan to Vice Presidential Debate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Debate Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans declared that Dan Quayle exceeded
expectations in the vice presidential debate Wednesday night, while
Democrats said the confrontation demonstrated Lloyd Bentsen's
experience and qualifications for president.
   As expected, reaction to the 90-minute debate held in Omaha,
Neb., and broadcast nationally, was strongly partisan, with backers
of Republican George Bush praising Quayle's performance, and
supporters of Democrat Michael Dukakis, declaring Bentsen the
victor.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater described President
Reagan as ``gratified'' by the outcome and said the president
called Quayle to congratulate him.
   Democratic Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois said, ``Neither scored a
knockout, but Lloyd Bentsen looked and sounded more presidential.''
   ``I don't think there's any question Quayle made himself an
asset to the ticket tonight,'' said Sen. Mitch McConnell of
Kentucky, a national co-chairman of the George Bush campaign.
``Prior to tonight he was not.''
   Bentsen's jibe at Quayle when the Indiana senator compared his
experience to that of John F. Kennedy drew a mixed reaction.
   ``Jack Kennedy was a friend of mine,'' the Texas Democrat told
Quayle. ``Senator, you're no Jack Kennedy.''
   ``That was uncalled for, senator,'' retorted Quayle.
   ``It threw a chill over the whole debate, a sour note,'' said
Atlanta-based pollster Clairbourne Darden. ``It changed from then
on, the way you looked at Lloyd Bentsen.''
   But Democrats said Quayle looked bad when he tried to compare
himself with Kennedy.
   ``I think Quayle's worst moment was when he tried to cpmpare
himself to Jack Kennedy,'' said Democratic Sen. Alan Cranston of
California.
   ``He (Quayle) was forced to think for himself and it didn't go
over,'' said Sen. Albert Gore Jr., D-Tenn.
   Steve Teichner, a California pollster, said he saw no clear
winner.
   ``Because of the low expectations for Quayle, the polls will
probably show that Quayle probably won,'' said Teichner. ``As for
whether the debate will help in the overall race, I think it's a
wash.''
   Merle Black, a political scientist at the University of North
Carolina, said, ``I think Bentsen did a better job. I think the
Dukakis ticket ought to be helped by his performance.''
   But he also praised Quayle who, he said, ``performed well enough
that the Bush campaign will not have to engage in extensive damage
control after tonight. But I think he was out-debated by Bentsen.''
   Nancy Neuman, president of the League of Women Voters, called
the debate a draw.
   ``I don't see that one outshone the other particularly,'' she
said. ``I think they came off pretty well as they intended. Whether
the voters won, I'm still trying to figure out.''
</TEXT>
