<DOCNO> AP881005-0005 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 2344EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Quayle 3rdLd-Writethru a0860 10-05 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0860,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Public Told It Will `See the Real Dan Quayle'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 8 grafs after 6th graf pvs bgng, `Thank you,' to
UPDATE with Quayle at rally, new quotes</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential nominee Dan
Quayle said Wednesday night that he did ``great'' in his debate
with Lloyd Bentsen and said he was pleased at being grilled three
times about his qualifications for higher office.
   ``We were delighted that they brought it up three different
times because it gave us three different times to talk to the
American people about what I'll do for the country,'' Quayle said
as he left the Civic Auditorium where the debate was held and
headed toward a post-debate rally.
   Asked about his performance, Quayle smiled at reporters and
said, ``Great.''
   David Prosperi, Quayle's spokesman, said Quayle received
congratulatory calls after the debate from Vice President George
Bush, President Reagan and Senate Republican leader Bob Dole.
   He quoted Bush as telling his running mate, ``You did great.''
   ``Thank you very much,'' Quayle told Bush, according to Prosperi.
   At the rally at an outdoor park following the debate, Quayle
asked 2,000 flag-waving supporters, ``Did we win the debate?''
   They shouted back: ``Yes.''
   Referring to Wednesday's American League playoff game in which
the Oakland Athletics beat the Boston Red Sox 2-1, Quayle said,
``This afternoon, the team from Massachusetts lost, and tonight,
the man from Massachusetts lost.''
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis is governor of
Massachusetts.
   Quayle said Bentsen had made ``absolutely no response to the
fact that Michael Dukakis is simply out of step with mainstream
America.''
   ``After tonight, America has a little better picture of the road
that we want to take right into the 21st Century,'' Quayle said.
   As he was leaving the rally to head for his hotel room, Quayle
was asked by reporters about Bentsen's comment during the debate
that ``You're no Jack Kennedy.''
   ``It was uncalled for,'' Quayle said.
   Before the debate, Quayle, in a jocular mood, had admonished the
press to ``Watch us carefully. Take good notes. Good news stories
now.''
   ``I feel good,'' Quayle said as he left his hotel for the debate.
   Earlier Wednesday, the Indiana senator, wearing makeup for his
morning rehearsal before the cameras and tour of the Civic
Auditorium stage with his top aides, looked confident and relaxed.
   ``We're ready,'' Quayle told reporters as he emerged from his
hotel. Asked if he was nervous, Quayle replied, ``Not yet.''
   ``The mike works. That's very important to make sure the mike
works and ours is working well,' he said as he left the debate hall.
   As for Bentsen, his Democratic counterpart, Quayle joked, ``I
just hope he shows up.''
   Quayle had a low-key day as he prepared for the debate. He spent
the afternoon relaxing in his hotel room, except for a brief walk
outside.
   When reporters asked about his debate strategy, Quayle said,
``We don't want to give any strategies away.''
   But, he said: ``You're going to see Dan Quayle as he really is.
You're going to see the real Dan Quayle.''
   Quayle and his aides telegraphed his strategy days ago, saying
the focus would be on Dukakis rather than Bentsen, who the
Republicans say is closer to them than the Democrats on many issues.
   ``Dukakis is running for president, and he's the one I'm very
concerned about becoming president,'' Quayle told reporters
Tuesday. ``It would be a very troubling notion for many Americans.''
   Quayle took part in two mock debates this week with Sen. Bob
Packwood, R-Ore., who played Bentsen, and has had dozens of issues
briefings. He said Packwood and his briefing team ``thought of
every tough question you could possibly think of'' during the
rehearsals.
   ``I gave brilliant answers,'' he said.
</TEXT>
