<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush-Debate 1stLd-Writethru a0812 10-05 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Debate, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0812,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Praises Quayle's Performance in Debate</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 3 grafs after 3rd graf bgng, `Asked if,' to UPDATE
with Bush calling Quayle after debate ends</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas, (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush praised running mate Dan
Quayle's performance in the nationally televised debate Wednesday
night with rival Lloyd Bentsen, saying Quayle hit a ``home run'' on
his first answer.
   ``He's doing good, good opening, strong opening, right out of
the ball park, the Canseco of American politics,'' Bush told
reporters, referring to Oakland A's baseball player Jose Canseco.
``He hit it the first answer, home run.,''
   Asked if the question to Quayle _ a Republican senator from
Indiana _ on criticisms of his qualifications was a fair one, Bush
replied, ``Everything's fair in this business. ... I'd like to get
a slow ball like that in the first one. It's easy.''
   After the debate, Bush called Quayle to congratulate him,
according to David Prosperi, Quayle's spokesman.
   He quoted Bush as telling his running mate, ``You did great.''
   ``Thank you very much,'' Quayle told Bush, according to Prosperi.
   The vice president, who had arrived at his hotel here in time to
watch Quayle take on Bentsen, a Democratic senator from Texas, had
invited reporters to watch the first question with him.
   ``Deja vu ... same podiums we used,'' Bush commented, referring
to his debate with Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis,
the governor of Massachusetts.
   His concern with staging was evident as he commented on Quayle's
position when he shook hands with Bentsen. ``Full-faced, looks
good,'' he said, then added, laughing, ``Full-face, turn, it's a
very important thing.''
   Earlier Wednesday, Bush had taken some time out from campaigning
to telephone Quayle and wish him well in the debate, according to
Bush's chief of staff, Craig Fuller.
   During the 10-minute conversation, Bush told Quayle, ``Relax, I
know it will go well.''
</TEXT>
