<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 0036EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-GulfMines     10-05 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Mines,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mine Threat Serious But Ignored, Military Sources Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Governments with a stake in the oil-rich
Persian Gulf should give urgent priority to the threat from mines,
Western military and diplomatic officials say.
   Even though there is a cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war, ``the
mines don't know there's a cease-fire,'' said U.S. Navy Capt. Jim
Miller.
   Miller, who has commanded the U.S. mine-sweeping contingent in
the gulf for the past few months, said Monday, ``They're out there,
cocked and ready to fire. If we don't deal with them on our terms,
we'll have to deal with them on theirs.''
   At least seven mines have been found in the Persian Gulf since
the truce went into effect 45 days ago, and military sources speak
of a ``statistical probability'' that a ship will hit one of the
explosives.
   American intelligence assessments say there are 150 to 200 mines
still in the gulf, concentrated in the north. Most are believed to
have been laid by Iran and some by Iraq, officers say, but neither
country has provided data on the locations.
   These officers have predicted that the problem will worsen as
winter storms cause more of the long-submerged explosives to break
loose and follow prevailing currents down the western coast of the
gulf.
   Military sources, speaking on condition they not be identified,
said the mines threaten not only shipping but the fishing industry,
underwater oil pipelines and children who sometimes find the
odd-looking globes washed up on beaches.
   Several coastal fishing dhows have been sunk or damaged by
mines. One source recalled that two Bahrain children were killed by
a mine last year, and said another was found recently in Qatar.
   Between 12 and 50 mines are known to have been sunk, unexploded,
by local naval units off the coast between Kuwait and the United
Arab Emirates, one source said. ``If those aren't found and
destroyed, one of them bumping against a pipeline and exploding
could create an immense pollution problem,'' he said.
   Progress toward a coordinated effort to clear the mines is
impeded by political concerns within the six-member Gulf
Cooperation Council, the military and diplomatic sources said.
   The countries _ Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Bahrain, Qatar, the United
Arab Emirates and Oman _ remained nominally neutral during the war
but supported Iraq against non-Arab Iran.
   Now, say Western diplomats, the council states are reluctant to
undertake any action that either Baghdad or Tehran might interpret
as hostile. ``As long as the Geneva peace talks remain stalled,
nobody wants to do anything that could be seen as `anti-anybody,'
said one diplomat.
   The mine threat, one said, ``isn't something they're paying a
lot of attention to, and they're not likely to until things start
to go bang in the night.''
   Although council states privately welcomed the foreign warships
sent to the gulf last year to escort tankers, their presence
remains a touchy political issue and the governments might not
recognize the mine problem before anti-mine vessels leave the gulf,
one Western source said.
   There now are at least 16 foreign mine sweepers in the gulf
region, including six U.S., three British, two Italian, two French,
one Belgian, one Dutch and one or more Soviet.
   U.S. officers say there are no plans for the 30-year-old,
wooden-hulled American craft to leave and suggest some might remain
indefinitely.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
