<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 0042EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     10-05 0935</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,930</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmers' Share of Food Dollar Lowest in 75 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New government figures show that farmers last
year got the smallest portion of the food shopper's dollar since
the Agriculture Department began compiling such figures 75 years
ago.
   According to revised figures by the department's Economic
Research Service, the ``farm value'' of the retail cost of a market
basket of food sold in grocery stores in 1987 was 30 percent, down
for the third straight year from 35 percent in 1984.
   The farmer's share of the food dollar dropped to 32 percent in
1985 and to 31 percent in 1986.
   Earlier Agriculture Department estimates had put those readings
even lower: to 31 percent in 1985, 30 percent in 1986 and 29
percent in 1987.
   Department records show the farm share of each consumer food
dollar averaged 46 percent in 1913, when recordkeeping began. Until
the figure fell to 31 percent in 1986, the record low mark had been
32 percent in both 1932 and 1933 during the Depression. The high
was more than 50 percent in World War II and for a few years
thereafter.
   The market basket contains average quantities of domestically
produced food bought in grocery stores, excluding non-alcoholic
beverages, and fish and seafood.
   One reason for the slippage in the farm value of grocery items
has been a general weakening of prices for some raw commodities.
But the situation varies greatly from item to item. And it depends
on how much processing is involved.
   ``Only a slight amount of raw milk is lost, for example, as it
is handled and processed for sale in cartons to consumers,'' the
report said. ``Therefore, the farm value of the retail price per
half-gallon is just a little more than the price that milk
producers receive per half-gallon.''
   The report added: ``In contrast, nearly 2.4 pounds of live
animal are needed to yield one pound of Choice beef on the meat
counter. The payment the cattle producer receives for that large
quantity of live animal is the gross farm value in the price of one
pound of retail beef.''
   With the 1987 farm value of groceries at 30 cents of each
consumer food dollar, that means 70 cents went to non-farmers, the
people who buy, transport, process and sell food at wholesale and
retail.
   Each time the farmer's share declines, it means a greater
``farm-retail'' share for the others.
   Ralph Parlett, a food economist in the agency, says the trend to
a smaller share for farmers also is the result of a growing
consumer preference for a greater degree of processing in food.
   When the farmer's share of the food dollar was 45 cents to 49
cents in the early 1950s, there was less processing. People bought
raw food, took it home and cooked or preserved it. Now, Parlett
said in a recent telephone interview, supermarkets display the
latest in the processor's art.
   ``The products we have today aren't the same,'' he said.
``Microwave products are an example. We didn't have those at all a
few years ago.''
   Also, he said, the ``efficiencies of farmers have picked up,''
meaning that greater yields are resulting from the same acreages,
more meat from the same amount of feed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fears of a decade ago that city sprawl might
consume farmland by the millions of acres annually have not
materialized, according to a new study by the Agriculture
Department.
   Marlow Vesterby and Douglas H. Brooks of the department's
Economic Research Service estimated that urban areas grew at the
rate of about 740,000 acres a year during the 1970s.
   ``Concern continues about the survival of farms in high-growth,
rural-urban fringe areas and about the adequacy of cropland for
future food and fiber production,'' they said in the latest issue
of Agricultural Outlook magazine. ``However, ERS calculations based
on aerial photographs show that urbanization of agricultural land
is not occurring as rapidly as previously thought.''
   In January 1981, just before the Carter administration left
office, a report by the National Agricultural Lands Study said new
intiatives were needed to protect farmland and to ensure that the
nation would have enough productive capacity.
   The study estimated that the United States was losing
agricultural land at the rate of about 3 million acres a year,
including about 1 million acres from the nation's cropland base.
   Other experts at the time questioned the study's figures as
misleading. They asserted that the United States was in no danger
of running out of cropland.
   The study also estimated that American farmers would have to
plant between 84 million and 143 million additional acres by the
year 2000 ``in order to meet anticipated domestic and foreign
demands for agricultural products.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says farmers soon
will be getting about $1.2 billion in cash payments for
participating in the Conservation Reserve Program.
   Milton Hertz, executive vice president of the department's
Commodity Credit Corp., said Tuesday the payments are rental fees
for land contracts signed in the 1986, 1987 and 1988 fiscal years.
   Under the program, farmers agree to take highly erodible
cropland from production for 10 years. In return, USDA helps pay
for planting the land with protective grass or trees and provides
annual rental payments over the 10-year contract period.
   The goal under the program is to take 40 million to 45 million
acres of highly erodible land from crop production by 1990. More
than 25.5 million acres have have been enrolled officially, and an
additional 3.4 million acres were offered by farmers in a recent
signup.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
