<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Jurors     10-05 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Jurors,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Considers Whether All-White Jury Was Unfair to Black
Defendant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court is deciding whether
excluding prospective jurors because of race violates a criminal
defendant's right to a jury representing a cross-section of the
community.
   The high court ruled in 1986 that racially motivated
disqualifications violate equal-protection provisions of the law.
   However, Chicago attorney Patricia Unsinn asked the justices
Tuesday to expand on that decision by ordering a new trial for
Frank D. Teague, a black man convicted of armed robbery and
attempted murder.
   An all-white jury found Teague guilty in August 1978 after a
Cook County prosecutor used all of his peremptory challenges _ the
disqualification of potential jurors without stating a reason _ to
exclude 10 blacks from the jury.
   The Supreme Court ruled on April 30, 1986, in a case called
Batson vs. Kentucky, that a defendant's right to equal protection
would be violated if prosecutors disqualified potential jurors
based on their race.
   It later held that the ruling does not apply to convicted
criminals who had exhausted direct appeals in state courts prior to
the announcement of the Batson decision.
   While the Batson ruling came too late to help Teague, his
attorney argued that the exclusion of blacks also violated her
client's Sixth Amendment right to a jury representing a
cross-section of the community.
   ``Because the prosecutor took affirmative action to destroy the
representative makeup of that jury, we did not get the protection
that the Sixth Amendment guarantees,'' Unsinn said.
   Assistant Illinois Attorney General David E. Bindi argued that
it is impossible to ensure a representative cross-section of the
community for every trial and said the fact that Teague's jury was
all white did not necessarily deny him a fair trial.
   ``Cross-sectionalism is not the litmus test of impartiality,''
Bindi said. ``To equate jury impartiality with some form of mix on
the jury ... is to take a dangerous step toward saying that juries
be filled by quotas.''
   The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled in May 1987 that
past Supreme Court decisions make clear the fair cross-section
requirement of the Sixth Amendment does not apply to the jury
itself, but only to the pool of potential jurors from which the
jury is chosen.
   The Supreme Court is expected to rule on the case sometime next
year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
