<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     10-05 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GEORGETOWN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Kenny Walters used 3,000 $1 bills
to pay the county taxes on his tool-rental business, he thought his
feelings were clear and the matter was closed.
   But Clear Creek County Treasurer Geraldine Thompson may have
upstaged Walters. She returned his change of $110 mostly in
nickels, dimes and pennies.
   ``I guess he was just trying to make a statement,'' said
Thompson. ``I just gave him all the change I could dish out. I
mean, turnabout is fair play.''
   Walters said he enjoyed Thompson's response to his ``silent
protest.'' He said he was trying to make a point when he paid his
$2,890 in taxes in person with an old gunpowder crate full of $1
bills.
   ``I don't mind paying my property taxes,'' said Walters. ``But
sometimes they (county officials) have a tendency not to realize
how much money they're taking from people.
   ``I only get to see $3,000 twice a year _ once when I borrow it
to pay my income taxes and once when I borrow to pay my property
taxes.''
   Thompson said she has known Walters for about seven years and
realized he has an ``ornery'' sense of humor. She said it could
have been worse:
   ``He could have undone the bundles and just thrown them at me.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At first, teacher Shirley Cooley wasn't
sure what her third grade students at Greenville Elementary School
could learn from a truckload of pumpkins.
   But her experiment turned out to be a lesson in entrepreneurship
for the youngsters.
   Ms. Cooley lent her class $100 to start their own business,
called the Pumpkin Patch. She then persuaded her brother-in-law,
orchard owner Joe Huber, to give the class more than 300 pumpkins.
   Ms. Cooley's loan covered the cost of paint and brushes, which
the children use to draw goblin faces on the pumpkins. The
youngsters then sold their handiwork back to Huber at $1.50 each.
He, in turn, sells them to the public.
   The students already have made enough to pay off their loan. Ms.
Cooley expects the class to turn a profit of about $500, which will
be used to pay for several field trips. Extra money will be given
to the school to purchase playground equipment, she said.
   ``At the beginning of the year, many of these kids had a
difficult time calculating the value of money and being able to
make the right change, but this project has really gotten through
to them,'' Ms. Cooley said.
</TEXT>
