<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-NCAA     10-05 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-NCAA,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Studies NCAA's Disciplinary Practices</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Prenoon EDT top planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Basketball coach Jerry Tarkanian's long feud
with the NCAA is being refereed by the Supreme Court in a case
testing the collegiate organization's disciplinary authority.
   The court's decision could affect, among other things, the
National Collegiate Athletic Association's investigations into
alleged drug use by some athletes.
   The justices, who granted an NCAA appeal last February, were to
hear arguments in the case today. A decision is expected by July.
   Tarkanian, head coach at the University of Nevada at Las Vegas
since 1973, is trying to preserve the victory he won in lower
courts and avoid a two-year suspension for alleged NCAA violations.
   Following a 30-month investigation, NCAA officials said
Tarkanian arranged for a student to get a ``B'' grade without
attending class, provided free air fare to a student-athlete,
encouraged individuals to give the NCAA false information to impede
its probe, falsely certified UNLV's program as complying with NCAA
rules and failed to comport with high ethical standards.
   The Nevada Supreme Court ruled that Tarkanian was denied
due-process during the NCAA investigation that led to his
suspension. But to reach that conclusion, the state court had to
find that the NCAA, a private organization, acted with governmental
power.
   The justices' handling of that larger issue will affect coaches
and athletes at state-run NCAA member schools across the nation.
   Individuals and private organizations generally cannot violate
someone's constitutional rights. Only a government and its agents
can do that because the Constitution protects against governmental
_ not private _ wrongdoing.
   Courts call the concept the ``doctrine of state action.''
   The NCAA is a private organization representing nearly 1,000
colleges and universities.
   But in the Tarkanian case, the state court said the NCAA was
acting as a surrogate for UNLV, a state university.
   ``The right to discipline public employees is traditionally the
exclusive prerogative of the state,'' the Nevada court said. ``UNLV
cannot escape responsibility for disciplinary action against
employees by delegating that duty to a private entity.''
   Because the NCAA investigators were acting as agents of a state
school, the state court ruled, Tarkanian was entitled to more due
process _ more opportunities to be heard and more information about
the investigation.
   The NCAA, insisting its investigation was not ``state action,''
sought help from the nation's highest court.
   If the justices agree with the Nevada court, the NCAA will find
itself in a curious position. It will have to afford more
due-process rights to coaches and athletes at state-run schools
than those who work for or attend private schools.
   The UNLV program was placed on two years' probation in 1977 for
recruiting violations, and the NCAA that same year ordered the
school to suspend Tarkanian.
   His court fight staved off the suspension, and won him the right
to have the NCAA pay some of his legal fees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
