<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Set-Aside     10-05 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Set-Aside,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Hears Case On Minority Role In Public Works Projects</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top planned after conclusion of arguments, scheduled for noon
EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The power of states and local governments to
require minority participation in public works projects is being
explored by the Supreme Court in a key affirmative action dispute.
   The justices were to hear arguments today over a Richmond, Va.,
program that set aside 30 percent of the value of all municipal
building projects for minority participation. The court is expected
to decide by July whether the plan should be reinstated.
   The plan was challenged successfully in a lower court by J.A.
Croson Co., a building contractor.
   At stake could be similar set-aside plans established by most
states and some 190 local governments.
   The case also is attracting widespread attention because of what
it might foretell about the court's future approach to other forms
of affirmative action and alleged reverse discrimination.
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy is participating in his first case
involving preferential treatment for minorities since joining the
court last February. He replaced Justice Lewis F. Powell, who often
cast the deciding vote on affirmative action issues in the closely
divided court.
   Set-aside programs also have caused some deep divisions and
seemingly contradictory views within the Reagan administration.
   President Reagan, for example, said in 1984 he favored
channeling billions of additional contract dollars to
minority-owned firms. And the administration generally has looked
upon public works set-asides more sympathetically than other
affirmative action quotas it sternly opposes.
   But the Justice Department, responding to an invitation from the
Supreme Court in a case similar to the Richmond dispute, challenged
the constitutionality of set-asides.
   The Richmond plan was declared unlawful in September 1987 by the
4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals. The appeals court said there is
insufficient evidence that Richmond city officials discriminated
against minority-owned businesses in the past.
   Also, the appeals court said the city's 30 percent quota
appeared to be a completely arbitrary figure that ``simply emerged
from the mists.''
   Richmond adopted the plan in 1983 to require that a prime
contractor on any city building project subcontract at least 30
percent of the value of the project to firms that are at least
one-half minority owned.
   The minorities named in the plan are blacks, Hispanics,
Orientals, Indians, Eskimos and Aleuts.
   The 4th Circuit court, in invalidating the program, relied
heavily on a 1986 Supreme Court ruling that struck down an
affirmative action plan in Michigan designed to protect from
lay-offs the jobs of minority teachers with less seniority than
whites.
   The justices in that case said preferential treatment of
minorities must be narrowly tailored to avoid hurting whites. The
justices also restricted the power of employers to adopt
affirmative action programs when there has not been proof the
employers practiced past discrimination.
   But civil rights groups point to a 1980 Supreme Court ruling
that allows Congress to earmark 10 percent of federal public works
contracts for minority-controlled businesses.
   The court also has upheld other forms of affirmative action
programs in a string of recent decisions.
   Minorities make up about half of Richmond's population, and
minority-owned businesses received less than 1 percent of the value
of city contracts prior to adoption of the set-aside.
   The plan was challenged by J.A. Croson Co. after its bid _ the
only one submitted to install stainless steel urinals and water
closets at the city jail was rejected.
   City officials refused to award the contract even though Croson
said there was only one minority contractor that could help on that
project and Croson considered that company unqualified. Croson also
said the cost of the project would rise by $7,663 if the minority
contractor took part. The city then called for new bids.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
