<DOCNO> AP881005-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 0120EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Cuba-Drugs     10-05 0142</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Cuba-Drugs,0145</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Yacht, Crew Detained In Cuba</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuban authorities seized a U.S.-registered
yacht in Cuban waters and arrested its three crew members as they
were sailing from Florida to pick up a cocaine shipment in
Colombia, the Cuban news agency Prensa Latina said.
   Prensa Latina, in a dispatch monitored in Mexico City on
Tuesday, quoted an Interior Ministry statement as saying coast
guard personnel seized the Rosendo Cardoso on Monday after the
yacht entered Cuban territorial waters.
   The ministry statement identified the three crew members as
German Cardoso Cruz, Juan Abreu Paez and Calixto Evelio Hidalgo
Diaz. It said all were ``of Cuban origin'' and that they left
Marathon, Fla., ``with the objective of receiving a shipment of
cocaine in Colombia.''
   Prensa Latina said the yacht and crew ``were put at the
disposition of competent authorities.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881005-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 0016EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Honduras-Contras Bjt   10-05 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Honduras-Contras, Bjt,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honduras Wants United Nations To Evict Nicaraguan Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honduras is calling for the creation of a
United Nations peace force to evacuate thousands of Nicaraguan
rebels based in Honduras and relocate them far from its borders.
   The Honduran proposal, unveiled Tuesday night by Foreign
Minister Carlos Lopez Contreras, also would apply to the
comparatively small number of leftist rebels from El Salvador who
operate out of Honduras.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said Tuesday night he
had not seen Lopez Contreras' speech and had no comment.
   Nonetheless, the speech appeared to signal Honduras'
determination to end the tacit cooperation it has been providing to
the United States by allowing the anti-communist rebels to use
Honduras as a staging area for attacks against Nicaragua.
   Underscoring Lopez Contreras' apparent effort to disassociate
Honduras from U.S. policy was his description of the United States,
along with the Soviet Union, as a ``hegemonistic power.''
   Lopez Contreras called on U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar to oversee the creation of a peace force comprised of
troops from Canada, Spain and West Germany.
   The force would guarantee the ``non-use'' of Honduran territory
by foreign insurgents, he said, adding that the proposed unit
should be authorized to use force, if necessary, to achieve its
objectives.
   The unit should locate the combatants in Nicaraguan and
Salvadoran territories, ``far away from Honduran borders,'' he
said. ``Their relocation in third countries should be carried out
from sites in Costa Rica and Guatemala. whose governments have
declared themselves neutral,'' he added.
   The proposal represents a revised and updated version of a plan
which the Hondurans set forth in November 1987. At the time,
however, there were relatively few Contras in the border era.
   Honduras, as a front-line state which shares a long border with
Nicaragua, has been a major pillar of American policy toward
Central America for more than six years. As a deterrent to
potential Nicaraguan aggression, the United States maintains about
1,200 troops in the country and has carried out numerous U.S.
military training missions there. Honduras also has been a major
recipient of U.S. economic aid.
   But Honduras always has been uneasy about the presence of the
U.S.-backed Contras along the border, fearing that the situation
could be used by the militarily powerful Sandinista government as
an excuse to invade Honduras. There have been numerous cross-border
incidents involving the two countries.
   The situation in the region has changed radically since
February, when the Congress rejected an administration proposal for
additional military aid to the Contras. Thousands of Contras have
fled across the border to the Honduran base camps where U.S.
foreign aid officials have been carrying out a large scale
humanitarian assistance program.
   Under an agreement the Contras signed with the Sandinistas in
March, the aid was to have been distributed to Contras in several
designated zones inside Nicaragua. But that plan was never
implemented, leaving many Contras no choice but to go to the border
area for sustenance.
   Honduras has watched these developments unfold with a deep sense
of unease, worried about the possibility that the Contras may
settle in the border area for an indefinite period.
   The rebels and the Sadinista government signed a temporary
cease-fire agreement on March 23 but have been unable to agree on a
lasting peace accord.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881005-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 0123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Quayle     10-05 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Says Will `Be Myself' At Tonight's Debate With Bentsen</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Quayle walk-thru scheduled for 12:45 p.m. EDT; Top prospects
uncertain.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Dan Quayle, with two mock debates
and dozens of issues briefings behind him, says he'll ``just be
myself'' when he faces Democrat Lloyd Bentsen in tonight's
nationally broadcast confrontation between the vice presidential
candidates.
   With George Bush's media guru, Roger Ailes, and a host of top
campaign strategists at his side, Quayle arrived in Omaha Tuesday
night. He declined to tip his hand about debate strategy, saying
only, ``tune in and find out.''
   But it's no secret that Quayle will be on the attack against
Democratic presidential candidate Michael Dukakis, not the Texas
senator, whom the Republicans portray as closer to them on the
issues than to the Democrats.
   ``Dukakis is running for president, and he's the one I'm very
concerned about becoming president. It would be a very troubling
notion for many Americans,'' Quayle told reporters on his campaign
plane en route to Omaha.
   Quayle plans a brief walk-through today of the Omaha Civic
Auditorium, scene of the debate.
   He sounded upbeat and appeared confident Tuesday as he chatted
with reporters in the first such on-the-record session he's had on
his plane.
   ``I'm going to just be myself,'' Quayle said. ``I will be
prepared to answer any and all questions.''
   Quayle said he sees the debate as ``an opportunity to
communicate with the American public in an unedited version.''
   ``They'll be able to see Dan Quayle as I really am,'' he said.
``The American people don't know me. They have a lot of questions
... They don't have any details of who Dan Quayle is.''
   Asked in what areas he was anticipating attacks from Bentsen,
Quayle replied, ``Everywhere.''
   Aides to George Bush were effusive Tuesday in their public
expressions of confidence in the Indiana senator, and denied that
they had tried to boost his odds going into the confrontation by
lowering expectations for his performance.
   ``We are very, very proud of you. We are very, very proud of the
job you are doing for this campaign, and we are very, very proud of
the job we know you're going to do ... in Omaha,'' Bush campaign
chairman James Baker said at a rally at campaign headquarters in
Washington, D.C.
   Quayle's tenure as Bush's running mate has been marked by
intense media scrutiny and controveries over his academic record,
military service and personal life. He has also committed a number
of gaffes and malapropisms during the campaign.
   GOP strategists have said that because Quayle has been portrayed
as a caricature and lightweight candidate he should benefit from
the low expectations for his performance. In essence, they suggest,
anything short of a major blunder will allow him to come away
looking good.
   But Lee Atwater, Bush's campaign manager, said, ``We haven't
done anything at all about lowering expectations.''
   ``I think he'll do fine on all the issues,'' Atwater said.
   Quayle has had two 90-minute mock debates, Saturday and Monday
night, with Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., who played Bentsen during
the debate preparation. His aides have been conducting briefings
along with question-and-answer sessions since last week.
   David Prosperi, Quayle's spokesman, said much of the area they
had focused on involved attacks that were anticipated from Bentsen.
   Polls have indicated that voters have doubts about Quayle's
qualifications, but Prosperi resisted suggestions that tonight's
debate could have a critical effect on the election.
   ``This is only part of the campaign. There's a continuous debate
every day and there will be until Nov. 8,'' he said. ``The debate
will be an important part of it, but it's not the end-all.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
