<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     10-05 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Home For A Day After Courting Midwest Voters</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Dukakis holds news conference at 1:30 p.m. EDT; Top prospects
uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis returned home to catch up on
gubernatorial duties after courting crucial voters in the
industrial Midwest with a promise of a White House that cares about
the plight of struggling families.
   ``I care about working people and working families and that's
the difference between Mike Dukakis and George Bush and Democrats
and Republicans,'' the Democratic presidential nominee told a rally
Tuesday afternoon in Toledo, Ohio. ``We care.''
   Dukakis was in Toledo to tour its Jeep assembly plant, where he
received a warm welcome from its union workers. Earlier he
addressed students and faculty at Northwestern University in
Illinois, and he ended his campaign day by attending two private
receptions in Washington, D.C., with Democratic Party luminaries.
   Dukakis was spending most of today at the Massachusetts
Statehouse and was scheduled to meet with reporters this afternoon.
He also was attending a rally with supporters after tonight's vice
presidential debate between Democrat Lloyd Bentsen and Republican
Dan Quayle.
   Because of the focus on the space shuttle mission and the vice
presidential debate, Dukakis offered no new proposals this week but
sought to bring together his initiatives under the umbrella issue
of restoring U.S. dominance in the world marketplace. He also
underscored the theme of his campaign's largest advertising effort
_ a four-ad series portraying Bush as a product of media handlers
who has presented no viable solutions to the nation's problems.
   ``He offers slogans and symbols; we offer solutions,'' Dukakis
said. ``This nation didn't become the greatest on earth because we
were satisfied with the status quo.''
   Dukakis also repeatedly likened this year's race to the
Kennedy-Nixon contest of 1960, at one point comparing Bush's
tactics to those of Richard M. Nixon in the race 28 years ago.
   ``They said the same thing about Jack Kennedy in 1960 _ all that
gloom and doom,'' Dukakis said. ``And what was he saying? `We can
do better.'''
   Dukakis aides, while conceding they still trail Bush, have said
privately in the past two days that some of Bush's support appears
to be waning and that Dukakis hopes to attract the growing number
of undecided voters in the campaign's final five weeks.
   ``The stakes are very high and the race is geting even closer,''
Dukakis told his Ohio audience.
   In the Illinois speech, Dukakis delivered a sharply worded
attack on Bush and said his rival was running from ``a record of
failure and walking away from every major challenge he has faced.''
   He told the college audience that he and Bentsen would restore
America's leadership in the world economy through innovative
business and labor partnerships at home and a tough trade stance
abroad.
   Dukakis said Bush was trying to pin the ``gloom and doom'' label
on Democrats because he had no answers to the trade and budget
deficits and the decline of research and development in the United
States.
   ``Cite these facts and George Bush will tell you that you're
downgrading America, the same thing Richard Nixon did in 1960 when
John Kennedy was telling us to look to a new frontier,'' Dukakis
said. ``My friends, if we disregard these facts we endanger
America.''
   He also boasted: ``I'm running for president on my record. Mr.
Bush is running away from his _ a record of failure and walking
away from every major challenge he has faced.''
   There were no new proposals in the speech. Dukakis repeated his
familiar call for business-labor partnerships, tough enforcement of
the new trade law, reduction of the trade and budget deficits and
``some reasonable limits on the merger and acquisition binge that
continues to sweep this country.''
</TEXT>
