<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-NationalGuard     10-05 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-National Guard,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Appeals Federal Control Over Guard Units</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael S. Dukakis is fighting in court for the
rights of governors to veto federally issued training assignments
for the National Guard, a position that a U.S. attorney said was a
``dagger aimed at the heart of national defense.''
   In a hearing Tuesday in federal appeals court, Massachusetts
Attorney General Douglas Wilkins argued that governors have a right
under the ``militia clause'' of the Constitution to veto National
Guard training assignments.
   John Bolton, head of the U.S. Justice Department's civil
division, said ``this is a political case'' and warned that
Dukakis, governor of Massachusetts, might regret a victory if
elected president.
   ``The view from Washington is very different from the view from
Boston,'' Bolton said. If each of the 50 governors were allowed to
opt out of controversial training assignments, he said, ``you end
up with potential chaos.''
   Bolton said the state's position amounted to ``a dagger aimed at
the heart of national defense.''
   The issue began when federal authorities ordered 13 public
relations specialists from the Massachusetts National Guard to
train in Honduras and Panama in May and June. Dukakis withheld his
consent and filed suit on Jan. 29 seeking to block the mission.
   However, the court upheld the authority of federal officials on
May 6 on the grounds that National Guard troops are sworn to
federal duty as well as state duty. The mission was carried out.
   The three-judge panel of the 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
said it would review the arguments. Lawyers said it could take
months to issue a ruling.
   Afterward, Dukakis' Statehouse press secretary, James Dorsey,
said Dukakis was trying to uphold a principle endorsed by many
governors of both parties.
   ``There is a very important principle at stake here _ a 200-year
tradition of the states being responsible for the training of the
militia,'' Dorsey said.
   Asked if the Dukakis campaign was concerned that the governor's
position could be used against him in the presidential campaign to
portray Dukakis as ``soft'' on defense, Dorsey shot back: ``Who's
going to make that argument, Dan Quayle?''
   He was referring to Republican vice presidential nominee Dan
Quayle, who came under criticism for seeking a position in the
Indiana National Guard during the Vietnam War, a status that spared
him from combat duty.
   Bolton warned that if Massachusetts prevailed, it would ``permit
governors to interfere in sensitive foreign policy decisions.''
   Specifically, he said, the Constitution gave Congress the power
to enact the 1986 Montgomery Amendment, which prohibited governors
from objecting to National Guard assignments in peacetime unless
their states were facing an emergency such as a flood.
   The Massachusetts case is paralleled by a similar challenge
filed by Minnesota Gov. Rudy Perpich, which was also rejected at
the district court level. The Minnesota case also is on appeal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
