<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfTalks Bjt   10-05 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Talks, Bjt,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq's Foreign Minister Insists Shatt-al-Arab And Gulf Must Be
Navigable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Iraqi foreign minister complained of
Iranian searches of shipping on the Persian Gulf and insisted that
Iraq's outlet to the Persian Gulf be cleared for navigation before
the latest peace talks progress.
   Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz met with U.N. Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar on Tuesday and then spoke to the U.N.
General Assembly.
   Afterward, he told reporters, ``We had a very constructive
exchange of views about the course of the negotiations, and he
(Perez de Cuellar) is going to see my Iranian counterpart.''
   Iraq and Iran renewed peace talks Saturday at U.N. headquarters
in New York after a session in Geneva from Aug. 25 to Sept. 13. The
talks followed a cease-fire Aug. 20 in the 8-year-old war, which
left at least 1 million killed or wounded.
   The statements made by both delegations during the weekend and
by Aziz on Tuesday gave no indication of substantial progress on
major issues.
   When asked Tuesday if Perez de Cuellar had introduced new
proposals to break the deadlock, Aziz answered:
   ``We are discussing all possible ideas, you see, on how to make
further progress, and the discussions went well with his
excellency'' the secretary-general.
   Perez de Cuellar has reportedly suggested that Iraq agree to
postpone discussion of the Shatt-al-Arab waterway, its outlet to
the Persian Gulf, until later in the talks, and that Iran stop
searching neutral ships in the gulf.
   The two belligerents would then proceed to deal with exchange of
prisoners of war and withdrawal of troops.
   Aziz told delegates to the 43rd General Assembly that Iran
``accepted the (Security Council's peace proposal) resolution only
because of a crushing military defeat.
   ``This suspicious position on the part of the Iranian delegation
was followed by its insistence on provisions which impose a de
facto arms embargo on Iraq at sea,'' said Aziz. He was referring to
Iran's searches of neutral ships in the gulf.
   Iraq insists the Shatt-al-Arab waterway forming the southern
border between the two nations must be cleared of sunken ships and
silt accumulated during the war.
   ``Shatt-al-Arab is Iraq's only outlet to the high seas,'' Aziz
said Tuesday. He said navigation there must be addressed for ``the
peace to be durable, comprehensive and just.''
   But Aziz denied he was setting a precondition for peace talks,
calling such an interpretation ``a pure lie and deception.''
   Baghdad also says Iran's policy of searching neutral ships in
the gulf for war cargo bound for Iraq violates the cease-fire,
which calls for ending all military activity.
   Iran says it has the right as a nation at war to search ships
for war material bound for its enemy. It says the issue of
navigation on the Shatt-al-Arab should not be included in peace
talks.
   Aziz's speech was moved up at his request from its scheduled
time Friday to Tuesday evening so he could leave for Baghdad early.
Aziz did not explain his premature departure.
   On Saturday, Aziz met with Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar
Velayati for direct talks, but the session soon shifted to indirect
talks. The secretary-general and his special mediator, Swedish U.N.
Ambassador Jan K. Eliasson, shuttled between the Iranian and Iraqi
delegations in separate rooms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
