<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 0138EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-States-Fiscal     10-05 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-States-Fiscal,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Governments Healthy Now, Vulnerable to Future Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State governments are vulnerable to new
financial strains in 1989, despite their success this year in
maintaining services without major tax increases, according to a
study by the National Governors Association.
   In its biannual survey, the governors said a drop next year in
federal aid could trigger economic problems for states, since their
budget surpluses are narrowing.
   ``These balances, if they hold as projected, are already at
their lowest point in the 12 years we have been producing the
survey,'' said Raymond G. Scheppach, the NGA's executive director.
   The survey released Tuesday showed revenue collections exceeded
expenditures in all three fiscal years studied.
   But the states are reporting steady growth in spending: up 6.3
percent in fiscal 1987, 6 percent the following year and an
estimated 6.8 percent in fiscal 1989.
   In the 1988 legislative session, 27 states passed tax laws, but
most involved minor changes to conform with the new federal tax
structure. The new tax laws were expected to yield less than an
additional $1 billion, with most of the money generated by motor
vehicle fuel tax increases.
   In general, state economies seem to be growing. While the
Northeast and Far West continue to enjoy solid growth, most states
elsewhere that were hurt by poor farm performances and a downturn
in energy prices seem to be making significant economic and
budgetary improvements.
   Here is an overview of the regions:
   _New England: The region enjoys the lowest unemployment rate and
highest personal income growth in the country. The positive
economic signs are manifested in the highest percentage increase in
state expenditures projected for fiscal 1989.
   _Mideast: Unemployment rates are lower than the national average
and increases in personal income are 1 percent higher than the
national average. General fund expenditures are slightly higher
than the aggregate figure for all states.
   _Great Lakes: The region's unemployment rate is higher than the
national average. In addition, the expected fiscal 1989
expenditures show the lowest growth rate in the country.
   _The Plains: These states have made a recovery from the economic
and budgetary doldrums of a few years ago. Since the March
governors' association survey, the unemployment rate dropped
dramatically from 5.5 percent to 4.2 percent. But the annual growth
in personal income also declined in the same period. The growth in
expenditures is slightly above the national average, with the
exception of North Dakota and Minnesota.
   _Southeast: Unemployment has declined and personal income has
risen since the March survey. But the fiscally troubled states of
Kentucky, Louisiana and West Virginia make an analysis of the
region's economy difficult.
   _Southwest: This region has the highest unemployment rate and
the second lowest percentage increase in personal income, in part
because of the oil bust in Texas, the state that dominates the area.
   _Rocky Mountain states: This area struggles to improve its
economic and fiscal health. Personal income growth is the lowest in
the nation, while unemployment is slightly above the national
average.
   _Far West: Growth here continues strong, with personal income
increasing at an average of 6.7 percent annually, led by Nevada
with a rise of 8.9 percent and Oregon at 7.2 percent. Unemployment
is very close to the national average.
</TEXT>
