<HEAD>Bush To Curb His Dukakis Attacks, At Least A Little</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Bush speaks at high school 12:55 p.m. EDT; tops uncertain.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush wants to tone down his attacks on
Democratic presidential rival Michael Dukakis, a top aide contends,
but Bush continues to sprinkle speeches with a hefty dose of
opponent bashing.
   Bush's chief of staff, Craig Fuller, told reporters on Tuesday
that the Republican presidential candidate wanted to get away from
the appearance of waging a negative rather than issue-oriented
campaign.
   ``He was uncomfortable with a perception forming that his is a
campaign that was not talking about issues as much, because he has
been talking about issues,'' said Fuller.
   He cited Bush's first campaign stop Tuesday as evidence of the
new approach.
   In a speech to the business-oriented Comstock Club of
Sacramento, Calif., Bush made barely a passing reference to
Dukakis. He proposed a $100 million program to encourage community
volunteer service by young people. A new foundation, chaired by the
president, would work with existing volunteer programs and act as a
clearinghouse to help get more youths involved in community service.
   Today's campaigning in Denver included remarks on a companion
topic _ what society can do for children and education.
   But after Tuesday's speech calling for a Youth Engaged in
Service to America program of voluntary charitable activity, Bush
went back to some familiar Dukakis one-liners.
   The barbs he delivered in his stump speech to a rowdy rally on
the steps of the Riverside County courthouse lacked a bit of the
sting that has characterized similar recent speeches.
   But he unveiled a new one-liner commenting on Dukakis' proposal
to reduce the deficit by beefing up Internal Revenue Service
collection of unpaid taxes.
   ``Politicians used to promise a chicken in every pot,'' he said.
``He promises a tax agent in every kitchen.''
   By the time he got to a late-afternoon rally in Albuquerque,
Bush was revved up for attack.
   Referring derisively to his opponent as ``the liberal governor
of Massachusetts,'' Bush said: ``I love calling him that. I love
it.''
   Dukakis, Bush said, ``doesn't even dare use the big `L' word''
anymore.
   He trotted out his environmental attack on Dukakis, ridiculing
the Democrat for making an environmental pitch in California when
he was the governor ``who wanted to dump the crud from
Massachusetts'' in a waste site offshore from New Jersey.
   Bush laced the negative comments into a speech in which he
portrayed himself as an environmentalist, ``in the mold of Teddy
Roosevelt,'' and a man concerned about education and crime and one
who wants to build a more caring nation.
   He noted Dukakis had proclaimed himself tough on crime.
   ``If you believe that, he's got some bottled water from the
Boston Harbor to sell you,'' Bush said in one of his favorite
references to the severe pollution in the governor's homestate
harbor.
   But Fuller maintained this week's agenda would be devoted to
more positive issue-based speeches.
   ``He would like his campaign to talk about issues ... and not be
caught up in an attack on his opponent,'' he said.
   That does not mean that Bush is going soft on Dukakis, said
Fuller, forecasting ``future speeches that draw sharp contrasts
between the two candidates.''
   Bush today was visiting Arapahoe High School where the
intinerary included a tour of the science lab and remarks at an
assembly where National Merit Scholarship finalists will be
recognized.
   Bush then was holding a rally at the 16th Street Mall before
heading off for a campaign stop in Oklahoma City.
</TEXT>
