<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Colombia-Peace     10-05 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Colombia-Peace,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Says Government Abandoning Peace Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Virgilio Barco withdrew a
peace proposal to leftist guerrillas because of a wave of rebel
attacks, and the army has been ordered to attack the insurgents, a
cabinet minister said.
   ``It is incomprehensible that the answer by subversive groups to
a generous peace proposal would be so violent and criminal,'' the
minister of government, Cesar Gaviria Trujillo, said in a broadcast
interview Tuesday.
   Trujillo is in charge of internal security in Colombia.
   Last month the president offered a cease-fire, negotiations,
pardons to guerrillas who surrendered and a chance for rebel
leaders to speak before congress.
   All six of Colombia's leftist guerrilla groups rejected the
plan, calling it an ultimatum for surrender.
   Gaviria was particularly critical of the country's largest
guerrilla group, the Colombian Revolutionary Armed Forces, known by
its Spanish acronym as the FARC.
   Sunday and Monday FARC attacks killed 12 soldiers, six policemen
and three civilians, the Defense Ministry said Monday.
   ``The government authorizes full institutional support for the
armed forces to confront the guerrillas, because weakness or
complacency doesn't result in peace,'' Gaviria said in an interview
with the Bogota radio station Caracol.
   Minister of Justice Guillermo Plazas said the guerrillas' answer
to ``the olive branch offered by President Barco has been attacks
on the army, blowing up of pipelines and setting off bombs.''
   The FARC has used a cease-fire during the last four years ``to
cheat the government'' by building up its strength, Plazas said in
a broadcast interview with the Bogota radio station RCN.
   The FARC signed a truce with the government of President
Belisario Betancur four years ago. There has been sporadic fighting
between the FARC and government security forces during the truce.
   Another guerrilla group, the National Liberation Army, has blown
up the country's main oil pipeline 85 times in the last two years.
   Last Saturday the guerrilla group blew up the pipeline, which
carries 225,000 barrels of oil a day from the Canon Limon field in
the northeast state of Arauca.
   Last Wednesday the National Liberation Army set off a bomb in
Bogota as the car of a Texaco executive was passing by.
   The executive, John Buttle, a Canadian, was not injured.
   And last July the National Liberation Army kidnapped the owner
of General Pipe Co., of Houston, Jake Gambini. There has been no
word on Gambini's fate.
</TEXT>
