with a photographer, publicists said.
   Rob Camilletti, 24, was arrested June 27 and booked for
investigation of felony assault with a deadly weapon after a
confrontation with Star tabloid photographer Peter Brandt outside
the Benedict Canyon home that Camilletti and Cher share. He was
released on $2,000 bail.
   Camilletti said he lost control of Cher's Ferrari and crashed
into Brandt's car while swerving into the home's driveway to avoid
photographers. He has admitted to smashing Brandt's camera.
   ``He tried to kill me. He tried to run me over at a high rate of
speed,'' Brandt said at the time.
   In a statement released Tuesday by publicists Lois Smith and
Lisa Kasteler, Camilletti said: ``I'm very pleased that the city
attorney understood that I never tried to hit the tabloid
photographer. It's true that I broke the guy's camera and telephone
after the accident, and I intend to reimburse him for that.''
   The release said the city attorney's office concluded that
Camilletti had not intended to run down the photographer.
   ``With this decision not to file any felony charges, I am now
hopeful that Cher and I can get back to some degree of normalcy
with our lives,'' he said.
   The city attorney could not immediately be reached for comment
by The Associated Press as there was no answer at the office
Tuesday evening. An attorney for Brandt also was out of the office.
   At the time, Cher and Camilletti, who is launching his own
acting career, said the crash was the result of weeks of
frustration with photographers they said were harassing them.
   Brandt filed a lawsuit against Cher and Camilletti, seeking
unspecified damages.
