<HEAD>New Truce Violations Reported in Nicaragua, 16 Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Honduras-Contras, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas battled government troops
at least seven times during recent days in new truce violations,
and 16 rebels were killed, the Defense Ministry reported.
   Meanwhile, military sources speaking on condition of anonymity
said two relatives of President Daniel Ortega were wounded when
rebels ambushed a civilian vehicle Tuesday in Chontales province.
Government officials did not confirm the report.
   The Defense Ministry statement released Tuesday night did not
say if there were any government casualties in the clashes.
   It said rebels attacked Monday in speedboats with 60-mm mortars
at a government border post 125 miles northwest of Managua. The
post at El Charro is on the Gulf of Fonseca, which is shared by
Nicaragua, Honduras and El Salvador on the Pacific coast.
   The Ministry said the other clashes occurred Saturday through
Monday in northern Jinotega and southeastern Zelaya Sur provinces.
   Defense Ministry sources said rebels wounded Ortega's relatives
when they ambushed a civilian vehicle Tuesday morning in central
Chontales province.
   They identified the two relatives as Irma Mongrio Rivas and
Alfonso Ortega. Mongrio Rivas suffered a bullet wound in a leg, the
sources said. The extent of Alfonso Ortega's injuries was not known.
   Their exact relationship to the president could not be
determined.
   The temporary truce between the leftist Sandinista government
and U.S.-supported rebels has been in effect on March 21. Each side
has accused the other of frequent violations, and negotiations
aimed at a permanent cease-fire to the 7-year-old civil war broke
down in June.
   The opposition newspaper La Prensa reported Tuesday that three
activists with the Confederation of Trade Union Unity were
assassinated Sunday by gunmen in military uniforms in Leon, 45
miles west of Managua.
   The pro-government newspaper El Nuevo Diario said three men,
including an army soldier, were arrested in connection with the
shootings.
