<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen     10-05 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Confident Although Campaign Downplaying Expectations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice presidential nominee Lloyd Bentsen is
sounding confident about his showdown tonight with Republican Dan
Quayle although the Democrat's staff is downplaying expectations by
expressing concern.
   ``Are you going to be standing behind me as we open the Quayle
season early tomorrow night?'' Bentsen asked a flag-waving crowd of
more than 500 who greeted him at the Omaha airport Tuesday night.
   The Texas senator hammered the Republicans on issues he's bound
to raise, given the chance, in the first nationally broadcast
debate between the two candidates.
   ``Tomorrow night we're going to have 90 minutes to present Mike
Dukakis' vision of America _ an America on the move, an America
that believes in excellence in education for all of our children,''
Bentsen said.
   It would be, he said, ``a Democratic administration that's
committed to protecting Social Security against the Republican
raids that have come year after year with Dan Quayle voting eight
times to cut Social Security.''
   He said the Democrats would pursue health insurance for the
uninsured while ``the opposition has done nothing.''
   ``Mike Dukakis is committed to an America that is number one in
the economy of the world and ... number one in national defense,''
he said, later citing the huge budget deficits of the Reagan years.
   One of Bentsen's goals will be to counter what he contends are
distortions of Dukakis' positions on defense and crime-fighting _
important issues in Texas and other Southern states where Bentsen
is working hardest for the ticket.
   Bentsen has led a nearly cloistered existence for four days,
taking part in issues briefings and conducting mock debates in
Washington, D.C., and later in Austin, Texas. But he set off for
Omaha with a flurry, speaking at a campaign rally at the Texas
state capitol and later at the Omaha airport.
   Campaign staff said Bentsen again would slip behind closed doors
today, except for a quick midday trip to examine the setup in the
auditorium and later the debate itself.
   Bentsen talked casually with reporters on his campaign plane en
route to Omaha, appearing relaxed and upbeat. But his staff
continued to try to blunt public expectations that the powerful
Bentsen would thrash the less experienced Quayle.
   Despite days of practice, aides said the 67-year-old Texas
senator was not adept at the media-age need to boil down his
statements into one- and two-minute sound bites.
   Press secretary Mike McCurry, who was Quayle's stand-in for
Bentsen in mock debates in Austin on Tuesday, said the Democratic
candidate was looking for ``the best way of making a point
memorable or punchy,'' and he was still having trouble with the
time limits.
   ``The red light goes off frequently,'' he said.
   ``It's all a matter of getting ready to present it (his
positions) in two-minute answers and one-minute rebuttals,'' said
Susan Estrich, Michael Dukakis' campaign manager who was helping
brief Bentsen. ``Our counsel to him has been to be himself.''
   Bentsen displayed no sign of being unsure of himself.
   ``Tomorrow is a big day for us, and a big day for this
campaign,'' Bentsen told the crowd of about 1,500 people at the
Austin rally. ``And I can't think of a greater way to start it than
surrounded by friends here on the capitol steps of Texas.''
   Bentsen said the Democrats offered ``proven and tested
leadership.''
   ``George Bush and Dan Quayle hear no questions and offer no
answers. They tell us to lower our sights, to live on our past,
rest on our laurels,'' while the Democrats would offer new
leadership, he said.
</TEXT>
