<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nielsens 1stLd-Writethru a0459 10-05 0714</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nielsens, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0459,0727</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Olympics Top Nielsens But Fall Well Below Estimate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `CBS has ...' to CORRECT that next winter
games are 1992, sted 1994.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC plans to do some research to find out why
its coverage of the Summer Olympics fell more than 3 rating points
short of the guarantee to advertisers _ a discrepancy that could
cost the network millions.
   Gerald Jaffe, NBC vice president for research projects, said the
network probably wouldn't make the results of the study public,
since it could bear on competition with the 1992 games.
   But among the likeliest contributors: the 14-hour time
difference between Seoul and New York that put live coverage of
such popular events as gymnastics in the morning, and the late
September-early-October timing.
   The games ended Sunday, and NBC's coverage had an average A.C.
Nielsen Co. rating of 17.9 _ not counting opening and closing
ceremonies _ considerably lower than the 21.2 rating NBC had
promised advertisers. The 1984 summer games from Los Angeles had
averaged a 23.2 for ABC.
   Each rating point represents 904,000 households with television.
   NBC will have to give advertisers as much as $70 million in
commercial time, to make up for what had been promised, according
to the Wall Street Journal.
   CBS has been awarded the TV contract for the next Winter
Olympics, which will be held in 1992, and expects to make a bid for
that year's summer games. The network also is studying NBC's
results.
   But CBS' vice President for marketing, David Poltrack, thinks
the 1988 Olympics suffered mainly from competition with other
sports and from time pressures on viewers, especially students back
in school.
   ``I attribute a lot of the under-delivery of ratings to the fall
scheduling. It's not necessarily typical of what we can expect in
future Olympics,'' said Poltrack. The 1992 games, in Barcelona,
Spain, will be earlier in the summer.
   Nonetheless, NBC's six nights of Olympics coverage last week
took six of the the top 10 spots in the Nielsen ratings and gave
NBC a decisive victory over ABC and CBS. NBC had an average 17.5
rating to ABC's 12.3 and CBS' 11.2. It also provided an important
promotional base for NBC's new fall shows.
   ``The actual performance by the Olympics in key groups (of
viewers) was a really dominant performance. Whether it was as
dominant as anticipated, that's something else,'' said Jaffe.
   The closing ceremonies Sunday fell to a 12.3 rating. NBC had
expected closer to 20.0. CBS' ``60 Minutes,'' ``Murder, She Wrote''
and the movie ``Cocoon'' out-rated the Sunday coverage, as did
``Liberace'' on ABC. Those four shows made up the rest of the top
10. The closing ceremonies ranked 22 out of 55 shows.
   During the games' first week, ratings tended to climb as the
week wore on. The second week, they tended to decline. Monday's
coverage was the highest-rated show of the week, with a 19.3 rating.
   ABC's ``World News Tonight'' won in the news Nielsens with a
10.0 rating. The ``CBS Evening News'' was second with a 9.8. ``NBC
Nightly News,'' pre-empted on the West Coast by Olympics coverage,
had a 9.6.
   The week's lowest-rated prime-time shows were: ``Live! Dick
Clark Presents,'' ``Wiseguy,'' ``Mutts,'' ``Beauty & the Beast,''
``Equalizer,'' ``Mr. Belvedere _ Sunday,'' ``Deal of the Century,''
``Frank's Place,'' ``First Impressions'' and a paid political
program by Lyndon LaRouche.
   CBS announced Tuesday that due to low ratings it had canceled
``Frank's Place,'' the critically acclaimed comedy starring Tim
Reid as the owner of a Creole restaurant in New Orleans.
   Also Tuesday, the union that represents NBC's technical workers
said the network has offered to buy out the jobs of 140 New
York-based engineers and technicians.
   ``If all 140 people accept, they will pay it, although they are
aiming to cut only 40 positions,'' said Paul McElroy, a spokesman
for Local 11 of the National Association of Broadcast Employees and
Technicians.
   NBC, like ABC and CBS, has dramatically reduced its payroll
since it was taken over, in its case by the General Electric Co.,
two years ago. About 400 people in the news division lost their
jobs and 110 others are scheduled to go before the end of the year.
</TEXT>
