<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 0230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Kenya-Church     10-05 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kenya-Church,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bishops Object To Politician's Threats To Religious Freedom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-ranking official of the ruling
party has threatened to strip an outspoken Anglican bishop of his
freedom to worship, but other clergmen have vowed to defy any
infringement on their religious rights.
   Moses Mudavadi, secretary-general of the Kenya African National
Union, threatened to strip Biship David Gitari of his freedom to
worship after the bishop criticized the way the ruling party
adopted resolutions.
   ``You should not be surprised if we, as a KANU government,
removed that freedom from you through Parliament,'' Mudavadi said
to Gitari in comments reported Saturday by Kenya's three
English-language newspapers.
   Anglican Archbishop Manasses Kuria, in a Sunday sermon to a
Nairobi parish, said the Church of the Province of Kenya would not
allow anyone to deny Christians the right to worship.
   ``The freedom of worship is God-given and cannot be taken away
at will by any individual,'' Kuria said.
   Anglican Bishop Alexander Muge, of the Rift Valley Eldoret
province, said Mudavadi's comments marked a ``sad moment for our
independent Kenya.
   ``Prison cells and enough graveyards must be prepared before the
decree is effected because many will continue to worship whether
Mr. Mudavadi likes it or not,'' Muge said.
   Muge and Kuria were quoted by the English-language Daily Nation
and The Standard. The Kenya Times, which is owned by the ruling
party, also reported Kuria's remarks.
   Gitari, bishop of Mount Kenya East diocese, angered politicians
by saying delegates to the party's conference rubber-stamped the
party's resolutions.
   The Kenya African National Union is Kenya's sole legal political
party.
   On Thursday, legislators lambasted Gitari, accusing him and
three other outspoken clergymen of trying to destabilize the
government.
   It was the second time in three months parliamentarians have
suspended legislative business to criticize clergy members, a sign
of increasing friction between the government of President Daniel
arap Moi and Anglican clergy, who have spoken out against alleged
government corruption and human rights abuses.
   Muge said he was briefly detained on July 17 and police kept
parishioners from entering his church after one run-in with the
government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
