<DOCNO> AP881005-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 0249EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HollywoodTeamsters Bjt   10-05 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hollywood Teamsters, Bjt,0666</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Threats Of Strike Violence Stop Production At Television Studio</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In two days of picketing, the Hollywood
Teamsters' strike has accomplished what scriptwriters failed to
achieve over five months in their walkout: the shutdown of a studio.
   Citing death threats, bomb scares and sabotaged equipment,
Cannell Studios said Tuesday it has halted production on its
television shows ``Hunter'' and ``Sonny Spoon.''
   It said the incidents were related to the strike by 3,200
drivers, laborers and electricians and that production would resume
work only when it is safe.
   In a separate incident, one picket was arrested for battery
Tuesday morning at Universal Studios, said police Lt. Ron Young.
The picket was released on $250 bail.
   A Cannell spokeswoman said production of the NBC-TV programs was
suspended because tires were slashed or deflated on nine vehicles,
a brake line was severed on a semi-trailer, holding tanks were
punctured on a mobile dressing room, a trailer hitch was sabotaged
and at least three employees were physically assaulted.
   Employees also received death threats and the company's Los
Angeles office received a bomb scare, said the spokeswoman, Lisa
Lewinson. The office building, containing several hundred
employees, was evacuated for more than two hours Monday, the first
day of the strike.
   Lewinson said the company was ``outraged by the acts of
violence, vandalism and threats to our employees and property.''
The studio planned to resume production ``as soon as possible with
or without an end to the strike.''
   A Teamster official denied that the union members had done
anything illegal.
   ``All of the members were advised that they were to conduct
themselves in a lawful manner,'' said Ed Prelock, director of legal
and contract affairs.
   ``We're going to do everything that's lawfully permissible and
nothing more,'' he said. ``Sure, there's liable to be emotions.
Hopefully, the reactions are simply that and nothing more. We are
not personally aware of any physical violence.''
   Teamsters pickets were stationed Tuesday at nearly every
Hollywood studio.
   The Teamsters drivers, who transport actors, equipment and props
for television and movie producers, picketed Monday at the Cannell
offices and the outdoor productions of ``Sonny Spoon'' at an
undisclosed location and of ``Hunter'' at the Santa Monica pier.
   At the ``Hunter'' filming, some pickets blew air horns and
banged on a trash container during scenes. Filming was delayed by
more than an hour and the production closed earlier than scheduled
Monday evening, Lewinson said.
   ``Hunter'' stars former pro football player Fred Dryer as a
quick-witted detective; ``Sonny Spoon,'' an NBC adventure program,
features Mario Van Peebles. The Cannell Studios are named after
producer-scriptwriter Stephen J. Cannell, who also created ``The
Rockford Files'' and ``The A-Team.''
   There have been other reported bomb threats related to the
strike, said police Sgt. Roger Jackson. At least one other studio
complained that some replacement drivers had been harassed by
pickets.
   ``These actions will not be tolerated,'' the Alliance of Motion
Picture and Television Producers said in a statement. The incidents
``are not only inappropriate, but perhaps illegal. ... We expect
and demand that no further incidents take place. And we call on the
Teamsters to take appropriate action to ensure that their strike be
conducted in a legal and nonviolent atmosphere.''
   The strike against the 217-member alliance began early Monday
after weekend negotiations collapsed. On Thursday, the Teamsters
voted 1,441-196 to reject the contract proposal submitted by the
alliance.
   Unresolved issues include overtime rules for weekend work,
salary rates, wages for out-of-town film and television production
and guidelines for the making of nonunion films. Some drivers are
being asked to take a pay cut from $16.61 to $14 per hour.
   Although the five-month strike by the 9,000-member Writers Guild
of America halted much of the industry's production, it never
caused any the alliance members to close their doors and halt
production.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881005-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 0251EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PMSTreatment     10-05 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PMS Treatment,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Antibiotic Appears To Help Some Women With Premenstrual Syndrome</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women suffering from premenstrual syndrome
should react cautiously to a new report suggesting that a common
antibiotic may help ease symptoms in some, says a National
Institute of Mental Health researcher.
   Dr. David Rubinow, a psychiatrist and clinical director at the
institute, said many treatments have been proposed for premenstrual
syndrome but none have been proven to work.
   ``I think the whole area of premenstrual syndrome has been
characterized by a new story and a new treatment every year for the
last 50 years,'' he said.
   He made the comment following an announcement Tuesday that the
antibiotic doxycycline could ease symptoms in women who had an
unrecognized underlying infection. The report by Dr. Atilla Toth, a
gynecologist at the New York Hospital-Cornell Medical Center in New
York, was published in The Journal of International Medical
Research.
   Rubinow said he was not familiar with Toth's study, but he had
some general comments about premenstrual syndrome, which is one of
his research interests.
   ``While I can't reject the results of this study out of hand
without having an opportunity to review the work, I would simply
urge considerable caution in the interpretation of this data, lest
people run out and demand the latest of a long series of treatments
that may not be effective, at best, and may be associated with
complications, at worst.''
   At a press conference, Toth said that 15 women who were given
the antibiotic and asked to rate their symptoms showed a ``highly
significant improvement in the symptom score at the end of the
month.'' Fifteen others given a placebo showed little change in
symptoms.
   Toth said an estimated 90 percent of women suffer from
premenstrual syndrome during their reproductive years, and about
one-fourth of those have symptoms severe enough to disrupt their
professional or personal lives. The symptoms can include weight
gain, breast tenderness, extreme irritability, fatigue and
sometimes suicidal tendencies, he said.
   He said he does not know how many of the women may have
infections and could therefore be helped by the antibiotic. ``I
don't think there's going to be one approach that's going to answer
the universe of patients that have this difficulty,'' he said.
   Doxycycline is a commonly used drug without severe side effects,
Rubinow said. The danger is that doctors who do not do a careful
evaluation of a patient may prescribe it and miss another
underlying psychiatric or medical condition that could be treated,
he said.
   Toth said seven of the women studied remained free of symptoms
as long as three years after taking doxycycline.
   His explanation is that low-grade infections in these women are
disrupting the lining of the uterus or the function of the ovaries,
producing hormonal irregularities that result in the symptoms of
premenstrual syndrome.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
