<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Politics     10-05 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Politics,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Leader Slams Labor's Swing To Center</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLACKPOOL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of Britain's transit
workers union warns that the Labor Party, by moving to the center
to broaden its appeal, could jeopardize its standing with its
strongest supporters.
   ``They want our money and our strength, but they fear our
power,'' Ron Todd, head of the 1.25 million-member Transport and
General Workers' Union, said Tuesday night during a meeting at the
party's annual conference.
   ``There is a real division in the party which needs to be
bridged as a matter of urgency,'' he said.
   Todd's broadside marked the first serious public clash at the
weeklong conference, which party leader Neil Kinnock regards as a
key step toward the adoption of a wholesale review of Labor
policies.
   Todd controls one-fifth of the voting strength of the
policy-making conference through a system under which the bosses of
the Trades Union Congress, the national labor federation, wield
huge blocks of votes allocated according to membership.
   The arrangement dates back to the turn of the century when the
unions founded the party.
   In the 1920s, Labor overtook the centrist Liberals to become,
along with the currently governing Conservatives, one of Britain's
two major parties.
   The first post-World War II Labor government founded the welfare
state and set up the free National Health Service.
   Earlier in the conference, which ends Friday, Todd and other top
union chiefs used their block votes to ensure Kinnock a huge
victory in a leadership challenge by the leader of Labor's left,
Tony Benn.
   The union leaders also endorsed broadly the first phase of a
two-stage policy review which acknowledges a permanent role for
capitalism and drops previous commitments to wholesale
renationalization of state-owned industries sold by Conservative
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   The unions are themselves divided between moderates and leftists
such as Todd.
   But their near-unanimous stance in Blackpool reflected a tacit
acceptance of Kinnock's argument that the party must modify its
image as the only hope of regaining power after three election
defeats by Mrs. Thatcher.
   Polls show that the clout of the unions, which fund the party
and provided more than $3.3 million for the general election
campaign in 1987, is itself a vote loser for Labor.
   Kinnock's aides said privately they were annoyed by Todd's
outburst soon after the leadership election ballot and the vote on
the policy review.
   The speech partly overshadowed Kinnock's keynote address Tuesday
in which he said Labor must adopt new economic policies. He
rejected charges that he was selling out Socialism.
   ``There is no concession to Thatcherism as great as letting it
win again,'' said Kinnock.
   Todd also is opposed to dropping Labor's electorally unpopular
commitment to scrap Britain's nuclear weapons unilaterally.
   The second- and third-biggest unions, engineers and municipal
workers, are led by moderates who now suggest a reduction in union
voting power in favor of legislators and local party branches at
Labor conferences.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881005-0062 </DOCNO>
