<HEAD>Michigan Girl To Meet Pen Pal Noriega</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 10-year-old Michigan girl has been
invited to spend a week in Panama as a guest of Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega after the two became pen pals, a military official said.
   Sarah York of Negaunee, a town of 5,000 people in northern
Michigan, and her mother, Pauline York, were to begin their visit
today, said Defense Forces spokesman Maj. Edgardo Lopez Grimaldo.
   ``The girl has risen above the behavior of the adults that
actually direct U.S. politics,'' he said.
   Noriega, Panama's de facto ruler and head of the Defense Forces,
is under indictment in the United States on drug trafficking
charges. He has withstood U.S. economic sanctions against Panama
and diplomatic pressure to force him to resign.
   Lopez Grimaldo said the girl first wrote Noriega on March 3
after she saw him interviewed on television.
   ``I would like to see you in civilian clothes, without the
uniform,'' wrote the girl, who asked Noriega to recommend
literature about Central American politics and history.
   The youngster and the general have corresponded regularly and
exchanged gifts ever since, said Lopez Grimaldo, who made several
letters available to The Associated Press.
   He said the girl will attend the country's Second Agriculture
and Military Fair that begins today and meet with acting President
Manuel Solis Palma.
   The girl and Mrs. York plan to return to Michigan on Oct. 11, he
said.
   ``It is significant that this child has built a type of
spiritual relationship with a man who has been harrassed, badly
treated, persecuted and reviled by the adult politicians of her
country,'' Lopez Grimaldo said.
</TEXT>
