<1ST_LINE>d a PM-PublicationHalted     10-05 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Publication Halted,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Government Shuts Down Campus Paper After Satire Published</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Editors at the California State
University campus here are wrangling with the student government
over censorship after the student politicians shut down the
newspaper over a satiric edition.
   The California State University, Long Beach Associated Students
Senate withdrew funding for The Union last week because of the
newspaper's satire supplement, ``The Grunion,'' which took as its
theme the ``Sexually Frustrated Male.''
   The issue featured phallic illustrations and a photograph of
three nearly nude cavorters.
   Union editor Gary Stark, who is appealing the decision to the
student judiciary, charged the Senate violated its own policies in
its Sept. 28 decision.
   ``Our bylaws specifically state that staffing and editorial
content shall not be subject to the review or approval of the A.S.
Senate,'' Stark said.
   Student body president Roger Thompson said there is no First
Amendment violation because the paper can continue without student
funding.
   ``The $10,000 we give the Union comes from student fees. I have
to ask myself, how appropriate is it to spend $10,000 on this?''
Thompson said.
   Journalism professor Ben Cunningham said there is friction
whenever campus papers are funded by student fees.
   ``It's an unholy alliance that invites this kind of thing to
occur,'' said Cunningham, adding that the editor exercised poor
judgment and the student government overreacted.
   ``If the politicians didn't want to pay for a student newspaper,
this wasn't the time to make the decision. What they did was to
make it very clearly a First Amendment issue,'' Cunningham said.
   The school's administration has remained neutral.
</TEXT>
