<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $115 million bid by Toronto businessman
Stephen R. Mernick for the PTL ministry was accepted Tuesday by the
ministry's bankruptcy trustee. Other parties who sought to buy the
ministry included:
   _PTL founder and deposed leader Jim Bakker. Bakker claimed
throughout the summer he had a $100 million line of credit, and
later presented a $172 million bid. Though he appeared to be the
leading contender for a time, Bakker failed to meet several
deadlines for producing a $3 million down payment.
   _Charlotte, N.C., businessman George Shinn. Shinn, owner of the
newly formed Charlotte Hornets of the National Basketball
Association and the Charlotte Knights Double A baseball team,
originally hoped to use part of the land to build a stadium for his
teams. Shinn never announced the amount of his bid, but published
reports put it around $75 million. He eventually entered a deal to
build a stadium a few miles from PTL.
   _Australian businessman Gavin Morehu. Morehu, described as a
millionaire Christian involved in the import-export business,
initially tendered a $200 million offer, but failed to come up with
$50 million in earnest money.
   _Canadian real estate tycoon Peter Thomas. Thomas, a native of
Vancouver, British Columbia, is a major stockholder in Century 21,
the real estate franchiser, and president of Samoth Capital Corp.
He offered $113 million for the ministry. He withdrew his bid as
Bakker seemed close to success, but re-entered later, and said
Tuesday he was disappointed with the outcome, which still must be
approved by a U.S. Bankruptcy Court judge. Thomas said he would
keep Heritage USA as a religious retreat.
