<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     10-05 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched up against the Japanese yen
today, while share prices fell moderately on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average again lost 95.53 points, or
0.35 percent, following Tuesday's 44.51-point drop. The index
gained 72.25 points in the early morning, reaching 27,573.27, but
headed down and closed at 27,501.02 points.
   Since Oct. 1, the index has lost 518.18 points even though the
second half of the fiscal year has begun, when market trading
should be active, dealers said.
   ``There is no negative factor in the economy that should lead
the market to keep losing,'' said Yoshio Shimoyama with the Nikko
Securities. He said increased selling for profit-taking resulted in
the Nikkei's decline today.
   ``Also, there was some cautiousness among investors before the
(announcement of the) U.S. umemployment rate'' for September,
scheduled for Friday, he said.
   But Shimoyama implied the major market-affecting factor was
participants' uncertainty about ailing Emperor Hirohito, whose
condition was reported stable but serious. The 87-year-old Hirohito
has been bedridden and continues to hemorrhage since he vomited
blood Sept. 19.
   Volume traded on the first section of the exchange was estimated
at 1 billion shares.
   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at 133.48 yen,
up 0.33 yen from Tuesday's close of 133.15 yen. Opening slightly
lower at 133.40 yen, the currency ranged within a tight range of
133.40-133.57 yen.
   ``The dollar-yen rate was moving very little,'' said a dealer
with the Bank of Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``Participants remained on the sidelines as the release of the
U.S. unemployment figure approaches, and were just adjusting the
amount of currencies they've had,'' he said.
</TEXT>
