<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Afghanistan     10-05 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Afghanistan,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Guerrillas Fire On Kabul</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan guerrillas fired rockets into Kabul today
during morning rush hour, killing 11 people and injuring 26 others
in the capital city, the Tass news agency reported.
   Also today, the Communist Party newspaper Pravda reiterated
Soviet complaints that Pakistan is to blame for violations of the
U.N. accord providing for the withdrawal of Soviet troops from
Afghanistan.
   ``All indications are that in Islamabad, they have a very flawed
idea of international law, state-to-state relations and
treaty-based commitments,'' the newspaper said.
   The Soviet Union said last week it had halted the withdrawal of
its troops from Afghanistan, citing violations of the accord.
   Pravda said the Afghan government has registered more than 1,500
violations of the accord with U.N. monitors.
   Tass said 23 rockets were fired from positions northwest of
Kabul during morning rush hour. It said 11 people died and 26
others were wounded.
   Under the accord signed April 14, the Soviet Union agreed to
withdraw its 100,000 soldiers from Afghanistan in exchange for a
pledge of non-interference by Pakistan and other countries that
have been aiding the guerrillas. The guerrillas are not party to
the agreement.
   Half of the Soviet force in Afghanistan was withdrawn between
May 15 and Aug. 15, and the Soviet Union has until Feb. 15 to
complete the pullout.
   But the Soviet Union charges Pakistan has not moved to shut down
guerrilla camps on its territory and still serves as a conduit for
U.S.-supplied arms.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979, replaced one
pro-Soviet government with another and remained to fight the
anti-Marxist insurgents. More than 13,000 Soviet soldiers have been
killed in that time and 35,000 wounded.
</TEXT>
