<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Spain-Shooting     10-05 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spain-Shooting,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leftist Terror Group Grapo Says It Killed Madrid Policeman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tiny leftist terror group GRAPO has
claimed responsibility for slaying a national police officer, a
radio network reported today.
   The private network SER said it received an anonymous telephone
call Tuesday night in which a man claimed the killing on behalf of
the extreme-left terror group, the 1st of October Anti-fascist
Resistance Group, known by its Spanish acronym GRAPO.
   Two men and a woman took part in the killing early Tuesday in
which one man shot to death a 47-year-old policeman who had been on
duty at an identity card office, police said.
   The man also slightly injured another police officer and a man
and a woman during the shooting, police said.
   Police said GRAPO was particularly active in Spain in 1976-77
when they claimed the killings of 12 policeman and more than 30
terrorist attacks including bombings, shootings and kidnappings.
   Most GRAPO members were jailed in the late 1970s and early
1980s, police said.
   Interior Minister Jose Luis Corcuera told reporters Tuesday that
the GRAPO unit that killed the policeman was made up of two men and
two women.
   Eyewitnesses positively identified three of them in police
pictures as Laureano Ortega Ortega, Encarnacion Leon Lara and Maria
Jesus Romero.
   The second man has not been identified by police, he said.
   Police have sought Ortega and the two women since they were
identified as having been involved in the May 27 shooting death of
a businessman in the northwestern port city of La Coruna.
   The GRAPO group claimed responsibility for that shooting a few
days later in a letter to a newspaper in the southeastern city of
Valencia, police said.
   The three are also wanted for other attacks.
   Corcuera said the four-person GRAPO unit was the sole remaining
active component of the group.
</TEXT>
