<1ST_LINE>u i PM-TextileBill-Asia     10-05 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Textile Bill-Asia,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Asians Welcome Failure of Textile Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Textile Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials in several Asian countries breathed a
sigh of relief today after the U.S. House failed to override a veto
of limits on textile imports, but they fretted over U.S.
protectionist sentiment that gave rise to the bill.
   ``The textile bill is dead,'' trumpeted Hong Kong's director of
trade, Michael Sze.
   But, he added, ``the textile lobby is not going to give up. It
will be looking for ways to make protection for the textiles
industry more palatable to U.S. legislators. This could seriously
threaten Hong Kong's trading interests.''
   In the latest statistics available in Hong Kong, the British
colony exported $3.4 billion worth of clothing and accessories and
$116 million worth of textile fabrics to the United States in 1986.
   The House voted 272-152 in favor of overriding President
Reagan's veto of the bill. The tally fell 11 votes short of the
two-thirds majority needed to override the veto and impose the
restrictions.
   The bill would have frozen 1988 textile and apparel imports at
last year's level and limited growth to 1 percent annually
beginning in 1989. It also would have capped imports of non-rubber
footwear with no provision for future increases.
   Asian countries that sell billions of dollars worth of textiles
and clothing to the United States had expressed alarm as the bill
moved through Congress, criticizing it as protectionist and
unwarranted.
   ``Our concern has been resolved as the effort by the House to
override the presidential veto has failed,'' Mitsuaki Hayashi, a
spokesman for Japan's Ministry of International Trade and Industry,
said today.
   Japan exported $118 million worth of textiles to the United
States in 1987, and the ministry had said earlier the U.S.
legislation violated international trade agreements and would hurt
future accords.
   The Foreign Ministry also said it welcomed the
``anti-protectionist efforts made by President Reagan and his
administration.'' But a ministry statement also noted that nearly
two-thirds of the House had voted for a bill that ``contains very
restrictive and discriminatory articles that are not compatible
with free trade.''
   In Thailand, the Foreign Ministry's deputy spokesman,
Prachyadavi Tavedikul, said both Americans and Thais would benefit
from the upheld veto.
   ``We favor free trade. Our people and Americans will gain from
lower textile prices,'' Tavedikul said.
</TEXT>
