<HEAD>Government Looking at Solidarity Spokesman's U.S. Testimony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor will look at statements made
by Solidarity national spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz at a U.S.
congressional hearing last month to see if any Polish law was
violated, the government has said.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said Tuesday that is was
``peculiar'' for a Polish citizen to appear before a foreign
government and give testimony about affairs in Poland, but he did
not know if any laws were violated.
   The Foreign Ministry planned to establish the facts of the
testimony and a prosecutor will examine the statements for possible
legal violations, Urban said at his weekly news conference.
   Onyszkiewicz, a mathematics instructor at Warsaw University who
has been Solidarity's spokesman since 1981, returned to Poland on
Sunday after a trip to the United States. He was received there by
President Reagan and appeared before a congressional hearing on
Sept. 23.
   During the U.S. visit, Onyszkiewicz urged continued American
pressure on Poland to bring about legal recognition of Solidarity,
the East bloc's first independent trade unon which was banned in
1981 after the imposition of martial law.
   Onyszkiewicz and Jan Nowak, director of the Polish-American
Congress, an organization of Americans of Polish descent, testified
before a congressional committee about human rights in Poland and
treatment of Poles elsewhere, including the Soviet Union.
   The appearance before Congress by Onyszkiewicz was the subject
of criticism in the government-controlled press, which said he was
appearing as a employee reporting to his employer.
   Polish officials frequently criticize U.S. support of Solidarity
over the past several years, saying it makes the banned union an
agent of a foreign power.
