<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Gold Stable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against major foreign currencies
in quiet European trading today. Gold prices barely moved.
   Dealers said the dollar is in a moderate upward trend while the
market waits for Friday's scheduled release of American
unemployment figures for September.
   They said the figures will have no major impact on the dollar if
they show, as expected, a slight decline from August's unemployment
rate of 5.6 percent.
   ``There is no news to trade on,'' said one Frankfurt dealer.
``The market seems to be finished for the year.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.33 yen to a closing 133.48. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 133.65 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday,
were:
   _1.8655 West German marks, up from $1.8610
   _1.5840 Swiss francs, up from $1.5775
   _6.3540 French francs, up from $6.3285
   _2.1027 Dutch guilders, up from $2.0950
   _1,390.50 Italian lire, up from $1,385.875
   _1.2080 Canadian dollars, down from $1.20965
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6925, slightly cheaper for
buyers than late Tuesday's $1.6945.
   Currency dealers predicted the pound would soften because of
nervousness following the government's decision Tuesday to order
the Kuwait Investment Office to reduce its stake in British
Petroleum Co. PLC.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $397.50 a troy ounce, up
from the $397.45 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $397.25.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $396.90, unchanged from late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.77 a troy ounce to close at
a bid $400.46.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.22 a troy
ounce, down marginally from Tuesday's $6.23.
</TEXT>
