<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Yugoslavia-Suvar     10-05 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia-Suvar,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Leader Announces Leadership Shakeup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party chief Stipe Suvar
has announced a plan to overhaul the party leadership, perhaps
replacing up to one-third of the 165-member Central Committee.
   Suvar said on Sarajevo television Tuesday night that the ruling
Presidium would propose the changes to the Central Committee, which
is to hold a crucial session on Oct. 17.
   ``Very soon new people will be brought into the Central
Committee of the League of Communists and its presidium,'' Suvar
said, according to a dispatch from the official Tanjug news agency.
   He said at the forthcoming meeting the party Presidium ``will
strive ... to determine the criteria of possible responsibility of
its members'' for Yugoslavia's economic and political crisis.
   ``If it fails in this, the Central Committee will assume this
role and anyone who does not win two-thirds of votes of the
membership of the Central Committee will leave this body,'' the
party chief declared.
   He added 43 members of the Central Committee and the presidium
so far have been charged with lack of responsibility.
   The replacement of one-third of the Central Committee is the
maximum permitted by the party statute, except at a party congress.
The party presidium has 23 members.
   Suvar announced that a similar overhaul was expected in the
party leaderships of Yugoslavia's six republics and two autonomous
provinces.
   There have been increasing calls for top-level personnel changes
in the party leadership. Leaders have been blamed for failing to
stop ethnic tensions between ethnic Albanians and Slavs in the
restive Kosovo province and the deteriotating economic and
political situation.
   Yugoslavia is burdened with a 217 percent annual inflation, a 15
percent unemployment rate and a $21 billion foreign debt.
   On Tuesday, about 5,000 workers from the Rakovica industrial
suburb of Belgrade marched on Parliament, protesting low wages and
sagging living standards. Several hundred women did the same this
morning, protesting low standards of living.
</TEXT>
