<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 0707EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-FloridaRunoff     10-05 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Florida Runoff,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Rep. MacKay Wins Democratic Race To Oppose Mack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Kenneth ``Buddy'' MacKay said after
winning the Democratic Senate runoff that he would try to heal
wounds from the divisive race while looking ahead to a ``mainstream
versus extreme'' contest with Republican Connie Mack.
   MacKay said he would meet in Tallahassee today with state
Insurance Commissioner Bill Gunter, the defeated Democratic
candidate who pledged to support MacKay less than a week after
accusing the third-term congressman of running the nastiest
campaign in Florida history.
   Unofficial returns from Tuesday's runoff gave MacKay 362,234, or
52 percent of the vote, to Gunter's 330,297, or 48 percent.
   Mack, a former Cape Coral bank president and grandson of the
baseball Hall of Fame manager, is a well-funded conservative whose
candidacy is drawing national Republican help. Mack and MacKay will
face each other on the November ballot for the seat held by
Democratic Sen. Lawton Chiles, who is retiring after three terms.
   ``We are the candidacy that can beat Connie Mack,'' MacKay said
Tuesday night. ``I see this election as mainstream versus extreme.''
   Mack agreed that voters faced an ideological decision.
   ``I think the voters in Florida are going to have a very clear
choice between the liberal Buddy MacKay and the conservative Connie
Mack,'' he said.
   The Senate runoff climaxed twisting events that began last
December, when Chiles, 58, announced he wouldn't seek re-election,
saying he was burned out by the Senate and didn't like the high
cost of running for re-election.
   Popular former two-term Gov. Reubin Askew then entered the race
against Mack. But Askew, well ahead in all polls, withdrew May 7,
saying he didn't like all the time spent raising funds.
   Gunter and MacKay jumped in after Askew pulled out, and they ran
one-two in the Sept. 6 primary. But neither received a majority,
making a runoff necessary.
   MacKay, a lawyer from a wealthy landowning family, was endorsed
by Askew, 1986 Democratic gubernatorial nominee Steve Pajcic,
third-place primary finisher Rep. Dan Mica and fourth-place
finisher state Sen. Patricia Frank.
   The runoff campaign was filled with negative advertising and
sharp exchanges in debates, and Democratic officials worried that
Mack would face a crippled opponent in the general election.
   MacKay, 55, attacked Gunter's integrity for his practice each
election of using campaign contributions from the insurance
industry he regulates, including from two companies that later
collapsed in corruption. He also charged that Gunter voted against
desegregation 15 years ago.
   Gunter, 54, charged that MacKay's congressional record betrayed
Israel, Social Security and anti-drug efforts, and he claimed
MacKay was being supported by corrupt defense contractors.
   MacKay warned that the well-funded Mack could exploit Gunter's
alleged ethics problems. Mack, meanwhile, went on the attack
against MacKay, running television and newspaper ads charging:
``Hey Buddy, You're liberal!''
   Gunter lost a 1974 Democratic Senate runoff and won a 1980
Senate runoff only to lose in the general election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881005-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 0718EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Fiji     10-05 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fiji,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coup Leader Given Promotion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUVA, Fiji (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of two military coups last year was
given a promotion in the army today as this South Pacific nation
approached its first anniversary as a republic.
   Sitiveni Rabuka was third in the army hierachy and a lieutenant
colonel when he staged his first coup May 14, 1987. He mounted a
second takeover four months later and then elevated himself to the
rank of brigadier-general.
   Friday marks the first anniversary of his declaration that Fiji,
a former British colony and once a staunch member of the
Commonwealth, had severed its ties with Britain to become a
republic.
   To mark the event, President Ratu Sir Penaia Ganilau announced
today that Rabuka now holds the rank of major-general. Ganilau was
the country's former governor-general, and as such official
representative of Britain's Queen Elizabeth 11.
   There was no immediate explanation for the promotion. Ganilau
had opposed Rabuka's aim to change the constitution to give
preference to ethnic Melanesian Fijians in a future parliament over
the Indian community, which has a majority in the 715,000
population.
   Indigenous Fijians account for 47 percent while Indians,
descendants of indentured sugar plantation laborers, comprise 49
percent. Rabuka staged the coups following weeks of civil unrest
against Indian businesses that is widely believed to have been
instigated by an extremist Fijian group.
   Rabuka remains chief of the army and head of the home affairs
ministry, a powerful position because it puts him in charge of
security.
   Rabuka, 40, staged his first coup and overthrew the
multi-racial, Indian-domination government of Timoci Bavadra, just
one month after Bavadra was elected in free elections.
   Four months later, Rabuka carried out a second coup against an
interim government. Rabuka since has handed power to a nominally
civilian government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
