<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Ballard     10-05 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Ballard,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cinematographer Lucien Ballard Dies At 84</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANCHO MIRAGE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cinematographer Lucien Ballard,
whose high-contrast imagery brought a sharp edge to such films as
``True Grit'' and ``The Wild Bunch,'' died of injuries from a
traffic accident. He was 84.
   Ballard died Saturday at Eisenhower Medical Center, two days
after he collided with a tractor while riding his bicycle near his
home, his son, Tony Ballard, said Tuesday.
   The Oklahoma native, whose career spanned nearly 50 years, shot
more than 100 films, ranging from such serious efforts as ``The
Caretakers'' for which he was nominated for an Academy Award, to
two-reel comedies starring The Three Stooges.
   One of Hollywood's most distinguished cameramen, he worked with
such directors as Sam Peckinpah, Stanley Kubrick, Henry Hathaway,
Dorothy Arzner and Josef von Sternberg.
   But despite an illustrious career, Ballard never received the
industry's top honor, the Academy Award. Although nominated for
``The Caretakers'' in 1963, he lost to James Wong Howe for ``Hud.''
   Two of his most renowned Westerns, Peckinpah's ``The Wild
Bunch,'' and Hathaway's ``True Grit,'' were both filmed in 1969.
Some in Hollywood believed they may have canceled each other out in
the Oscar race for best cinematography that year. ``True Grit''
garnered a best actor Oscar for John Wayne.
   Ballard was planning to go into the lumber business when he
discovered moviemaking after a script girl he was dating took him
to a three-day party whose host was actress Clara Bow.
   Soon thereafter he visited Paramount studios, landing a job as a
film cutter.
   He gained von Sternberg's attention while working as an
assistant camera operator, and the director used him on his 1930
film ``Morocco,'' starring Marlene Dietrich. Ballard also worked
with von Sternberg on ``The Devil Is a Woman'' and ``Crime and
Punishment.''
   Ballard married actress Merle Oberon in 1945, but the couple
divorced four years later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
