<HEAD>Search Still On For Suspect in School Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MASCOTTE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police were searching for a young drifter
believed to be the gunman who shot into an elementary school
playground and wounded a third-grade student before disappearing
into the woods.
   ``We know who the suspect is, but we don't know the motive,''
Lake County Sheriff Noel Griffin Jr. said Tuesday as officers
chopped weeds and cleared brush near Mascotte Elementary in their
search for the rifle used in the shooting of 9-year-old Leah
Wilibanks.
   The bearded man who fired on the approximately 25 children in
the schoolyard Monday wore military-style camouflage clothes and a
punk haircut, shaved on the sides and sticking straight up in the
center, investigators said.
   Griffin wouldn't say how the gunman was identified but did say
he was not a local resident.
   The child was listed in serious condition at Orlando Regional
Medical Center, said spokesman Joe Brown. She was hit by a single
bullet that passed through the upper right arm and chest, officials
said.
   Her grandmother, Dolly Chapman, said the girl asked late Monday:
``Why would somebody shoot me?''
   Mascotte Police Chief Don Page said, ``We don't exactly know the
motive of why anybody would shoot a young child like that.''
   Deputies were stationed at all elementary and grade schools in
this community of 1,600.
   Although scores of officers and residents had joined in the
search Monday, only a few officers were left searching for the
suspect by late Tuesday.
   The sheriff discouraged civilians from trying to take the law
into their own hands.
   ``They should watch their kids ... and leave it to us,'' he said.
   Children in Mascotte and the surrounding towns of Groveland,
Minneola and Clermont would not be allowed on playgrounds for a few
days, said Lake County School Superintendent Freddie Garner.
   Police were on hand to stand guard when the elementary school
reopened Tuesday, and counselors were brought in to talk to the
children. Doors to all schools in the district were locked, and all
principals were instructed to take extra precautions.
   Mascotte Elementary reported more than 150 children absent
Tuesday, out of an enrollment of about 415. Normal absenteeism is
about 20.
</TEXT>
