<HEAD>Helicopter Crashes En Route to Flood Site, Two Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NIMES, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A helicopter taking experts to check flood
damage in this city crashed, killing the pilot and a passenger,
authorities said today. The accident raised the flood's death toll
to 10.
   Officials had said Tuesday that 11 people drowned in the flood
the day before. But they revised that figure downward to eight
before the latest deaths raised the toll today to 10.
   False assumptions and communications problems caused the
mistake, said Bernard Lesterlin, deputy prefect in the region.
   Torrential rains sent a sudden five-foot-deep surge of water and
mud through the streets of this city of 130,000 people about 440
miles south of Paris.
   President Francois Mitterrand toured the devastated streets
Tuesday. About 100 of an estimated 50,000 people with damaged homes
chanted ``compensation, compensation,'' and Mitterrand said the
government would try to meet their needs.
   The French army sent more than 5,000 soldiers to help with
relief and supply work.
