<2ND_LINE>PM-Hirohito, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0509-a0511,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor Gets Two More Blood Transfusions; Fever Worsens</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with second transfusion, fever
rising; edits to trim. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MONIKA JAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito received two more blood
transfusions today, and doctors kept a close watch on the
87-year-old monarch as his fever worsened, palace officials said.
   Hirohito vomited blood Sept. 19 and has continued to discharge a
small amount of blood intermittently. He has received transfusions
totaling 11{ pints of blood.
   Kenji Maeda, head of general affairs at the Imperial Household
Agency, said doctors gave the emperor 0.23 pints of blood after a
transfusion of 0.4 pints earlier today. Maeda said doctors gave him
a smaller amount the second time because too much blood might
strain his heart.
   Hirohito's temperature continued to climb steadily in the
evening and reached 100.94 degrees. His normal temperature is about
95.9. His pulse was 104, up from 81 in the morning.
   The emperor has not been able to consume any solid food except a
few spoonfuls of porridge since falling sick. He is being fed
intravenously.
   Besides whole blood, palace physicians this week began
administering platelets to the emperor. They also sought to
increase intravenous nutrients, including glucose and protein, news
reports said.
   Crown Prince Akihito, Crown Princess Michiko and their two sons,
Prince Hiro and Prince Aya, were among the first family members to
visit Hirohito at his bedside today.
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita visited Akihito at his Togu
Palace.
   Nearly 4 million people have signed registries around the
country to wish Hirohito a quick recovery. Fall festivals and other
celebrations have been canceled.
</TEXT>
