<1ST_LINE>u i PM-HamadiTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0532 10-05 0668</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hamadi Trial, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0532,0688</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stethem Wanted Comrades Spared, Witness Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with Stethem reportedly saying
he wanted to be killed instead of other divers; edits to trim. Pick
up 16th pvs, `In testimony...' Minor editing thereafter.
^By GEORGE BOEHMER</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Navy diver beaten and
slain aboard a hijacked TWA jetliner said he hoped the hijackers
would kill him instead of his married Navy comrades, a witness
testified today.
   Diver Robert Stethem made the remark after two Shiite Moslem air
pirates beat him so savagely he was in shock, said Rosemarie Anne
Henderson, a passenger aboard Flight 847.
   ``The young man (Stethem) was crying. He was unable to walk by
himself,'' said Mrs. Henderson, an Australian who was traveling
with her husband and daughter.
   She said Mohammed Ali Hamadi led Stethem down the airplane's
aisle, told her husband to get out of his seat and put Stethem next
to her.
   Hamadi is on trial on charges of murder and air piracy in the
June 1985 hijacking of the Athens-to-Rome flight in which Stethem
was killed and 39 Americans were held captive for 17 days.
   Mrs. Henderson, 52, said she later switched seats with her
daughter and that her daughter talked to Stethem at length.
   ``He said to her that if anyone would have to be killed, he
hoped it would be him, because the others (the five fellow divers)
were all married,'' Mrs. Henderson said, her voice breaking with
emotion.
   ``He was in shock. He also had a bandage around his neck. It had
blood on it,'' Mrs. Henderson said.
   ``He said he thought his knee was broken. He told her he had
been tied up and that when they finished beating him he was hit
over the head with the pistol.''
   ``He was shaking,'' Mrs. Henderson said. ``He said some of his
ribs were broken.''
   Motioning with her hands, Mrs. Henderson said Stethem kept
rubbing an injured hand.
   ``He said he had no feeling (in it),'' Mrs. Henderson said.
   After the plane landed in Beirut, Stethem, 23, of Waldorf, Md.,
was shot and pushed out of the plane. He died on the airport tarmac.
   In testimony Tuesday, an American held during the hijacking
testified that Hamadi appeared proud of Stethem's slaying.
   ``He looked like the fox that got the chicken. He showed
absolutely no remorse,'' said Stuart Dahl, a 34-year-old U.S. Navy
diver.
   Dahl also said he believed Hamadi was the hijacker who shot
Stethem.
   Shaking his finger and pointing directly at Hamadi, he said: ``I
know he was the one that hit me on the back of the head. Although I
did not see him ... I would say he was the one who did it (shot
Stethem).''
   Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt Airport in January 1987 after
customs officials found liquid explosives in his luggage. His trial
began July 5 and is expected to last until December.
   Dahl, Stethem's Navy supervisor, said that ``immediately, not
more than a minute after the shooting,'' Hamadi came to where he
was sitting in the airplane and hit him on the back of the head
with the butt of the gun.
   ``He was very proud of his power; he was very proud of what he
had done,'' said Dahl.
   Witnesses have given conflicting testimony about who fired the
shot that killed Stethem.
   Dahl's testimony echoed that of pilot John Testrake, who said he
believed Hamadi was the gunman. Other witnesses said they thought
another hijacker shot him.
   Hamadi has admitted being one of the hijackers but has denied
killing Stethem.
   A third diver, 30-year-old Tony Daniel Watson, testified Tuesday
that Hamadi shoved a cocked pistol at his face and seemed ready to
shoot before a flight attendant begged him to stop.
   ``He had a chrome-plated automatic pistol in his hand. He
pointed it directly in my face and pulled back the hammer.''
   ``I was very afraid I would be shot,'' Watson said.

</TEXT>
