<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HarveyTrial     10-05 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Harvey Trial,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Faces Trial in February Takeover of Tuscaloosa School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who faces 110 counts of kidnapping
in the 12-hour takeover of a private school last February was
granted the right to defend himself after promising the judge he
wouldn't disrupt his trial.
   James L. Harvey made the promise to Circuit Judge John M. Karrh
at a pre-trial hearing Monday. Jury selection was to begin this
afternoon.
   Karrh, in granting Harvey's request to represent himself, warned
that the defendant would be taken from the courtroom if he shows
any ``disruptive or obstreperous behavior.''
   The judge also told Harvey he would not allow any statements not
related to the kidnapping charges.
   ``You won't have any problem out of me, I promise you that,''
said Harvey, 43, of Tuscaloosa.
   Harvey is accused in connection with the Feb. 2 takeover of West
End Christian School in Tuscaloosa. Armed with two pistols and a
rifle and wearing ski masks, Harvey and another man entered the
school and held 110 students and teachers hostage, saying he was
trying to draw attention to the nation's homeless and hungry.
   No one was injured in the incident, which ended 12 hours later
with Harvey's surrender on viewing a bogus pardon videotaped by
Gov. Guy Hunt. Charges were later dropped against the other man,
who police said was forced to participate in the takeover.
   The governor is one of 137 witnesses Harvey has subpoenaed.
Hunt's assistant press secretary, Stacy Rimer, said he would
testify.
   Harvey has been held in lieu of $8.4 million bond since Feb. 2.
If convicted, he could be sentenced to more than 10,000 years in
prison.
   ``I would never do anything to hurt anybody,'' Harvey told the
Tuscaloosa News in a telephone call from the county jail Monday.
``It is not inside of me.''
   He said any of his student hostages could have left ``any time
they wanted to walk out.''
   ``All I wanted to do,'' Harvey said, ``was help the many
oppressed people in pain and suffering in bondage and the many
starving people in my country. I do again beg forgiveness from
these children, teachers, parents and every citizen.''
   Because of publicity in Tuscaloosa, Karrh moved the trial to
Huntsville, about 160 miles away.
</TEXT>
