<1ST_LINE>u w PM-CounterterrorismFinding 3rdLd-Writethru a0550 10-05
0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Counterterrorism Finding, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0550,400</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Stethem, last graf. Disregard a0550,
which did not correct spelling error.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Reagan Authorized Free Hand for CIA on Counterterrorism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan signed intelligence
authorizations in 1984 and 1985 giving CIA agents broad
anti-terrorism powers that some administration officials saw as ``a
license to kill,'' according to a published report.
   The authorizations ``deemed'' as lawful any covert actions _
including potentially violent ones _ taken in ``good faith'' by
U.S. intelligence agents against terrorists, according to a report
in today's editions of The Washington Post.
   The language of the findings seemingly was ambiguous, the Post
said. Actions taken in good faith and as part of an approved
operation would be deemed lawful in advance, but also they ``must
be'' lawful, sources told the Post.
   The newspaper quoted a former White House official, whom it did
not identify, as saying the Reagan orders were a ``go-anywhere,
do-anything'' authority.
   The language of the findings caused disputes among
administration officials, the Post said, because actions that could
be authorized under the findings might conflict with earlier
presidential executive orders banning any direct or indirect
involvement of U.S. intelligence agents in assassinations.
   The Post quoted a source as saying the language was specifically
designed to ``circumvent the assassination ban'' and protect CIA
agents who might take part in foreign strike teams.
   White House spokesman Bob Hall told The Associated Press he knew
nothing about the findings late Tuesday night.
   The Post reported that unidentified White House officials said
Vice President George Bush would have been given a copy of or would
have had access to the findings.
   A Bush spokesman and Bush campaign chairman James Baker III, who
was White House chief of staff at the time Reagan signed the 1984
finding, had no comment, the Post said.
   Reagan signed the first finding on Nov. 13, 1984, shortly after
his landslide reelection victory, the report said, because U.S.
officials had become frustrated with car-bombings at U.S.
facilities and the taking of American hostages.
   Congressional intelligence committees were not informed of the
crucial language in the findings, the report said.
   The authorization was rescinded on April 10, 1985, a month after
a car bomb exploded, killing 80 people in Beirut near the residence
of a leader of one faction of Iranian fundamentalists.
   The second authorization which included similar language was
signed by Reagan on Aug. 11, 1985, two months after the highjacking
of TWA Flight 847 in which American Navy diver Robert Stethem was
killed. The intelligence panels were briefed after the signing of
the second finding, the Post said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881005-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 0935EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vietnam-USMIA     10-05 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-US MIA,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Remains Found in Joint U.S.-Vietnamese Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HANOI, Vietnam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S-Vietnamese teams investigating the
fates of American airmen shot down on bombing missions found two
sets of human remains and the possible site of other remains,
officials said today.
   ``We found partial human remains at two different locations,''
said Bill Bell, leader of the six U.S. military experts. ``Neither
U.S. nor Vietnamese forensic experts have had access to them at
this point. The Vietnamese have pledged to immediately repatriate
any remains so we expect to receive them in the near future.''
   The two teams of experts found the remains and pieces of
aircraft wreckage in an eight-day search of areas in five provinces
around Hanoi. In the search, which ended Tuesday, the investigators
interviewed villagers and inspected sites were planes crashed
during the Vietnam War.
   The teams focused on trying to determine what happened to six
airmen shot down during bombing missions from 1965 to 1967, said
Nguyen Can, head of Vietnam's Office For Seeking Missing Personnel.
U.S. officials said some of the six men were believed to have
survived, although there was no evidence they are still alive.
   Villagers led investigators to remains in Lang Son and Ha Nam
Ninh provinces, said Can. He said the chances of identifying the
remains was improved because teeth were found.
   The remains will be sent to the United States after Vietnamese
experts examine them.
   U.S. investigators said the remains at Lang Son were found in a
graveyard, but they doubted the body was that of an American. They
also reported visiting sites in Ha Nam Ninh and Ha Bac provinces
that villagers said contained remains of Americans.
   The Americans left Hanoi today for Bangkok, Thailand, but were
to return Friday to review their findings and possibly discuss
additional joint work including excavations of the crash sites.
   Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach of Vietnam said Tuesday his
government agreed in principle to many more joint investigations
over the next two months to resolve the 70 ``discrepancy cases'' _
including the six airmen _ that the United States considers top
priority. Washington says there is evidence Vietnamese authorities
should have information on these cases, which include airmen who
were captured but never returned after U.S. forces withdrew from
Vietnam in 1973.
   The United States for years urged joint investigations, but
Vietnam previously allowed only one previous joint field project,
the 1985 excavation of a crash site outside Hanoi.
   The U.S. government lists 2,393 Americans as missing in action
from the Indochina war in Cambodia, Laos and Vietnam. The three
Indochinese governments deny holding any live Americans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881005-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 0939EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Yugoslavia-Protest     10-05 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia-Protest,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Workers March Into Parliament Demanding Leadership Ouster</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IVAN STEFANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of workers protesting
government failure to deal with a severe economic crisis marched on
the Parliament today demanding the ouster of Yugoslavia's communist
leaders, it was reported.
   About 5,000 workers from a factory in the Belgrade suburb of
Rakovica crowded in front of the Parliament, demanding to speak to
Serbian Communist Party leader Slobodan Milosevic, the official
Tanjug news agency reported.
   About 2,000 of the workers entered the building, protesting that
they had been locked inside their factory and prevented from
joining fellow workers in a protest march on Parliament on Tuesday.
   ``We have been betrayed!'' and ``We were locked up!'' they
chanted as they rushed in.
   Milosevic, who is hailed by supporters as the political heir to
the late Yugoslav leader Josip Broz Tito, told them:
   ``You should have trust that we shall carry out our reforms. The
moment you lose the trust, you should replace us.''
   The Rakovica workers _ who earn about $100 a month, or
two-thirds of the national average _ are part of the growing
national unrest in the face of a government austerity program
introduced in May that resulted in huge price rises and wage cuts.
   Today's protest ended peacefully, with the workers leaving after
speaking to Milosevic, said witnesses, who requested anonymity.
   On Tuesday, a cordon of policemen held back another angry crowd
of 5,000 workers from the Parliament building as they chanted
demands for Premier Branko Mikulic and his government to resign.
The workers jeered at Deputy Premier Milos Milosavljevic and
Parliament president Dusan Popovski, who has said he may resign.
   Yugoslavia is facing increasing labor and social unrest in the
worst economic crisis in its postwar history. The foreign debt is
$21 billion, unemployment is at least 15 percent and the official
inflation rate has reached 217 percent. However, it is widely
believed the inflation rate is actually higher.
   Two top Communist Party leaders resigned last week from the
23-member ruling Presidium in reaction to mass rallies organized by
Milosevic supporters in Serbia, the largest of Yugoslavia's six
republics.
   Communist Party leader Stipe Suvar announced Tuesday that up to
one-third of the Central Committee may be replaced at a key meeting
Oct. 17, where a major shakedown is expected over the party's
failure to manage the economic, ethnic and political tensions in
Yugoslavia.
   Party leaders also have been blamed for failing to stop tensions
in the autonomous region of Kosovo between ethnic Albanians, who
are Moslems, and the Christian Slavs.
</TEXT>
