<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GreenwoodShooting     10-05 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greenwood Shooting,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mental Health Commissioner Orders Inquiry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state's mental health commissioner has
ordered an inquiry into his department's handling of the case of
James William Wilson, the man accused in the Greenwood school
shooting spree last week that killed two children.
   Joseph Bevilacqua said Tuesday he could not yet assess whether
the mental health department made errors in not committing Wilson,
19, for treatment before his deadly visit to Oakland Elementary
School on Sept. 26.
   Two children died, and nine people, including two teachers, were
wounded.
   ``I, of course, have concerns where you have a situation of the
magnitude of this case in regard to the disruption of the community
and the lives that have been involved,'' Bevilacqua said.
   He said a panel of outside experts and people from within the
department will review Wilson's files and interview people involved
in the case.
   ``We're not blaming anyone,'' Bevilacqua said. ``We're trying to
get an assessment of what happened in a very difficult situation.
And if we should make corrective actions, we will, in fact, make
the corrective action.''
   The department twice since 1986 had rejected attempts by
Wilson's relatives to have him involuntary committed to a state
facility, according to a retired probate judge who had been
involved in the attempts.
   The former judge, Rosemary M. Trakas, told The Greenville News
that Wilson's family twice filed affidavits seeking his commitment
since 1986. She said he was evaluated on both occasions by the
department's Beckman Mental Health Center in Greenwood, and that
the petitions were rejected.
   She said Wilson had been involuntarily committed to the State
Hospital in Columbia for a period ``of just a few months'' in 1983.
He is back in that hospital now, undergoing a psyciatric
examination ordered by a court after the shootings.
   Dr. Willie Moseley of Greenwood, a private psychiatrist who had
treated Wilson, said Wilson checked himself into the mental health
unit at Self Memorial Hospital in Greenwood for 15 days about six
months ago.
   He said after that Wilson, described by his family as
hyperactive, reclusive and fascinated with multiple killers, was
referred to the Beckman center, but that he never went there for
treatment.
   Wilson's father, James T. Wilson Jr., said his son was no longer
covered by the family insurance policy when he turned 19 in April
and that private psychiatric care was too expensive.
</TEXT>
