<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 1006EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Shuttle-Discovery     10-05 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle-Discovery,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Space Shuttle In The Garage For Servicing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA crews today prepared
Discovery for its piggyback ride atop a jet to Florida and repaired
minor damage suffered in the space shuttle's 65 orbits of Earth.
   ``The crews are working, and they will work round the clock
until the orbiter leaves'' Saturday, said Ted Ayers, deputy site
manager for the National Aeronautics and Space Administration's
Dryden Flight Research Facility here.
   The spacecraft, which landed here Monday, had six heat-shield
tiles gouged by debris, apparently during liftoff, said John
Talone, shuttle processing director.
   Workers also found some ``dings'' to a few of the hundreds of
tiles that coat the shuttle, but detected no damage to the
orbiter's brakes, landing gear or tires, Talone said.
   Discovery sat inside the 100-foot-tall ``mate-demate device,'' a
shuttle garage where it is being serviced before its trip aboard a
jet Saturday to its Florida launch site.
   Workers must deactivate fuel cells, photograph tile damage and
replace gouged tiles, purge main engines and orbital maneuvering
engines, and attach locks to prevent control flaps from fluttering
during the piggyback flight.
   Discovery's mission was America's first manned space mission
since the Challenger tragedy in January 1986 that killed seven crew
members.
   ``The vehicle looks beautiful,'' Talone said during a news
conference Tuesday. ``It looks probably as good or better as any
vehicle we've brought in here.''
   Six tiles near the right wing must be replaced because of a
12-inch-long, 6-inch-wide, 1{-inch-deep gouge apparently caused by
debris during the shuttle's launch Thursday, Talone said.
   Talone said officials weren't yet sure if the debris was ice
that formed on the outside of the shuttle's external tank, which
contains supercold fuel.
   ``There's a minor number of traditional dings'' on some other
tiles, caused by the impact of tiny particles during liftoff and
landing, he added.
   After preliminary inspection found no damage, the shuttle's
brakes were shipped to B.F. Goodrich in Ohio for a closer look, he
said. The brakes were improved because of brake and tire damage
during previous missions.
   Talone said NASA workers haven't identified the cause of the
trouble with Discovery's flash evaporators _ a problem that made
the astronauts endure temperatures in the 80s during their flight.
   NASA plans for Discovery to depart Edwards early Saturday,
arriving at Kennedy Space Center in Florida before dark following a
single stop near San Antonio, Texas, Talone said.
   Discovery's next mission is scheduled to start Feb. 18, three
months after Atlantis' planned Nov. 17 liftoff with a classified
Defense Department payload.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
