<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Egypt-Parade     10-05 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Egypt-Parade,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Egypt Marks 1973 War With Low-Key Parade, First Since Sadat Slain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small group of top officials today
attended a low-key military parade, the first since President Anwar
Sadat was assassinated, to mark the 15th anniversary of the 1973
Middle East War.
   Sadat was killed at a much more elaborate anniversary parade on
Oct. 6, 1981.
   President Hosni Mubarak, government ministers and a select group
of diplomats were the only spectators allowed inside the high walls
of the Military College for today's two-hour parade, broadcast live
on television and radio.
   The government did not say why it held the parade a day earlier
than the anniversary of the war's start. Egypt considers its
crossing of the Suez Canal on Oct. 6, 1973, and capture of Israeli
positions on the western side as its finest modern-day military
accomplishment.
   The government also did not say why it resumed the military
parade, an annual tradition under Sadat. It was suspended after
Moslem extremists killed the president and seven other people.
   Under Sadat, the parades were held on one of Cairo's largest
streets. The day he died, he wore a white, high-booted uniform with
gold braid. Mubarak, commander of the air force before Sadat chose
him as vice president, stood beside him in uniform.
   Mubarak has not worn his uniform in public since that day.
Today, he wore a dark blue suit and mirrored sunglasses.
   In Sadat's parades, hundreds of gleaming tanks and armored
personnel carriers filled the streets and jet fighter-bombers gave
spectacular aerial shows.
   Today, trailers carrying tanks passed the elevated presidential
box one at a time. A handful of helicopters with Egypt's flag
dangling from them flew overhead for a while, and 15 parachutists
landed on the wide parade grounds. The parade was mainly a show of
the weapons that Egypt and Syria used in the 1973 war, called the
Yom Kippur War in Israel and the 10th of Ramadan War in the Arab
world.
   In a brief videotaped address, Mubarak said Sadat was a brave
hero who decided to make war and won, then decided to make peace.
   Sadat and former Israeli Prime Minister Menachem Begin, spurred
by President Carter, signed the Camp David accord in 1979. It is
still the only peace agreement between an Arab country and the
Jewish state.
</TEXT>
