<HEAD>Soviet Observers Inspect British Army Maneuvers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with names of Soviet officials, details of
military exercise. No Pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Soviet observers flew over the English
countryside today armed with tape recorders and cameras to inspect
military maneuvers on British territory for the first time.
   The Soviets are visiting Britain under terms of the 1986
Stockholm Agreement on East-West confidence building measures.
Under the accord, all 35 participating nations must be notified of
each other's large-scale maneuvers.
   The colonels, Anatoli Makhov, Vladimir Greshnikov, Yuri Leonov
and Vladimir Trofimov, landed at London's Heathrow Airport early
this morning and were taken by helicopter to the British army's
Bulford Barracks near Salisbury, 80 miles west of London.
   The Defense Ministry said the exercise, which is codenamed
Drake's Drum, began Saturday and ends Sunday. It extends over 5,500
square miles of southern England and includes several south coast
ports. The troops are practicing the defense of installations such
as airfields and ports, the ministry said.
   After a briefing by Col. John Cooper, chief of staff of the
army's land forces, British officers escorted the Soviets on their
inspection.
   The ministry said the Soviets will observe the exercise for two
days.
</TEXT>
