<DOCNO> AP881005-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 1105EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Chile 3rdLd-Writethru   10-05 0742</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chile, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0551,0765</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chileans Decide Their Future, Pinochet's Fate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with heavy turnout, Pinochet
quotes. Pick up 8th pvs, `If a...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of troops guarded polling
places today and voters stood in mile-long lines to cast ``yes'' or
``no'' ballots on a proposal to extend President Augusto Pinochet's
15-year rule to 1997.
   Power outages blamed on terrorist bombings plunged the capital
and other cities into darkness late Tuesday, but the country was
calm as polls opened at 8 a.m.
   By midmorning, thousands of voters lined up at Santiago voting
centers, waiting patiently under a sunny, cloudless sky in warm
spring weather.
   Chile's 7.4 million registered voters are required by law to
vote. Some voters said they arrived early for fear of trouble later
in the day.
   Pinochet, who voted downtown late this morning, spoke
sarcastically of the blackout by using the slogan of the
opposition: ``It's the joy that's coming.'' But the 72-year-old
army commander told reporters he heard no reports of incidents in
the first hours of voting. ``There are no problems,'' he said.
``The people are voting normally.''
   Pinochet, who campaigned hard across the country for a ``yes''
vote, was asked about the outcome and said, ``I'm always
optimistic.''
   Among early voters was Patricio Aylwin, president o the centrist
Christian Democratic Party and leader of a 16-party coalition
campaigning for Pinochet's defeat.
   ``It's like returning to the times of the republic,'' he
declared after casting his ballot in Chile's first presidential
vote since 1970.
   The downtown was virtually deserted, with shops and offices
closed for election day, a national holiday.
   Radio reports also indicated a heavy turnout without serious
problems in provincial cities and towns.
   If a majority votes ``yes,'' Pinochet will assume a new
eight-year term in March. If most vote ``no,'' an open election
with two or more candidates will take place next year, and the
winner will assume the presidency in March 1990.
   At least eight explosions were heard in Santiago on Tuesday
night, moments after the power outage affected a 1,300-mile stretch
of the country.
   Police said terrorists bombed at least three electrical towers,
but said they had no reports of damage or injuries from the
subsequent explosions, indicating they may have been noise bombs
intended to frighten but not harm.
   The nation's long-idled election machinery was put back in place
for the referendum on Pinochet, who lifted emergency rule and
loosened his tight grip on the opposition in the months preceding
the balloting.
   The first unofficial returns are to be released about an hour
after polls close at 5 a.m.
   The opposition coalition, distrustful of the Interior Ministry's
tabulations, planned a separate vote count. The group says it will
accept as official the results of the National Electoral Service,
which are to be disclosed on Friday.
   Gen. Jorge Zincke, military commander of Santiago, said
officials were ordered to provide access at polling places to an
estimated 500 foreign observers. ``We have nothing to hide,'' he
said.
   About 150,000 members of the armed forces and national police
have been on barracks alert since Sunday.
   If Pinochet's new eight-year term is approved, the military
junta he leads, which theoretically served as the legislative
branch of his government, will be disbanded. A new Congress would
be seated in 1990, with two-thirds elected and the remaining third
appointed by Pinochet.
   Whatever the outcome of the referendum, congressional elections
will be held in 1990, but the legislature will have limited
authority. It will be virtually powerless to amend a 1980
constitution, which gives the military autonomy and a supervisory
role in national policy-making.
   Pinochet has pointed to an improved economy and the promise of
growth and stability if he is retained as president. His critics
say the rich have benefited the most and that human rights abuses
continue under his rule.
   About 3 million of the 7.4 million voters were too young to vote
in 1973, when Pinochet led a bloody coup that toppled the elected
government of President Salvador Allende, a Marxist. Allende died
in the coup.
   In 1978, Pinochet's military government won a vote of confidence
and in 1980, it won passage the a new constitution.
   But both ballots were loosely organized, with no formal voter
registration and few if any protections against fraud, which
opposition groups say was widespread. This time, the opposition has
expressed satisfaction with the safeguards.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
