<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--Greylord     10-05 0158</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Greylord,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Convicted, Two Acquitted in Corruption Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge was convicted of accepting bribes but a
retired judge and an attorney were acquitted of related charges
resulting from Operation Greylord, an extensive investigation of
court corruption.
   Tuesday's acquittals were only the second and third acquittals
in more than four years of trials resulting from the probe.
   So far, 90 judges, lawyers and other court employees have been
indicted and 70 have been convicted, including 14 judges. Two
people have died while awaiting trial, and the remaining cases are
pending.
   Cook County Associate Judge Daniel Glecier, 60, was found guilty
of one count of racketeering conspiracy. He was convicted of paying
bribes as a defense attorney and accepting them as a judge. He will
be stripped of his post and his $75,000 salary when he is sentenced
Nov. 29.
   Former Cook County Judge Francis Maher and attorney David Dineff
were found innocent Tuesday.
</TEXT>
