<HEAD>Dukakis Accepts, Bush Declines ABC Offer for Open Faceoff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush today declined an
invitation to appear with Democrat Michael Dukakis on the ABC-TV
program ``Nightline'' _ outside the tight restrictions of their
other two debates _ after Dukakis had accepted the offer.
   The network invited both candidates to ``engage in an open-ended
discussion concerning the issues being raised in the 1988
presidential campaign,'' Roone Arledge, ABC News president, said in
a statement.
   Dukakis spokesman Dayton Duncan said today, ``We thought it was
a great opportunity for the American people to get beyond the
slogans and balloons and bring George Bush out from behind the flag
and get him to talk about the issues.''
   Duncan said ABC left open the possibility of Dukakis going on
alone with the program's host, Ted Koppel, but that nothing was
definite.
   Bush spokesman Mark Goodin said the campaign had rejected the
invitation.
   ``We're not going to do it. An open-ended disucussion of the
issues is a debate,'' Goodin said.
   ``We committed the campaign to two debates. The American people
will have, at the conclusion of the debates, an opportunity to look
at both candidates. Frankly, our campaign schedule requires the
candiate to be on the road after the second debate, taking his
message to the voters directly,'' he said.
</TEXT>
