<HEAD>Fans at Christian Rock Concert Break Barricade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A throng of teen-agers at a Christian rock
show broke a barricade as they pushed their way toward the stage
after promoters announced the show's opening act would not perform,
witnesses said.
   A barricade made of scaffolding and plywood gave way under the
rush of fans at the Tuesday night concert by Stryper, a nationally
known group that bills itself as a Christian heavy metal rock band.
   After the problem with the opening act was announced, Stryper's
performance as the main act was delayed for an hour.
   No injuries were reported. A small fire broke out when some
electrical wiring was trampled, according to officials and
witnesses. It was extinguished without incident.
   The barricade, which was intended to separate spectators from
the stage, was removed when it became structurally unsound, said
Paul Johnson, manager of the Bismarck Civic Center. Johnson
estimated the crowd at 3,350.
   ``As soon as the barricade started to bend, the concert stopped
and we assessed the situation,'' said Johnson.
   One of the concertgoers said the rush of fans toward the stage
was caused by the announcement that the opening act, White Lion,
would not appear.
   ``Everyone was ticked,'' said Missy Stainaker, who suffered
bruises on her ribs.
   White Lion backed out of the concert and was replaced by a
regional band bec Ld - Writethru, a0534,0575
</TEXT>
<HEAD>U.S. Rep. MacKay Wins Democratic Race To Oppose Mack</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with two candidates appearing
together today; picks up 5th graf pvs, `We are...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Kenneth ``Buddy'' MacKay won the
Democratic Senate runoff and said he would try to heal wounds from
the divisive race while looking ahead to a ``mainstream versus
extreme'' contest with Republican Connie Mack.
   State Insurance Commissioner Bill Gunter, who Tuesday lost a
runoff to MacKay in his third try at the Senate, put on a MacKay
button today in Tallahassee, the state capital. The two pledged to
put behind what Gunter had called one of the ugliest campaigns in
state history.
   ``We've had our differences, we're together now; we're going to
go forward,'' said MacKay, a third-term congressman.
   Unofficial returns from Tuesday's runoff gave MacKay 362,234, or
52 percent of the vote, to Gunter's 330,297, or 48 percent.
   Mack, a former Cape Coral bank president and grandson of the
baseball Hall of Fame manager, is a well-funded conservative whose
candidacy is drawing national Republican help. He won the GOP
primary on Sept. 6, getting more than half the votes so that a
runoff wasn't necessary.
   Mack and MacKay will face each other on the November ballot for
the seat held by Democratic Sen. Lawton Chiles, who is retiring
after three terms.
   ``We are the candidacy that can beat Connie Mack,'' MacKay said
Tuesday night. ``I see this election as mainstream versus extreme.''
   Mack agreed that voters faced an ideological decision.
   ``I think the voters in Florida are going to have a very clear
choice between the liberal Buddy MacKay and the conservative Connie
Mack,'' he said.
   The Senate runoff climaxed twisting events that began last
December, when Chiles, 58, announced he wouldn't seek re-election,
saying he was burned out by the Senate and didn't like the high
cost of running for re-election.
   Popular former two-term Gov. Reubin Askew then entered the race
against Mack. But Askew, well ahead in all polls, withdrew May 7,
saying he didn't like all the time spent raising funds.
   Gunter and MacKay jumped in after Askew pulled out, and they ran
one-two in the Sept. 6 primary. But neither received a majority,
making a runoff necessary.
   MacKay, a lawyer from a wealthy landowning family, was endorsed
by Askew, 1986 Democratic gubernatorial nominee Steve Pajcic,
third-place primary finisher Rep. Dan Mica and fourth-place
finisher state Sen. Patricia Frank.
   The runoff campaign was filled with negative advertising and
sharp exchanges in debates, and Democratic officials worried that
Mack would face a crippled opponent in the general election.
   MacKay, 55, attacked Gunter's integrity for his practice each
election of using campaign contributions from the insurance
industry he regulates, including from two companies that later
collapsed in corruption. He also charged that Gunter voted against
desegregation 15 years ago.
   Gunter, 54, charged that MacKay's congressional record betrayed
Israel, Social Security and anti-drug efforts, and he claimed
MacKay was being supported by corrupt defense contractors.
   MacKay warned that the well-funded Mack could exploit Gunter's
alleged ethics problems. Mack, meanwhile, went on the attack
against MacKay, running television and newspaper ads charging:
``Hey Buddy, You're liberal!''
   Gunter lost a 1974 Democratic Senate runoff and won a 1980
Senate runoff only to lose in the general election.
</TEXT>
