<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-TrainCrash     10-05 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Train Crash,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witnesses Report Shock After Train Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dazed survivors wandered the streets of Sverdlovsk
and flames shot 1,000 feet above the city after two freight cars
collided with a coal train and exploded, according to witness
accounts published Wednesday.
   Monday's explosion blasted a crater 200 feet wide and smashed 20
apartment buildings to rubble in the city 850 miles east of Moscow,
reporter Vladimir Sanatin wrote in Komsomolskaya Pravda.
   He wrote that he found a mother who had lived in one of the
buildings wandering in the street and repeating: ``I snatched him
from under the plaster. Seryozha, my son. He's 5 years old. And
he's alive!''
   Four people were killed and 500 sought medical care, the
newspaper Sovietskaya Rossiya reported. Of those, 90 were
hospitalized.
   Initial reports Tuesday said 280 people sought medical care and
that 87 were hospitalized.
   The latest reports said 359 families were left homeless.
   The explosions blasted a 30-foot-deep crater, set fire to tanks
of oil and gas and blanketed Sverdlovsk with dark smoke, the
government paper Izvestia said.
   The explosions damaged 108 stores, 86 restaurants and seven
hospitals, said Sovietskaya Rossiya. Glass was broken five miles
away from the railyard, Komsomolskaya Pravda said.
   Komsomolskaya Pravda said firefighters guarded other damaged oil
tanks to prevent the blaze from setting off more explosions.
   The accounts in the state-run media did not identify the
explosives. They said only that they were for use in the domestic
economy.
   The disaster was the latest in a series of major accidents that
have prompted sharp criticism of the heavily used Soviet rail
system.
   An express passenger train crashed on its way from Leningrad to
Moscow on Aug. 17, killing 24 people and injuring more than 100.
   In June, three box cars loaded with explosives blew up in the
industrial city of Arzamas about 240 miles east of Moscow. Eighty
people died in that blast and 229 were injured.
   The press accounts blamed the Sverdlovsk explosion on a
dispatcher who ordered the freight train to halt at the wrong
location on a track leading into the railyard. The cars loaded with
explosives became disconnected from the locomotive and started
rolling away.
   Engineer V. Pimenov managed to reconnect the locomotive, but
could not stop the train before it slammed through a junction into
the coal train, the reports said. A commission was formed to
investigate the accident.
</TEXT>
