<DOCNO> AP881005-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 1406EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ContraAid     10-05 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Aid,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House May Seek Release of Stockpiled Arms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House is considering asking Congress
to soon release $16.5 million in stockpiled weapons to the Contra
rebels in Nicaragua, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said
Wednesday.
   ``We are analyzing that possibility,'' Fitwater told reporters
at his daily briefing. ``A final decision has not been made at this
point.''
   Prospects for renewing military aid to the rebels has been
deemed a long shot by congressional leaders, who hope to have the
Senate and House adjourn for the year next week so that lawmakers
can campaign full-time for re-election.
   Congress rejected an administration military aid request last
Feb. 3 and the formal cutoff of weapons deliveries to the Contras
occurred on Feb. 29.
   Some $16.5 million in military equipment has been stockpiled in
Honduras. It was purchased with earlier U.S. aid, but its delivery
was frozen because of the peace process and cease-fire between the
Contras and Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government.
   Asked about the possibility of renewed aid, Fitzwater noted that
a provision in defense appropriations bill Reagan signed last
weekend permits the president to request a congressional vote on
whether to release the weapons to the rebels.
   The Pentagon bill ``authorizes the release of $16 million in
lethal material that had been purchased earlier but had not been
delivered ... and it sets forth findings that the president would
make in requesting that release,'' the spokesman said.
   He noted that under the legislation, the president must find
that Nicaragua has caused a crisis in Central America, the
administration must consult with the four Central American
democracies and then report to Congress justifying his request.
   Fitzwater said the president's justification for the release of
the aid must also meet two out of three conditions cited in the
legislation.
   Of the three, he said, the administration believes two had been
met _ continuing unacceptable levels of Soviet aid and Sandinista
violations of the peace accords.
   The spokesman called the third condition _ that the Sandinistas
have initiated an ``all-out attack'' against the Contras _ ``an
open question.''
   ``The status is, it's all under consideration and we haven't
made a formal decision,'' he said.
