<2ND_LINE>AM-School Shooting,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Child Anxious to Leave Hospital; Lawmen Expand Search for Gunman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MASCOTTE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine-year-old Leah Wilbanks talked of
fishing with her dad as lawmen expanded their search Wednesday for
a punk-haired gunman who shot the youngster while she did
cartwheels on her school playground.
   The blonde third-grader clutched a new fishing reel and argued
with her father about who would catch the biggest fish when she
gets out of an Orlando hospital.
   She remained in serious condition but ``that little sparkle was
back in her eye,'' her grandmother, Dolly Chapman said late Tuesday.
   Police said a skinny, bearded man in camouflage clothes fled
after firing Monday into the playground filled with children at
Mascotte Elementary School. Residents of this farm and grove
community in central Florida joined the hunt.
   The motive for the shooting was unknown, police said.
   ``I'm just hoping and praying for the big break to come,'' said
Police Chief Don Page. ``It's been an awful stress on mothers and
fathers.''
   Lake County Sheriff Noel Griffin Jr. said officers had
identified ``a good suspect'' believed to be still in the county.
Others described the suspect as a drifter known to have sought odd
jobs around the area.
   Officers combed woods and wetlands, knocked on doors, escorted
school buses and patrolled schools in Mascotte and nearby. A
hitchhiker on the main road through town said different officers
stopped him three times to check him out.
   Leah, an avid angler and cheerleader, was hit in the arm and
chest by one of three shots fired into the fenced playground, said
sheriff's Capt. Randy Swails.
   The gunman wore in his hair in a punk style, spiked on top and
shaved on the sides, police said.
   Twenty-four other third-graders and a physical education teacher
on the playground were not injured.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
