<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CoalFire     10-05 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Coal Fire,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Action Sought On Underground Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CHALFANT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NELSONVILLE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A slow, underground coal fire
discovered by the children plunging sticks into the ground should
be put out as soon as possible because it poses a threat to lives
and property, officials said Wednesday.
   State and local officials who surveyed the site on a wooded
hillside overlooking a city street proposed that the U.S. Office of
Surface Mining consider the fire an emergency to keep it from
spreading.
   The agency sent a representative to investigate.
   The fire was discovered Friday after parents of children who had
been playing on the hillside notified the Fire Department.
   ``They had been sticking sticks in the ground, poking them down,
and when they pulled them back up, they were on fire, and they were
really fascinated by that,'' said Tim Baden, fire chief in this
southeastern Ohio city of 5,000.
   ``When we arrived, there were three or four trees on fire and a
very hot spot on the ground.''
   The fire appeared to be in waste coal from a nearby unmapped
mine believed abandoned since the 1920s, said Mitchell Farley of
the Ohio Department of Natural Resources' Division of Reclamation.
   The fire posed no immediate threat to two houses about 60 feet
away. But as many as 30 houses could be threatened if it spreads
into the coal seam, officials said. Baden also said there was a
possibility of a brush fire.
   Bill Miska of the Office of Surface Mining in Columbus said if
his agency agrees there is an emergency, it will begin a cleanup. A
decision could be reached by Friday.
</TEXT>
