<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     10-05 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghans Say Rebel Rocket Attack Killed 13 In Capital</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Stands for Moscow-dated story slugged Soviet-Afghanistan on
advisory.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan guerrillas fired rockets at
Kabul during rush hour Wednesday and killed 13 people, disproving
claims that the rebels attack only military targets, Afghan media
reported.
   Radio Kabul, monitored in Islamabad, said 34 people were wounded
in the Afghan capital.
   It blamed the attack on ``criminal extremists,'' a reference to
the U.S.-backed rebels who have been fighting the Soviet-backed
government in Kabul for 10 years.
   The broadcast criticized Western media for ``claiming that the
so-called Mujahedeen are attacking military installations only.''
Commanders of the Afghan guerrillas have said they attack only
military targets, not residential areas.
   Tass, the official Soviet news agency, said 26 rockets
``exploded on the streets and squares of Kabul as its four
districts came under intensive shelling.''
   It quoted Afghanistan's official Bakhtar news agency as saying
16 shells hit Kabul suburbs and that the insurgents increased
pressure on the eastern city of Khost. It did not report casualties
in those attacks.
   The Soviet news agency said rebels are subjecting Khost ``to
nearly daily massive rocket and artillery shelling.''
   Tass also said Afghan government forces killed 23 rebels and
captured weapons in strikes at bases in Paktia, Balkh and Samangan
provinces.
   It reported continuing fighting among the rebels in Kuhestan,
Nejrab, Ghazni and Arghandab, and said about 50 insurgents were
killed.
   Radio Kabul said six people were killed in the eastern city of
Gardez in rocket attacks Tuesday afternoon and Wednesday morning.
Gardez is 60 miles southeast of Kabul.
   The Soviet Communist Party newspaper Pravda reiterated Soviet
complaints that Pakistan is to blame for violations of the U.N.
accord providing for the withdrawal of Soviet troops from
Afghanistan.
   ``All indications are that in Islamabad, they have a very flawed
idea of international law, state-to-state relations and
treaty-based commitments,'' the newspaper said.
   The Soviet Union said last week it halted the withdrawal of its
troops from Afghanistan, citing violations of the accord.
   Pravda said the Afghan government has registered more than 1,500
violations with U.N. monitors.
   Radio Kabul charged that among the alleged violations, Pakistan
is circulating forged afghanis, the local currency, in Kabul. The
radio offered no details.
   Under the accord signed April 14, the Soviet Union agreed to
withdraw its 100,000 soldiers from Afghanistan in exchange for a
pledge of non-interference by Pakistan and other countries that
have been aiding the guerrillas. The guerrillas are not party to
the agreement.
   Half of the Soviet force in Afghanistan was withdrawn between
May 15 and Aug. 15, and the Soviet Union has until Feb. 15 to
complete the pullout.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979, replaced one
pro-Soviet government with another and remained to fight the
anti-Marxist insurgents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
