<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Masks     10-05 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Masks,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Issuing Gas Masks To 37,000 Israelis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army said Wednesday it will distribute gas
masks to about 37,000 Israelis following reports that Arab
countries may resort to chemical weapons in a war against the
Jewish state.
   The test program will be coupled with studies to try to
determine if the reported use of chemicals in the Persian Gulf war
has prompted Israelis to take the threat seriously, said an army
spokesman.
   The masks will be given to 3,000 residents of the town of
Shelomi on the Israeli-Lebanese border and to about 34,000 people
in the Tel Aviv suburb of Ramat Hasharon, the spokesman said,
speaking on condition of anonymtiy.
   No exact date has been set for the distribution, but the
spokesman said it would take place in the ``near future.''
   ``There could eventually be a decision to distribute the masks
nationwide,'' he said. ``But that would be real far off. This is
only a test case.''
   A 1988 Middle East Military Balance report from Tel Aviv
University's Jaffee Center for Strategic Studies said chemical
weapons are an ``integral part'' of military offensive strategies
in Arab countries.
   ``It appears ... that chemical weapons are an important element
in the ... concept of overall strategic parity with Israel,'' the
report said. ``(Chemical weapons) are quickly and easily
attainable.''
   The army spokesman said Ramat Hasharon and Shelomi were chosen
for the test because studies show them to be representative of the
general population.
   ``It's possible people have become more aware of the threat of
chemical weapons,'' he said. ``But without that awareness, it's
pretty useless to give them the masks.''
   In August, the army began equipping troops with newly developed
pills that increase immunity to chemical weapons.
</TEXT>
