   On Tuesday, South Korean President Roh Tae-woo called for summit
talks with Kim Il Sung, leader of the communist North, and said he
was ready to cooperate to end tension between the two countries.
   ``Our people and People's Army soldiers are watching with
heightened vigilance the moves of the (South Korean government) in
deliberately rendering the situation strained as soon as the
Olympic Games ended,'' KCNA said.
   The North decided to boycott the Olympics, which ended on Oct. 2
in Seoul, after the International Olympic Committee turned down its
request to be a co-host.
   The Korean Peninsula was divided at the end of World War II.
