<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 1514EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-GrasshopperWar     10-05 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grasshopper War,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists Trying New Products to Battle Grasshoppers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The age-old war against marauding grasshoppers
is being waged with some promising new biological weapons, the
Agriculture Department said Wednesday.
   In one development, two commercial firms _ Evans BioControl Inc.
of Broomfield, Colo., and Bozeman Bio Tech of Bozeman, Mont. _ have
adapted USDA technology for producing and storing a parasite,
Nosema lucustae. Department studies show the parasite kills 50
percent to 60 percent of grasshoppers in three to four weeks.
   The basic tests and development were done by the department's
Agricultural Research Service at the agency's Rangeland Insect
Laboratory in Bozeman by J.E. Henry and colleagues.
   Henry said the parasite is available to homeowners and ranchers
through regional agents and on contract to government agencies,
which use it on a large scale in the West. Grasshoppers cause an
estimated $400 million in damage to grass and crops each year, he
said.
   Spores of the parasite are put on wheat bran flakes to form a
bait. After the insects eat the bait, the organism ``attacks the
pest's fat cells and depletes its energy stores,'' Henry said in a
report issued here.
   The parasite remains in the grasshopper population because sick
females pass it on to offspring, and survivors eat dead relatives,
he said.
   Meanwhile, another development involves an agreement with Evans
Biotechnical to field test another natural killer, grasshopper
entomopoxvirus, the agency said. In laboratory tests, the virus
kills 20 percent to 30 percent of the grasshoppers right away and
stunts the growth of an additional 20 percent to 30 percent.
   Doug A. Streett, an entomoligist at the agency's Bozeman
laboratory, said Evans BioControl plans to produce the virus and
mix it with the parasite for tests on 1,000 acres in the West.
   Streett said that in combination the two ingredients may work
more rapidly to kill the grasshoppers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881005-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 1523EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scotus-SetAside     10-05 0727</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Set Aside,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Examines Affirmative Action Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court heard arguments Wednesday
that programs to reserve some public works contracts for minorities
cause reverse discrimination, while proponents said they break down
rigid racial barriers.
   The justices explored the power of state and local governments
to give preferential treatment to minority-owned businesses in a
key affirmative action case from Richmond, Va., to be decided by
July.
   At stake could be set-aside programs adopted by most states and
some 190 local governments.
   The Richmond plan was intended to fight racial discrimination,
``a scourge of our society,'' said John Payton, a lawyer
representing the city.
   Black participation in the construction trades had been ``close
to zero,'' he said. ``The evidence is stark and dramatic'' that
blacks were excluded systematically from entering and advancing in
the industry.
   ``Other remedies had no impact. They simply weren't working,''
he added.
   But Walter Ryland, representing building contractor J.A. Croson
Co., said setting aside part of the contracts for minorities is
reverse discrimination.
   ``If (city officials) wanted to attack societal discrimination,
they could do it by racially neutral means,'' he said.
   Croson successfully challenged the set-aside after the company
lost a city contract for failure to include a minority-owned
business as a subcontractor.
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled in September 1987
there is insufficient evidence that city officials discriminated
against minority-owned businesses in the past and it said the
plan's quota appeared to be completely arbitrary.
   Richmond adopted the plan in 1983 to require that a prime
contractor on any city building project subcontract at least 30
percent of the value of the project to firms that are at least
one-half minority owned.
   While the minorities named in the plan include Hispanics,
Orientals, Indians, Eskimos and Aleuts, the primary beneficiary
would be blacks _ who make up around half of Richmond's black
population.
   The Supreme Court has been closely divided on affirmative action
disputes, and Wednesday's hour-long argument session provided few
hints on the likely outcome of the Richmond case.
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, the court's newest member and
possibly the key to the outcome of the case, pressed the lawyers on
both sides to explain their positions.
   ``Is (the set-aside) the most narrowly tailored remedy'' for
racial bias, he asked? Kennedy suggested that the quota could mean
higher costs for city projects.
   Payton replied ``there is no real constitutional question''
posed by that possibility. ``Richmond can decide that is the cost
of remedying'' past discrimination.
   Kennedy, participating in his first affirmative action case
since joining the court last February, replaced Justice Lewis F.
Powell, who often cast the deciding vote on programs involving
preferential treatment for minorities.
   The Richmond case also may help foretell the court's future
approach to other forms of affirmative action and alleged reverse
discrimination. The justices in a recent string of decisions
generally have upheld preferential treatment for minorities and
women.
   Ryland challenged Richmond's motives in adopting the set-aside
policy. Noting that the city council had a black majority and that
the city's population is around 50 percent black, he said the plan
``could be just a pork-barrel thing.''
   But Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist noted that the court in
1980 upheld a similar 10 percent quota adopted by Congress for
federal building contracts.
   Congress also might adopt pork-barrel legislation, Rehnquist
said, ``but we give it a presumption of validity.''
   How Richmond selected a 30 percent quota is one of the issues at
the heart of the case.
   Ryland said the figure was ``pulled out of the air'' and was
``so high it can force a particularly serious impact on non-minorty
firms.''
   But Payton said 30 percent is a reasonable compromise in a city
that is half black and where historically minority-owned businesses
received less than 1 percent of the value of city contracts.
   Set-aside programs also have caused some deep divisions and
seemingly contradictory views within the Reagan administration.
   President Reagan, for example, said in 1984 he favored
channeling billions of additional contract dollars to
minority-owned firms. And the administration generally has looked
upon public works set-asides more sympathetically than other
affirmative action quotas it sternly opposes.
   But the Justice Department, responding to an invitation from the
Supreme Court in a case similar to the Richmond dispute, challenged
the constitutionality of set-asides.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
