<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 1549EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Counterterrorism     10-05 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Counterterrorism,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Denies Reagan Signed Order Authorizing Assassinations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House denied Wednesday that
intelligence authorizations signed by President Reagan in the
mid-1980s gave CIA agents latitude to use assassinations in the
fight against terrorism.
   But chief spokesman Marlin Fitzwater acknowledged that language
in two intelligence findings in 1984 and 1985 subsequently was
rescinded by the National Security Council, though he wouldn't say
why.
   Reagan's spokesman took strong exception to a Washington Post
report Wednesday which said phrasing in the earlier documents
amounted to a ``license to kill'' for intelligence agents.
   Fitzwater suggested that the Post story was an attempt to
embarrass the administration during the election campaign. But he
stopped short of saying precisely that, telling reporters to ``make
your own judgment.''
   ``I think this is an extraordinary cheap shot. It's not true,''
he said.
   Fitzwater's harsh statements at the daily White House news
briefing mirrored comments he made Sept. 28, 1987 on a book by Bob
Woodward, assistant managing editor of The Post for investigative
reporting, entitled ``VEIL: The Secret Wars of the CIA.''
   The book among other things described intelligence findings
signed by Reagan in 1984 and 1985 which contained language
interpreted by some in the administration as providing a means for
U.S. spies to make an end run around a 1981 Reagan executive order
flatly prohibiting assassinations.
   On September 1987, Fitzwater, responding to the revelations in
Woodward's book, said Reagan ``was never aware of ... never
authorized ... any assassination efforts.''
   On Wednesday, he said, ``This an old story being rehashed again,
interestingly timed, but has no foundation.'' Woodward was a
co-author of the story that appeared in Wednesday's editions of The
Post.
   The authorizations ``deemed'' as lawful any covert actions _
including potentially violent ones _ taken in ``good faith'' by
U.S. intelligence agents against terrorists, according to the
report.
   Fitzwater denied that the intelligence findings could have been
construed as sanctioning assassination in attempts to combat
worldwide terrorism.
   ``I'm not going to give you a specific definition ... (of the
phrasing in question) because I don't know and ... because we
wouldn't discuss it anyway,'' he said. ``But the purpose was to
authorize counterintelligence activities to counter terrorism.''
   ``The point is they did not authorize assassinations, period,''
Fitzwater added. ``Because there's an executive order in effect
that said they didn't. Because the president said they didn't.''
   ``It was rescinded when a new terrorism finding was made in May
of 1986. It was omitted, but I don't know why. And then when they
(intelligence findings) were all reviewed again in May of '87, it
was firmly and specifically omitted.''
   The Post story said Reagan signed intelligence authorizations in
both 1984 and 1985 giving CIA agents broad anti-terrorism powers.
   It reported that unidentified White House officials said Vice
President George Bush would have been given a copy of or would have
had access to the findings.
   Bush also denied the report Wednesday, saying, ``If we weren't
in polite company, I'd tell you what I thought about a report like
that.'' Asked during an appearance in Littleton, Colo., if it were
true, Bush said ``Absolutely not. To circumvent the law against
assassinations is absolutely criminal.''
   Reagan signed the first finding on Nov. 13, 1984, shortly after
his landslide re-election victory, the Post report said, because
U.S. officials had become frustrated with car-bombings at U.S.
facilities and the taking of American hostages.
   Congressional intelligence committees were not informed of the
crucial language in the findings, the report said. Fitzwater denied
that Wednesday, saying there had been notification.
   The authorization was rescinded on April 10, 1985, a month after
a car bomb exploded, killing 80 people in Beirut near the residence
of a leader of one faction of Iranian fundamentalists.
   The second authorization which included similar language was
signed by Reagan on Aug. 11, 1985, two months after the highjacking
of TWA Flight 847 in which American Navy diver Robert Stethem was
killed. The intelligence panels were briefed after the signing of
the second finding, the Post said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
