<DOCNO> AP881005-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 1554EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-OzoneLawsuit     10-05 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ozone Lawsuit,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Environment Group Sues Government to Halt CFC Production</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An environmental group said Wednesday it had
sued the Environmental Protection Agency seeking to force it to
order a complete end to the use of chemicals that destroy the
earth's protective ozone layer.
   The suit by the Natural Resources Defense Council challenges the
adequacy of the partial cutbacks that EPA ordered for five major
chlorofluorocarbon compounds, or CFC's, on Aug. 1.
   Those regulations paralled provisions of the 1987 treaty by
major producing nations pledging themselves to a 50 percent
reduction in CFC output by 1998.
   EPA Administrator Lee M. Thomas last week said new analyses show
that the 50 percent cut will not protect the ozone layer high in
the stratosphere and the chemicals in question should be phased out.
   The ozone layer reduces the amount of cancer-causing ultraviolet
rays from the sun that reach the earth's surface. The CFC
compounds, normally inert, rise through the atmosphere to the ozone
layer, where those same ultraviolet rays break them apart and free
chlorine to destroy the ozone.
   CFC's are used as refrigeration fluids, solvents and plastic
foam blowing agents. Many countries still permit their use as
aerosol propellants, a use banned in the United States in 1978.
   ``The United States is the single largest contributor to
world-wide emissions of ozone-depleting chemicals,'' responsible
for about 30 percent of global use, said David Doniger, an attorney
for the council. ``We have a responsibility to clean up our own
house.''
   Doniger argued that the United States ``leads best when it leads
by example.'' He said the EPA could pressure other countries to
follow suit by banning imports of products made with CFC's unless
the importing country also was committed to ending CFC use.
   He said EPA's refusal to go beyond the treaty in its regulations
``appears to reflect a deal struck within the administration last
summer'' to placate a faction that believed no treaty was necessary.
   EPA spokesman Dave Cohen said Doniger's ``notion of a deal is
untrue and silly.''
   ``Our goal all along has been to get the nations of the world to
the table and agree to the deepest reductions we could possibly
get,'' Cohen said.
   ``We feel only a global solution will truly help the ozone
layer,'' and unilateral U.S. action could be counterproductive by
leading other nations to conclude they could safely increase their
use of CFC's as a result, Cohen said.
   The suit was filed in the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881005-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 1542EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Yugoslavia Bjt   10-05 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia, Bjt,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Shake-Up Scheduled In Ethnic And Economic Turmoil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party chief Stipe Suvar
called for a shake-up in the ruling Politburo and the
policy-setting Central Committee after weeks of ethnic and economic
protests, state-run media said Wednesday.
   About 5,000 workers marched on Parliament on Wednesday for the
second straight day. Workers have stepped up strikes and
demonstrations over the communist government's failure to reduce
217 percent inflation and unemployment, which is at 15 percent.
   Radio Belgrade said 140,000 Serbs attended two rallies in
central Serbia to push demands for greater Serbian control over the
autonomous provinces of Kosovo and Vojvodina, where ethnic
Albanians outnumber Serbs.
   Thousands more flag-waving Serbs attended a similar rally in
Novi Sad, 42 miles north of the capital, according to Radio
Belgrade and the state-run Tanjug news agency. Crowd estimates
ranged from 30,000 to 80,000.
   Suvar said Tuesday night that the 162-member Central Committee
probably will vote on personnel changes in the Politburo on Oct. 17
in a session expected to be a major showdown between factions in
the party leadership. State newspapers reported his comments
Wednesday.
   He said the Politburo will meet before Oct. 17 ``to determine
the criteria of possible responsibility of its members'' for the
country's worst economic and political crisis since World War II.
   ``If it fails in this, the Central Committee will assume this
role, and anyone who does not win two-thirds of the committee's
votes will have to leave the presidium (Politburo),'' he said.
   As the top body of Yugoslavia's only political party, the
Politburo is the most powerful institution in the country. It has
23 members, but two resigned last week under mounting criticism.
   Suvar also said about one-third of the Central Committee
membership will be changed by the end of the autumn.
   ``Very soon new people will be brought into the Central
Committee of the League of Communists and its presidium,'' Suvar
said.
   Suvar announced that a similar ``cadre renewal'' was expected in
the party leaderships of Yugoslavia's six republics and two
autonomous provinces.
   Yugoslavs have become increasingly vocal in demanding top-level
personnel changes. Leaders have been blamed for failing to defuse
tensions between the mostly Christian Serbian minority and the
largely Moslem Albanian majority in Kosovo.
   In addition to high inflation and double-digit unemployment, the
country has a $21 billion foreign debt.
   Yugoslav and foreign observers believe major personnel changes
at the Oct. 17 meeting will be aimed at reducing tensions between
different factions within the party.
   Senior leaders who have been denounced in public and are widely
expected to be sacked during or before the meeting include Stane
Dolanc, the nation's vice president from Slovenia; Josip Vrhovec, a
Croatian member in the collective presidency; and several officials
from the autonomous provinces of Vojvodina and Kosovo.
   Among those who expect to emerge victorious from the meeting are
hard-line Serbian officials and their supporters, led by the
Serbian republic's party boss, Slobodan Milosevic.
   Milosevic, riding a wave of popularity in the largest republic,
advocates more central control over the provinces.
   On Wednesday, for the second straight day, Milosevic addressed a
crowd of angry workers at Parliament and promised reforms.
   About 5,000 workers booed two other Communist leaders outside
Parliament on Tuesday.
   During the TV interview, Suvar rejected suggestions that the
introduction of a multiparty system in this single-party state
would resolve the crisis.
   He said that a type of a multiparty system already exists
because each of the republics and autonomous provinces has its own
communist party, but that the system does not work.
</TEXT>
