<HEAD>Child Survives After Falling Into Sewage Lift Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 3-year-old girl who tumbled into a
sewer opening survived by holding on to a pipe and bobbing for 45
minutes in 10-foot-deep water until rescue crews arrived,
authorities said.
   Elizabeth Marie Tong apparently fell into the 18-foot-deep
opening while playing with a friend at a construction site near her
home Tuesday evening.
   A woman who had been horseback riding in the area discovered the
child. ``She was a real trooper,'' said Elizabeth Winstead, who
called for help and talked to the girl to keep her calm.
   The young girl complained of being cold, but appeared to be
uninjured in the fall, said fire rescue spokesman Wayne Doolittle.
   The opening was about 4 to 5 feet in diameter. To keep her head
above water, the child, who fell in at about 7 p.m., wrapped her
arms around a 10-inch diameter pipe, Ms. Winstead said.
   ``I told her to hang on,'' she said, adding, ``I didn't know the
water was that deep.''
   Rescue crews lowered a ladder into the opening and climbed down
to get her.
   ``She was very lucky. She could have easily drowned,'' Doolittle
said Wednesday.
   The child was examined at Baptist Medical Center and released to
her parents. ``She's doing fantastic. She looks really good,'' said
Dr. John Stimler.
   Normally, Public Safety Director John Keane said, sewage station
openings are locked to prevent such accidents.
   ``We don't know why that lift station was not locked,'' he said.
</TEXT>
