<HEAD>Woman Gulps Pills At Foreclosure Hearing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENSBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman gulped pills in an apparent
suicide attempt during a break in a foreclosure proceeding where
she risked losing a dairy farm that has been in the family for at
least four generations, authorities said.
   ``Just about everything bad that could happen to people happened
to these people,'' attorney Ned Nakles Jr. said Wednesday of Ida A.
Depta and her family. ``The woman got caught up in such a feeling
of hopelessness.''
   Mrs. Depta, 48, of Alverton took the prescription pills from two
bottles in front of other people in a courthouse hallway Tuesday
afternoon.
   ``That tells me she wasn't so much trying to kill herself as she
was asking for help,'' said Nakles, who represents the estate of
Mrs. Depta's late mother, Irene Bowser.
   Mrs. Depta remained in Westmoreland Hospital. Officials withheld
her condition and other details at the family's request.
   Nakles said he did not know what kind of pills she swallowed.
   The incident occurred in the Westmoreland County Courthouse,
where negotiations were under way to settle an attempt by ITT
Financial Service to foreclose on the family's 100-acre dairy farm
in southwestern Pennsylvania.
   The lender sued in 1985, claiming Mrs. Bowser and the Deptas
defaulted on a $111,000 loan secured by the farm's 1984 estimated
market value of $220,000. Mrs. Bowser, who died in August, had
diabetes and was nearly blind, Nakles said.
   Mrs. Depta ``stated to us that all she wants is to join her mom
at the cemetery,'' said Deputy Sheriff Eric Sinclair. ``She's just
upset over her mom, her brother is dying of cancer, and the
possible loss of the farm.''
   Witnesses said the Deptas' 18-year-old daughter was able to pull
some of the pills from her mother's mouth.
   Misfortunes at the farm caused some of the Deptas' money
problems.
   Eighteen dairy cows died of an udder disease, and the Deptas
were forced to have water hauled to their cattle after the farm's
well was fouled around the time a gas well was drilled nearby,
Nakles said.
   In addition, Mrs. Depta's husband, Joseph, was unable to work
because of neck, back, shoulder and leg injuries from an auto
accident in 1984, according to court documents. Depta also was
treated for depression that year.
