<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 1917EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Incontinence     10-05 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Incontinence,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Doctors Can Do More To Help Incontinence Sufferers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten million Americans suffer from urinary
incontinence and most could be helped if doctors would apply proven
treatments in more cases, a National Institutes of Health committee
concluded Wednesday.
   ``We're not talking about rocket science here,'' said Dr. John
W. Rowe, chairman of the 15-member consensus development panel.
``This is something we can do tomorrow.''
   The committee report calls for family physicians to pay more
attention to incontinence problems in their elderly patients and
educate themselves about threatment. It also urges patients to be
more assertive in expecting adequate treatment if they are
incontinent.
   And it called for more research into the causes of incontinence,
a field the experts said has largely been overlooked in the quest
for answers to more exotic medical ailments.
   Their fundamental point, however, was that the existing
treatments often do not get to the people who need them because of
a widespread and erroneous belief, even by many doctors, that
incontinence is a natural consequence of aging.
   ``This is an issue we can no longer neglect,'' Rowe said at a
news conference wrapping up the panel's three-day meeting. ``Most
cases can be cured or improved.''
   He said more than half of those suffering from the problem are
not even evaluated, let alone treated.
   Rowe, a professor from The Mount Sinai School of Medicine in New
York City, offered this hypothetical remark from doctor to
incontinent patient as all too familiar: ``Well, what do you
expect, my dear. After all, you are 82.''
   He said the patient should reply: ``I expect to get responsible,
adequate medical care.''
   One specific recommendation was for legislation requiring the
manufacturers of adult diapers to carry a label message emphasizing
that most incontinence is treatable and that anyone suffering from
it should get a full medical evaluation.
   ``Many people with incontinence turn prematurely to the use of
absorbent materials without having their difficult properly
diagnosed and treated,'' the report said.
   There are several treatments for the various causes of
incontinence, which is defined in the report as ``a symptom rather
than a disease.''
   The condition can be treated with drugs, surgery or behavioral
techniques, which include exercises and biofeedback.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881005-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 1606EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen     10-05 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen `Feeling Great' for Showdown With Quayle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be topped after 8:30 p.m. EDT debate.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Lloyd Bentsen said he was ``feeling
great'' and ready for his prime-time showdown Wednesday night with
Republican Dan Quayle.
   The Texas senator, preparing for the most important night of his
vice presidential campaign, appeared relaxed as he headed to the
Omaha Civic Auditorium for a lighting and microphone check a few
hours before the 90-minute debate with his GOP counterpart.
   What would he try to accomplish in the debate? he was asked.
``Win,'' he replied.
   Bentsen spoke by telephone with Democratic nominee Michael
Dukakis in Boston. ``We had a good visit,'' Bentsen said, adding
that Dukakis' advice was to ``just be myself.''
   Dukakis and Bentsen planned a reunion Thursday at a steel plant
rally near Longview, Texas.
   Bentsen arrived in Omaha on Tuesday night after four days of
intense preparations, first in Washington and then in Austin,
Texas. He took time to spend with his wife and three children and
planned to work out in the hotel gym to help him relax before the
debate.
   B.A. Bentsen accompanied her husband to the private tour of the
debate site Wednesday afternoon. Afterward, according to press
secretary Mike McCurry, Bentsen, 67, picked up his wife and carried
her off the stage. ``She looked like she was willing to go with him
anywhere,'' he said.
   Much of his preparation was devoted to making Bentsen
comfortable with the format of the debate, which limited the
candidates to two-minute answers and one-minute responses, aides
said.
   ``It's a matter of taking the language of the U.S. Senate and
putting it in a form that's suitable for television,'' McCurry said.
   Although his advisers admitted helping Bentsen ``frame his
answers,'' McCurry said, ``we have not armed him with a lot of cute
one-liners. That's not really his style.''
   ``I think we'll leave the one-liners to Roger Ailes and Dan
Quayle,'' said Dukakis aide Leslie Dach, referring to the
Republican media strategist who has been coaching the GOP candidate.
   Bentsen and other Democrats have tried to exploit public
uneasiness about Quayle's qualifications for the job, and public
polls show Quayle is a drag on the Republican ticket. A strong
performance by the 41-year-old Quayle could turn that around.
   ``I don't think people are going to judge this just by the fact
he doesn't stumble,'' Dach said. He said Quayle needed ``an
extremely strong performance'' to overcome the public's doubts.
</TEXT>
