<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Elections     10-05 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Elections,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Bars Kahane's Anti-Arab Party From Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Plastic Bullets, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Central Elections Committee decided
Wednesday that Rabbi Meir Kahane's anti-Arab Kach Party is racist
and cannot run in the Nov. 1 parliamentary elections. The party
said it would appeal to the Supreme Court.
   The committee acted after the rival Labor and Likud parties
joined in condemning the American-born rabbi's party as racist and
anti-democratic. The committee is made up of members of the
Knesset, Israel's parliament, in proportion to each party's
representation.
   In another development, Attorney General Yosef Harish said there
was insufficient evidence for him to investigate charges that Labor
bugged Likud headquarters, Israel radio reported.
   Kach member Rahamim Cohen, who defended his party before the
committee, said: ``This was a political lynching. I personally feel
the Supreme Court will cancel this decision.''
   Israel's Supreme Court has upheld disqualification of a
political party only once, in 1965 when it ruled against a party
called Socialist List whose members allegedly belonged to an
outlawed group pledged to destruction of Israel.
   In 1984, it overruled an Elections Committee decision to
disqualify Kach, which had won a Knesset seat, occupied by Kahane,
in the 1984 election.
   After that committee decision, the Knesset passed a law barring
racist parties from running for office.
   The Kach platform calls for expulsion of the 2.2 million Arabs
living in Israel and the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Committee members voted 28-5, with three abstentions, to ban
Kach. The opposition came from three small religious parties.
   Kahane, born in Brooklyn, N.Y., established the Jewish Defense
League in the United States before moving to Israel and founding
Kach, which means ``Thus'' in Hebrew.
   His party's popularity has grown because of anti-Arab sentiment
fed by the 10-month-old Palestinian revolt in the occupied lands.
Recent polls indicated it could win up to three of the 120 Knesset
seats Nov. 1.
   Dan Meridor of Likud said of the election committee vote: ``This
was a difficult decision. We are depriving (the party) of a
fundamental right.''
   Many references were made to the Jews' own past as a persecuted
people during the committee debate, which lasted nearly four hours.
   ``Now that the Jewish people have become the majority, will they
treat people as did other nations which lost all semblance of
humanity?'' asked Chaim Ramon of Labor. ``The Nazis started the
same way with the same phrases.''
   Cohen denied Kach ideology was racist.
   ``Our attitudes toward the Arab population do not stem from
racist motives but from security considerations, because the Arab
population is a hostile population. Orthodox Jewish law obligates
every Jew to keep himself apart from the gentiles and not to
assimilate.''
   Kahane says his party platform is based on Orthodox law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
