<1ST_LINE>u p AM-FloridaRunoff     10-05 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Florida Runoff,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>MacKay Gains Defeated Rival's Support in Senate Race Against GOP's
Mack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Kenneth ``Buddy'' MacKay and
his defeated rival for the Democratic Senate nomination joined
forces Wednesday against the Republican nominee after their
bruising primary battle.
   MacKay, who won Tuesday's runoff against Insurance Commissioner
Bill Gunter, said he didn't think the divisive primary would harm
the Democrats' chances in November to claim the seat being vacated
by Democrat Lawton Chiles.
   MacKay faces U.S. Rep. Connie Mack, the grandson of the Hall of
Fame baseball manager of the same name, in the Nov. 8 general
election. Chiles is retiring after three terms.
   ``We're not going to lose this election because our party's
divided,'' MacKay, a three-term congressman, said after his 52
percent to 48 percent victory over Gunter.
   ``Though our experience had its pitfalls, had its ups and downs
and there was some pain, it was a much better exercise in the
Democratic process than the performance of `Cardboard Connie,'''
Gunter said at a news conference before attaching a MacKay sticker
to his suit.
   ``I'm proud to support him (MacKay) and will do all that I can
to ensure his election,'' he added.
   Mack said he knew the Democrats would nominate the most liberal
candidate. He adopted the tactic of GOP presidential nominee George
Bush in painting Democrats as liberals outside the mainstream.
   ``I am conservative. I am proud of being conservative,'' Mack
said during a stop in Tallahassee. ``The state of Florida is
conservative. I believe the things that I have talked about in the
past year are in the mainstream, and that's what the debate is
about.''
   Even before the runoff Tuesday, Mack ran commercials going after
MacKay, saying: ``Hey Buddy, You're Liberal!''
   MacKay cited Mack's support of former Marine Lt. Col. Oliver
North, who has campaigned for Mack, as an example of extremism. He
also brought up a zero rating assigned to Mack by the National
Council on Senior Citizens, who represent an important segment of
Florida's population, and environmentalists' criticism of Mack.
   ``I'm in the mainstream,'' MacKay said. ``He's in the extreme.''
</TEXT>
