<DOCNO> AP881005-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 1946EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Copyright     10-05 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Copyright,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Paves Way for Approval of International Copyright Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted 89-0 approval Wednesday of
legislation paving the way for the United States to join a
century-old agreement among 76 nations that grants global
copyrights to literary and artistic works.
   ``Adherence to the convention will greatly benefit the United
States,'' said Sen. Pat Leahy, D-Vt., chairman of the Senate
Judiciary Committee's subcommittee on patents, copyrights and
trademarks. ``It will provide the guidelines which govern the
copyright regulations between nations.''
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, ranking Republican on the panel,
agreed. ``Our participation will provide benefits to American
copyright holders and artists.''
   The bill would change U.S. copyright law, paving the way for
Senate consent to ratification of the treaty, signed in Berne,
Switzerland, on Sept. 9, 1886. Ratification will come on a separate
vote.
   The Berne Convention, which has been signed by 76 nations,
spells out minimum copyright standards, detailing what is protected
and how long the protection lasts.
   The pact prohibits member nations from discriminating against
copyrighted works of other member nations. It also provides for
copyright protection to take effect in other countries
automatically without the necessity of government formalities, such
as providing official notice of a copyright.
   The chief dispute over the legislation involved how best to
protect what are known as ``moral rights'' _ the authority of a
writer or artist to guard the integrity of his work against what he
thinks are damaging changes or misuse.
   Artists have generally argued for stiff coverage in U.S. law of
moral rights. Critics have said that strong coverage is
unnecessary, although they support the idea of protecting the
artistic integrity of works.
   American copyright law doesn't cover moral rights. The Berne
Convention requires signing nations to protect in law the right of
an artist to ensure the integrity of his work. However, that
protection doesn't have to be part of copyright law.
   The bill approved Wednesday sidesteps that issue, providing that
neither the measure nor adherence to the Berne Convention expands
or contracts a copyright holder's rights to object to any change in
a protected work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881005-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 1948EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scotus-Sentencing     10-05 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Sentencing,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer Questions Constitutionality of New Sentencing System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer urged the Supreme Court on Wednesday
to strike down a new sentencing system for people convicted of
federal crimes, saying, ``Judges are supposed to stay out of
political controversies.''
   Washington lawyer Alan Morrison attacked federal sentencing
rules that took effect last Nov. 1 because the seven-member
commission that issued them included three federal judges.
   Judges participating in a political process ``that could fairly
be called horse-trading'' is unconstitutional because it impugns
the federal judiciary's neutrality and impartiality, Morrison
argued.
   The job of passing laws about sentences for federal crimes
belongs to Congress and not to judges, Morrison said.
   But Solicitor General Charles Fried, the government's top
courtroom lawyer, called the U.S. Sentencing Commission's work a
constitutionally acceptable attempt to resolve ``grave, invidious
and inexplicable disparities in the sentencing process.''
   At issue is the validity of the commission, created by Congress,
and the validity of the sentencing rules it issued.
   More than 90 federal trial judges have refused to use the new
sentencing rules, declaring them and the commission
unconstitutional. But at least 60 of their colleagues have upheld
the system, imposing sentences under the new rules.
   By the time the justices announce their decision, expected by
July, thousands of defendants will be subject to resentencing _
regardless of which way the court rules.
   If the justices uphold the system, those defendants sentenced by
judges who refused to apply the new rules will have to be
resentenced. If the justices invalidate the system, those
defendants sentenced under the new rules will have to be
resentenced.
   The commission estimated that by Jan. 1, more than 10,000
federal court defendants will have been subjected to the new
sentencing system.
   Congress created the commission in the Sentencing Reform Act of
1984, legislation aimed at eliminating what some called unjustified
disparities in sentences.
   The law empowers the commission _ with its members appointed to
six-year terms by the president _ to tell federal judges what
sentences should be imposed for various crimes.
   The rules generally stiffened the prison time federal convicts
were required to serve. They also eliminated parole and curtailed
credit for good behavior.
   Morrison, representing a man who pleaded guilty in federal court
to conspiring to possess and distribute cocaine, argued that ``the
laying down of broad rules causes (the three commission member)
judges to be embroiled in political controversy.''
   ``Judges appointed for life must maintain their neutrality and
impartiality,'' Morris said.
   Fried acknowledged that having judges serve on the commission
raises certain ``policy concerns,'' but said those concerns ``have
no grounding as constitutional prohibitions.''
   Several members of the court, most persistently Justices Anthony
M. Kennedy and Antonin Scalia, asked Fried questions that appeared
to challenge his assertion of the commission's constitutionality.
   Representing the commission, Chicago lawyer Paul Bator said the
constitutionally required separation of the political branches does
not bar Congress from establishing an independent agency to make
laws about sentencing.
   He said Congress could give the Supreme Court the same authority
over federal sentencing without any constitutional violation.
   The test case before the justices stems from the prosecution of
John M. Mistretta, who pleaded guilty to conspiring to possess and
distribute cocaine after his arrest last year in Kansas City.
   Before Mistretta's sentence was imposed, he challenged the new
sentencing rules. A trial judge dismissed the challenge and
sentenced Mistretta to 18 months in prison, to be followed by a
three-year term of supervised release.
   Mistretta then appealed to the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, but the Supreme Court granted Fried's request that it
decide the constitutional issue while the case is pending before
the appeals court.
   The case is U.S. vs. Mistretta, 87-1904.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881005-0165 </DOCNO>
