<2ND_LINE>AM-Reading Raccoons,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Raccoon Family Shuts Down Library</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FTL1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DELRAY BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mother raccoon and her two babies
who fell through a library ceiling were back in their attic nest
Wednesday after spending a day browsing through the reference
section.
   The drop-in visitors, discovered Monday night when they set off
a burglar alarm, forced officials to close the library branch near
here Tuesday.
   A sheriff's deputy answering the alarm discovered the curious
family sitting on a desk among the literary reference books,
somewhere between Greek and Latin authors and the ``Critical Survey
of Long Fiction.''
   ``They seem to prefer history and the reference department,''
said circulation manager Carol Rouse. ``They read a better class of
literature than the average person.''
   The animals apparently had been nesting in the library for some
time before breaking through the ceiling tiles.
   On Tuesday night, animal control officials put a ladder covered
with burlap up to the hole in the ceiling to entice the mother, in
part because they believed she might have other babies still in the
roof.
   The strategy worked, and on Wednesday the library was open again
with the presumably well-informed raccoons roaming above the
ceiling, Ms. Rouse said.
</TEXT>
