<HEAD>House Votes for Recall of Lead-Lined Coolers, Production Ban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation to force the recall of lead-lined
water coolers and to ban the manufacture of coolers that are not
lead-free was passed Wednesday by the House and sent to the Senate.
   The bill, approved on a voice vote, would give the Consumer
Product Safety Commission a year to require manufacturers and
importers of lead-lined coolers to either repair, replace or give
refunds on such coolers.
   The proposal would authorize spending $90 million through 1992
for a grant program to assist schools to test for lead
contamination and replace drinking water plumbing containing lead.
   The bill also would authorize a three-year, $66 million program
of technical and grant assistance to detect and prevent lead
poisoning of children, who are more susceptible to poisoning than
adults.
