<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Berlin     10-05 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Berlin,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Says Soviets Take `Unconstructive Approach' On Berlin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department accused the Soviet Union
on Wednesday of taking an ``unconstructive approach'' on a proposal
by President Reagan to expand air links to West Berlin.
   ``They must understand that progress in East-West relations
cannot bypass Berlin,'' spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said. She did
not say whether the Soviets had actually turned Reagan down, but
she implied they had.
   ``The problem has much to do with differing interpretations of
the agreement governing the status of the city,'' said another U.S.
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The president, in a speech at the Berlin Wall on June 12, 1987,
urged the expansion of air service to Berlin and promotion of more
international conferences, youth exchanges and sporting events
there.
   The city, which was the capital of Nazi Germany in World War II,
has been administered since then by the four allied victors: the
United States, the Soviet Union, Britain and France.
   While Bonn is now the capital of West Germany, the three Western
countries keep trying to strengthen ties with West Berlin, which is
110 miles inside East Germany, a Soviet ally.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz has called repeatedly for
tearing down the Berlin Wall, which effectively separates East and
West.
   ``We are disappointed by the Soviets' unconstructive approach to
the initiative,'' Mrs. Oakley said. ``They must understand that
progress in East-West relations cannot bypass Berlin, and that
stability in and around the city can only be maintained over time
by taking steps to meet the legitimate aspirations of Berliners for
positive change.''
   She said the United States would continue to press for progress
on the initiative and its goals.
   ``I am not going to get into the details of their communication
this,'' the spokeswoman said of the Sept. 15 Soviet response.
``Obviously, we feel that it was not forthcoming. But we're going
to continue to press them on it.''
</TEXT>
