<1ST_LINE>u i AM-AlgerianRiots     10-05 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Algerian Riots,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rioters Take Over Downtown Algiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of youths rioting against
inflation virtually took over the capital's central district
Wednesday, setting cars ablaze and breaking shop windows while
police looked on, witnesses reported.
   The rioters, mostly schoolboys and university students, were
protesting a constantly increasing cost of living and consequent
reductions in real wages.
   Algeria has been hit by several strikes recently and new ones
were reported Wednesday at the offices of the carrier Air Algerie,
the post office and in various industries.
   Gangs of several hundred youngsters were seen overturning cars
and setting them afire on the main shopping streets, Didouche
Mourad and Mohamed Ben M'Hidi.
   They broke windows of shops and government-owned department
stores and attacked the information office of the Polisario
independence movement of the Western Sahara. Glass littered the
streets for well over a mile.
   One group of rioters stopped a bus, made the driver get out and
then broke all the windows, witnesses reported. The offices of the
West German airline Lufthansa and the Czechoslovak airline CSA were
wrecked, as were many shops that did not get their metal curtains
down quickly.
   At the Lufthansa office, counters were overturned, reservation
computers ripped out and documents scattered in the street.
   Rioters also invaded libraries, cafes and restaurants. A
nightclub called ``Blue Note'' was destroyed.
   About 100 young rioters brought bottles from inside the club and
used them as projectiles. Others carried the furniture from the
government's National Publicity Agency and set fire to it front of
the central post office.
   Security forces did little to stop the rampage, but several
vehicles carrying riot police with tear gas launchers took
positions at midday around the main Air Algerie office near the
lower end of Didouche Mourad. It office was not damaged.
   Young people were seen hurling stones at small groups of police
in side streets.
   Workers who struck an auto parts factory in late September said
they had not had a raise in years. Their strike led to a
confrontation with police.
   Employees of the plant earn the equivalent of $270-$330 a month
while many prices have soared because of new government economic
policies intended to ``rationalize consumption'' and encourage
production.
   Bread is subsidized and still sells for about 17 cents, but beef
costs nearly $12 a pound.
   Strikers and protesters also complain of shortages. Butter, for
example, has not been available for about a month.
   President Chadli Bendjedid says the reforms are necessary but
his government announced Tuesday in conjunction with the General
Union of Algerian Workers, the country's only labor union, that an
effort would be made to provide more staples at lower prices.
</TEXT>
