<HEAD>State Wants To Make Grand Jury Report Public</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state is expected to ask a judge
Thursday to make public a grand jury's investigation of the Tawana
Brawley case that reportedly concludes the black teen-ager lied
when she said she was kidnapped and raped by six whites.
   Attorney General Robert Abrams likely will go before state
Supreme Court Justice Angelo J. Ingrassia asking that he release
the grand jury report, Gary Fryer, a spokesman for Gov. Mario
Cuomo, said. In New York, the Supreme Court is the trial-level
court.
   Lanie Accles, spokeswoman for Abrams, said she had no comment on
any anticipated actions by the grand jury.
   The New York Times reported last month that the grand jury
concluded overwhelming evidence indicates the 16-year-old former
Wappingers Falls girl made up the story, perhaps to avoid
punishment for late nights out.
   Miss Brawley was found Nov. 28, 1987, her body smeared with
excrement and racial slurs. She claimed she had been held captive
and raped, but the teen-ager and her family refused to cooperate
with investigators, saying they couldn't get justice from the legal
system.
   Miss Brawley and her advisers denounced the Times report and
denied that she had staged the incident.
