<HEAD>Bill To Protect Rights of Senate Workers Introduced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation to extend to Senate staffers the
same protection against job discrimination that most American
workers received 24 years ago was introduced Wednesday by Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz.
   The bill is similar to a measure approved by the House for its
employees on Tuesday.
   The House voted 408-12 to give the protections of the Civil
Rights Act of 1964 to the 12,137 people who work for House members,
committees or in various Capitol offices.
   It means that discrimination on the basis of race, color,
national origin, religion, sex, handicap or age will be illegal in
the House.
   In introducing the Senate bill, McCain said such action was
``long, long, overdue.''
   ``For too long, the Senate has operated under different rules
from other employers,'' McCain said. ``For too long, the Senate has
exempted itself from rules regarding discrimination. We need to ask
ourselves some questions: Are we fair to our employees? Is it
really fair for them not to have the same safeguards that all other
citizens throughout the country enjoy?''
