<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-FederalInformation     10-05 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Federal Information,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Urges Better Information Systems for Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The spread of electronic data systems poses
the need for Congress to improve the way the government distributes
information, the congressional Office of Technology Assessment said
Wednesday.
   The report said existing laws and the government's methods for
information dissemination, established by Congress largely during
the pre-electronic era, have been overtaken by technology.
   ``The government is at a crucial point where opportunities
presented by the information technologies, such as productivity and
cost-effectiveness improvements, are substantial,'' the agency said.
   Bibliographic, reference, statistical and scientific and
technical information produced by the federal government is
particularly well-suited to electronic formats.
   But the major federal information systems _ the Government
Printing Office document sales program, the Depository Library
Program and the National Technical Information Service _ are
limited largely to paper and microfiche.
   Full use of electronic technologies could help these agencies,
OTA said.
   ``What OTA tells us in their report is that the methods we
depend on to transmit information have reached their limits, and
that new technologies are waiting to change the way government
communicates,'' said Rep. Robert Roe, D-N.J., chairman of the House
Committee on Science, Space and Technology.
</TEXT>
