<DOCNO> AP881005-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 2019EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-GulfTalks     10-05 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Gulf Talks,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Sources Say Iran Agrees To Stop Searching Ships In Persian
Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran has agreed to stop searching ships in
international waters of the Persian Gulf which it suspects of
carrying war cargo to Iraq, sources in the United Nations said
Wednesday.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, also said Iraq
agreed to postpone discussing ownership of the disputed
Shatt-al-Arab waterway, Iraq's only outlet to the gulf. Iran has a
long gulf coastline with numerous ports.
   Breakthroughs on these two issues could help end the stalemate
in the Iran-Iraq peace talks that began Aug. 25 in Geneva. The two
neighbors in the oil-rich gulf, at war for eight years, agreed on
Aug. 20 to a U.N.-sponsored truce.
   The sources said U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
proposed the compromises during talks that began last week with the
foreign ministers of Iran and Iraq. Those talks ended Wednesday.
   Under the proposals, Iran will no longer stop vessels flying a
neutral flag in international gulf waters and the Strait of Hormuz,
and Iraq consented to discuss its claims to Shatt-al-Arab later in
the negotiations, the sources said.
   Both parties will begin arranging a withdrawal of their forces
to the internationally recognized border and will discuss
repatriation of prisoners of war, they added.
   No announcement of the compromise will be issued until peace
talks resume in Geneva later this month because Iraq wants to wait
and see if Tehran honors the agreement, the sources said.
   In addition, Perez de Cuellar and the Iranian and Iraqi
diplomats agreed not to discuss details of their talks while
progress is being made in negotiations between their lower-ranked
representatives.
   Iraq's insistence that Shatt-al-Arab be cleared of sunken ships
and dredged to remove silt has blocked progress in the talks.
   To be taken up later in the peace talks is the issue of whether
both nations share rights to the waterway under a 1975 treaty or
whether Iraq has sovereignty over the whole passage and both its
banks, the sources reported.
   Baghdad also complained that Iran's searching of ships for
Iraq-bound war cargo violated a U.N. Security Council resolution
calling for the parties to ``discontinue all military activities on
land, at sea and in the air.''
   Iran held that searching for war cargo was a right that nations
at war generally are recognized to have.
   The Iran-Iraq war broke out in September 1980 when Iraqi forces
invaded western Iran after weeks of border skirmishes.
   More than 1 million casualties are estimated to have resulted
from the war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881005-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 2020EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Egypt-Parade     10-05 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-Parade,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Egypt Holds First Military Parade Since Sadat Assassination</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CAI2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. MANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egypt marked the 15th anniversary of the
last Middle East war Wednesday with its first military parade since
President Anwar Sadat was assassinated in 1981.
   President Hosni Mubarak, Sadat's vice president and successor,
watched from an elevated viewing box.
   On Oct. 6, 1981, Mubarak stood beside Sadat when Moslem
extremists bolted from a truck and sprayed the ground-level
reviewing stand with bullets that felled the president.
   Sadat and seven others died in attack led by an army lieutenant.
Twenty-eight people were wounded, but Mubarak was unhurt.
   On Wednesday, only Mubarak, his ministers, diplomats and other
officials were allowed into the suburban Military College to watch
the parade, which was televised and broadcast on radio.
   Earlier, Mubarak laid a wreath at Sadat's tomb and that of Gamal
Abdel Nasser, leader of the 1952 coup that ended the Egyptian
monarchy. Sadat was an army lieutenant colonel in Nasser's Free
Officers, who were responsible for the coup.
   In a videotaped speech broadcast before the wreath-laying,
Mubarak praised Sadat as a hero for engineering the surprise attack
on Israel that began the 1973 war and for signing a peace treaty
with the Jewish state six years later.
   Wednesday's parade mainly celebrated the military exploits of
the 1973 conflict.
   In Sadat's time, the annual military parade would fill one of
metropolitan Cairo's largest streets with tanks, artillery and men.
In Wednesday's parade, tanks, missiles and other heavy weapons
passed the reviewing stand on truck-drawn trailers.
   Since Sadat's death, Egypt's annual commemoration of the 1973
war has been limited to a televised speech by Mubarak on Oct. 6,
the anniversary of the capture of Israeli positions in the occupied
Sinai Peninsula that constituted Egypt's only success in four wars
with Israel.
   No explanation was given for either the decision to have a
parade this year or moving the celebration forward a day.
   The Oct. 6 parade became a tradition under Sadat, who watched
the displays dressed in a resplendent military uniform. On the day
he died, Sadat wore a white, gold-braided uniform with high boots.
   Mubarak, a former fighter pilot, was dressed in an air force
uniform on that day.
   It was his last public appearance in military uniform. On
Wednesday, he wore a blue suit and mirrored sunglasses.
