<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Romania     10-05 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Romania,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Cautions Romania's Ceausescu on Maverick Policies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev cautioned visiting
Romanian leader Nicolae Ceausescu on Wednesday that his maverick
policies may discredit socialism and the entire East bloc.
   Gorbachev, who has headed the Soviet Communist Party since 1985,
said, ``The notion of socialism will be formed on the basis of
evaluating the combined experience of socialist nations. The
success of each of them will be a common ideological achievement.
But the failure of any can, alas, mean a common setback too.''
   In reply, Ceausescu lauded the ``traditions of cooperation and
revolutionary solidarity'' between his country and the Soviet
Union, but asserted Romania's right to chart its own political
course.
   ``One should always bear in mind the fact that the revolutionary
process is unfolding in each country in different conditions,''
Ceausescu, who heads Romania's Communist Party, said.
   Their remarks at a Kremlin luncheon were reported by the
official Soviet news agency Tass. Ceausescu, accompanied by his
wife Elena and by Romanian officials, arrived in Moscow on Tuesday
for talks with the Soviets.
   Ceausescu has balked at following Gorbachev's social and
economic reform program, known by its Russian-language name of
``perestroika'' or restructuring.
   Gorbachev noted that ``all the socialist countries have their
own distinctive features,'' but said common action by the Soviet
Union and its allies was necessary.
   ``It is the initiative and identity shown by each fraternal
country in its contribution to achieving the objectives of their
concerted policies that broaden the range of socialism's influence
on international processes,'' he said.
   Gorbachev also made a pitch for his own economic, political and
social reforms, which he said were becoming part of Soviet life,
although not as fast as had been hoped.
   ``We see this as the best proof that perestroika will definitely
succeed,'' he said.
   Ceausescu has stirred a storm of protest in Hungary and
elsewhere over his plan to raze up to 7,000 villages, including
about 800 ethnic Hungarian communities, and resettle the population
in so-called agro-industrial centers.
   Romania has also drawn fire for stalling the 35-nation review
Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe in Vienna over
human rights provisions to be included in a final document.
   Gorbachev did not refer directly to those disputes, but
mentioned the need for ``respect for the rights and freedoms of
each citizen,'' and for ``the observance of legality and of the
rule of law.''
   On his visit to Romania in May 1987, Gorbachev implicitly
criticized in a televised speech the nepotism and personality cult
Ceausescu promotes in that country.
   He also demanded higher-quality goods to be delivered from
Romania, where widespread food and energy shortages make life
difficult for the country's 25 million people.
   Ceausescu admitted in a speech Monday that Romanian industry has
failed to meet export targets for this year.
   One issue likely to be discussed during Ceausescu's visit is
Romania's desire to obtain more Soviet crude oil and raw materials
in return for Romanian wheat, meat and agricultural products.
</TEXT>
