<HEAD>Misdemeanor Charges Filed Against Cher's Boyfriend</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 8-9, `Brandt and ..., to UPDATE with quote from
Brandt and CORRECT possible punishment for malicious mischief
counts.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cher's boyfriend was charged with reckless
driving and malicious mischief Wednesday over a confrontation June
27 in which his car crashed into a photographer's outside the home
he shares with the actress.
   The misdemeanor offenses are less serious than the felony charge
of assault with a deadly weapon on which Rob Camilletti, 24, was
booked.
   ``There was insufficient evidence of any attempt of assault,
based on the statements of witnesses,'' said Mike Qualls, spokesman
for the City Attorney's office.
   Camilletti was driving Cher's black Ferrari when it hit a car
belonging to Peter Brandt, a photographer for the entertainment
tabloid Star. Camilletti was released on $2,000 bail.
   The bagel maker and aspiring actor said he lost control of his
car while trying to swerve into the driveway to avoid the
photographers. Brandt accused Camilletti of trying to kill him and
sued the couple for unspecified damages.
   ``I'm very pleased that the city attorney understood that I
never tried to hit the tabloid photographer,'' Camiletti said in a
statement. ``It's true that I broke the guy's camera and telephone
after the accident, and I intend to reimburse him for that.''
   ``With this decision not to file any felony charges, I am now
hopeful that Cher and I can get back to some degree of normalcy
with our lives,'' Camilletti said.
   ``I think he should have been charged with assault with a deadly
weapon. No, I'm not pleased with these charges,'' said Brandt. ``I
guess the city attorney thought it was an accident. But I'm glad
they filed something.''
   Reckless driving carries up to 90 days in jail and a $1,000
fine, and the two counts of malicious mischief could bring up to 18
months in jail and $6,000 in fines.
