<HEAD>Fire Forces Evacuations At Oklahoma Memorial Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire sparked by a welder's torch spread
smoke through three floors of a hospital building Wednesday,
forcing the evacuation of about 50 outpatients. No one was injured
in the fire, authorities said.
   The evacuated patients were moved to another hospital building
or onto buses, while nurses, doctors and staff waited outside, many
of them wrapped in white hospital blankets to fend off the cold and
an intermittent drizzle.
   Only the basement and first and second floors of Everett Tower,
the main building of Oklahoma Memorial Hospital, had to be
evacuated, said hospital spokeswoman Kathy Kirk. The lowest floor
on which patients are housed is the fourth floor, she said.
   A welder's torch ignited insulation in a ceiling around an
elevator shaft in the building's southeast corner, and the smoke
spread quickly, setting off alarms, said fire department spokesman
Jon Hansen.
