<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Explosions In Cape Town and Johannesburg Suburbs; Activist
Controlled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Explosions damaged two court
buildings Wednesday night in suburbs of Cape Town and Johannesburg,
police reported.
   They said one was hurt in the blast outside Cape Town and there
were no immediate reports of injuries in the Johannesburg explosion.
   In another development, an organization opposed to the military
draft said police put tight restrictions on its leader Wednesday.
   The first of the two explosions occurred shortly after 7 p.m. at
the Stellenbosch Magistrates Court about 25 miles east of Cape
Town, police said. The second took place about two hours later at
the Alexandra Magistrates Court in a small business district that
separates the impoverished black township of Alexandra from
affluent white suburbs of Johannesburg.
   Police did not give details of damage to either building or the
cause of the explosions.
   At least 148 bombings have taken place in South Africa since the
government declared a nationwide state of emergency June 12, 1986,
including a record 29 in September.
   President P.W. Botha's government has blamed virtually all of
them on the the outlawed African National Congress, the main
guerrilla group fighting white domination.
   Anti-apartheid activists suggest, howeer, that recent attacks on
anti-apartheid groups and public facilities frequented mostly by
blacks were the work of right-wing whites.
   The End Conscription Campaign said its national secretary,
Alastair Teeling-Smith, was ordered not to speak with journalists,
prepare material for publication or attend any gathering convened
for the purpose of criticizing government policy.
   He and his organization oppose the mandatory military service
required of white South African men. It has appealed unsuccessfully
for alternative non-military service for men politically or morally
opposed to joining the army.
   Military service for other race groups is voluntary.
   Teeling-Smith's group was banned Aug. 22, three weeks after 143
white males _ including doctors, lawyers and scientists _
publically announced their refusal of military service.
</TEXT>
