<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Student'sSuit     10-05 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Student's Suit,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Fails Test, Sues School for MBA Degree</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A student who failed an economics test
twice but made good class grades is suing the University of Central
Florida to either receive a master's degree in business
administration or get her $5,000 tuition back.
   ``After paying all my dues and having a good average, I just
feel abused,'' said Nora Roth, 48. ``I really don't want their
money. I just want what I earned, which is a master's degree.''
   The dean of the school's College of Business, Clifford Eubanks,
defended the test format that requires students to review all the
material they have learned: finance, management, marketing and
economics.
   After passing the three other parts of the test, Mrs. Roth
failed the economics section. She hired a tutor, crammed for
another semester and took the test again but failed once more.
   Mrs. Roth, who commuted 100 miles round-trip for two years from
Cocoa Beach to the Orlando school for classes, filed suit last week
with the help of her husband, Kenneth, who is a lawyer.
   She alleged the test is unfair because each of the business
school's economics professors hold different theories and place
emphasis on different facets of the subject. Her test was prepared
by a professor she did not study under and included material she
had never studied, she contended.
   Eubanks said Tuesday the comprehensive test is common at
colleges across the country.
   Most of the school's MBA candidates are part-time students,
Eubanks said, and they spend up to five years earning the degree. A
comprehensive test ensures that students retain the material they
learned at the beginning, he said.
   Eubanks said it was not uncommon for students to fail the test
several times and that Mrs. Roth can take it again.
</TEXT>
