<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Crime     10-05 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Crime,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Soviet Rape Every Hour, One Murder Every 90 Minutes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the Soviet Union a theft is committed every 40
seconds on the average, one rape every hour and a premeditated
murder every 90 minutes, the government newspaper Izvestia reported
Wednesday.
   Izvestia made the figures public in an article marking the 70th
anniversary of the Ministry of Interior's Criminal Investigation
Department, in charge of tracking down crime suspects.
   Under President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's campaign for
``glasnost,'' or openness, more is becoming known about crime _ a
subject once virtually taboo in the state-run media.
   As one example, Radio Moscow revealed in March that 9,000 people
were murdered in the country in 1987.
   Extrapolating from the figures printed by Izvestia, which the
paper said came from the Criminal Investigation Department, 2,160
thefts, 24 rapes and 16 murders take place in the Soviet Union on
an average day.
   On a yearly basis, that would total 788,400 thefts, 8,760 rapes
and 5,840 premeditated murders for the nation as a whole.
   Detailed crime incidence reports are still not made public in
the Soviet Union, but officials in Moscow maintain that violent
crime is far less of a problem than in the United States. They cite
the small number of privately owned firearms as one major reason.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
