<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MarijuanaTreatment     10-05 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marijuana Treatment,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Glaucoma Patient Complains of Slow Pot Permission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A glaucoma patient here complains she is
going blind waiting for permission to legally use marijuana, and a
federal official acknowledged Wednesday that the application
procedure is complicated.
   Elvy Musikka was tried in August on charges of growing marijuana
plants in her back yard. She and her physician successfully argued
that using the drug was the only way to relieve glaucoma's pressure
on her eyes.
   After her arrest, she applied to the Food and Drug
Administration for a federal program to receive pot legally for
medical treatments.
   That was six months ago. Tuesday she said she is already blind
in the right eye, and slowly losing the remaining sight in her left
eye waiting for her application to be processed.
   Faye Peterson, a spokeswoman for the FDA in Washington, said by
law she cannot discuss details of Ms. Musikka's case. But she noted
that even the Drug Enforcement Administration is involved in
clearing applications.
   ``It not only involves this agency, it involves the DEA and the
National Institute on Drug Abuse,'' she said. ``It's not just a
simple matter of saying, `FDA, give us permission.'''
   Appearing with Ms. Mussika at her news conference was
stockbroker Irvin Rosenfeld, who suffers from a rare disease that
causes tumors to grow in his bones. Marijuana enhances the
medication he takes and helps ease the pain. He is one of only two
Broward residents permitted to use the drug legally.
   ``I know how many hours it takes to fill out the paperwork,''
said Rosenfeld. ``This is how they put me off for 5{ years.''
   Since her acquittal by Broward Circuit Judge Mark Polen, Ms.
Musikka said she has been getting marijuana when she can from
friends. It's either that or lose her remaining sight, she said.
   ``Anyone that's helping me now is breaking the law,'' she said.
``They're human people, compassionate people who care.''
   Bob Randall is president of the Alliance for Cannabis
Therapeutics, a Washington-based organization that helps people
legally get marijuana for medical purposes.
   ``We are publicly watching a human being go blind because of an
unresponsive federal government,'' said Randall, who won the legal
right to use marijuana to treat his glaucoma 12 years ago.
   He said it could take a lawsuit against the FDA to force action
on Ms. Mussika's application.
   Ms. Musikka was born with congenital cataracts and developed
glaucoma as she grew up. Glaucoma, the leading cause of blindness
in the United States, increases pressure on the eyeball and optic
nerve and causes a progressive loss of sight.
</TEXT>
