<2ND_LINE>AM-Baldwin Sterilization,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Sterilized To Get Lenience In Sentencing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Indianapolis woman facing sentencing for
neglect in the death of her four-year-old son was sterilized to
gain a judge's leniency, her half-brother said Wednesday.
   Melody S. Baldwin, 29, underwent the procedure Tuesday at
Wishard Memorial Hospital. Marion Superior Court Judge Roy E. Jones
had suggested he would be lenient with Baldwin if she were no
longer capable of having more children.
   ``She didn't like it, but said she wanted to do it, mainly to
cooperate with the court,'' James D. Slagle said following a bond
hearing for Baldwin.
   Baldwin gave birth to a son Sunday and gave him up for adoption,
defense attorney Michael J. Donahoe said.
   She pleaded guilty June 10 to neglect of a dependent and, in
exchange, prosecutors dropped a murder charge. The charges said she
``knowingly administered'' lethal doses of two psychotropic drugs
to her son 4-year-old son, Joshua, between Aug. 28 and Sept. 3,
1986.
   She faces a maximum sentence of 20 years in prison. Jones
granted a defense motion Wednesday to reinstate a $5,000 bond for
Baldwin and set sentencing for Nov. 9.
   Slagle said he felt his half-sister is not guilty of neglect and
said she entered into the plea agreement because she was
``threatened'' with the possibility of a 20- to 50-year prison term
on the murder charge.
