<1ST_LINE>u p AM-DebateRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0707 10-05 0901</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Debate Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0707,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle, Bentsen Take Center Stage in Veep Debate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with new polls, INSERT four grafs after 13th pvs,
Polls have...the ticket, and to UPDATE with new ads, ADD two grafs;
debate begins 8:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Dan Quayle and Democrat Lloyd
Bentsen prepared Wednesday for their prime-time debate, each man
eager to aid his presidential ticket and trade in his Senate seat
for the vice presidency.
   Debate sponsors looked for a television audience in the
millions, presidential standardbearers George Bush and Michael
Dukakis among them.
   For the 67-year-old Bentsen and the 41-year-old Quayle, the
stakes couldn't be higher in a presidential campaign that remained
too close to call. One poll suggested that the Indiana senator's
presence on the Republican ticket was working against Bush.
   Republicans hoped Quayle could reassure voters that he has the
maturity and qualifications to serve as vice president. Democrats
looked to Bentsen to attract undecided moderate and conservative
Democrats to Dukakis' side.
   Bentsen and Quayle both spent the day in final preparations,
taking a close look at the stage where they would face off for
their 90-minute televised encounter.
   ``We're ready,'' said Quayle. ``You're going to see Dan Quayle
as he really is.''
   Bentsen said he was ``feeling great.'' Asked what he would try
to accomplish in the debate, he replied simply, ``Win.''
   The 10,000-seat Omaha Civic Auditorium was condensed into a
2,000-seat theater decorated in red, white and blue for the debate.
Just 100 of the seats were available to the public, the rest
reserved by the campaigns.
   The two camps flew dozens of high-profile supporters to Omaha to
provide immediate post-debate partisan analysis of the encounter,
including many Senate colleagues of Bentsen and Quayle.
   Bush, campaigning in Colorado, declared he was ``not worried a
bit'' about Quayle's performance. Dukakis spent the day at the
Statehouse in Boston and said the public would see ``a very strong,
thoughtful, mature Senator Lloyd Bentsen,'' a slap at Quayle's
youthfulness.
   The vice presidential confrontation was the second of three
planned debates in the fall campaign. Dukakis and Bush squared off
late last month in North Carolina and are expected to meet again
late next week at a site to be determined, probably Los Angeles.
   With the Republicans owning a slight edge in the polls in the
race for the White House, Quayle was hoping to use the debate to
reassure the voters that his youth is not a liability. Bentsen and
the Democrats have sought to depict the Indiana senator as an
inexperienced young man ill-equipped to be a heartbeat away from
the presidency.
   Polls have indicated Quayle is a drag on the Republican ticket.
A CBS poll released earlier in the week suggested that Bush had a
slightly larger lead over Dukakis when voters were queried only
about the top of the ticket.
   A pair of surveys released Wednesday reiterated those concerns.
An ABC News-Washington Post survey conducted from Sept. 28 through
Tuesday put the race at 51-44, with the Republican ticket in the
numerical lead.
   A Harris poll, conducted last week, gave the Republican ticket a
49-46 lead.
   However, the ABC-Post survey showed that 40 percent of the
people believed Quayle to be qualified to become vice president,
compared with 67 percent for Bentsen. The Harris survey said a
third believed Quayle to be qualified to be president if that
became necessary, and Bentsen beat Quayle 59-37 when voters were
asked their preference for vice president.
   The ABC-Post survey of 1,196 had an error margin of about four
points. The Harris survey Sept. 24-29 of 1,235 likely voters had an
error margin of three points.
   While Quayle's youth and his Vietnam-era service in the National
Guard have made him a controversial candidate, Bentsen has had to
fend off questions about the numerous differences between his own
moderate views and those of Dukakis.
   Quayle has said he was eager to prove himself to the viewing
voters.
   ``The American people don't know me,'' he said Tuesday as he
traveled to Omaha with a host of top Bush strategists, including
media adviser Roger Ailes. ``They have a lot of questions .... They
don't have any details of who Dan Quayle is.''
   Both men prepared carefully for the encounter, reading thick
briefing books, enduring sessions with their handlers and
participating in mock debates.
   Oregon Republican Sen. Bob Packwood played the role of Bentsen
in Quayle's practice sessions. Rep. Dennis Eckart of Ohio played
the role of Quayle for Bentsen's workouts.
   While presidential debates have become more or less a familiar
landmark on the campaign trail, televised vice presidential
encounters are rare.
   Only two previous such confrontations have been held, the first
one in 1976 between Democrat Walter F. Mondale and GOP Bob Dole,
and the second one four years ago between Bush and Democrat
Geraldine Ferraro.
   As the two vice presidential candidates squared off, the ad wars
continued.
   A new set of 30-second Dukakis ads to be aired nationally
starting Wednesday made a more direct attack on Bush and his record
on drug enforcement, education, the environment and Social
Security. The four ads said the administration dealt secretly with
Manuel Antonio Noriega, ``the Panamanian drug lord,'' Bush
``personally'' weakened environmental regulations, ``personally''
cast the tie-breaking vote to cut Social Security'' and ``sat by
while college loans for working families were cut.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
