<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0705 10-05 0698</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0705,0716</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Soldiers Injured By Firebomb, Arab Dies Of Wounds</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with 14 Palestinians wounded. Pickup 2nd graf pvs
`Jerusalem police...'; INSERTS 1 graf after 9th `The detainees...'
to UPDATE with religious leader detained and SUBS 16th `In the...'
with 2 with details of shootings</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers shot and wounded 14
Palestinians in street clashes Wednesday, Arab hospital officials
said, and the army reported two soldiers injured when a firebomb
hit their jeep in the occupied West Bank.
   Jerusalem police made a house-to-house searches of two Arab
neighborhoods for the second day in a row, looking for suspected
rioters, police spokesman Alex Lapidot said.
   The sweep, involving 150 policemen, was one of the largest in
Jerusalem since the Palestinian uprising began last Dec. 8.
   Nitham Abu Hawelah, 23, of the West Bank's Balata refugee camp,
died Wednesday after being hit by nine bullets in a clash with
troops more than a week ago, officials at Jerusalem's Mukassad
Hospital said.
   The fatality brought to 281 the number of Palestinians killed in
the uprising in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, which Israel seized
from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war. Six Israelis
also have died in the violence.
   An army spokesman said the two soldiers were hit by a firebomb
as they drove through Tulkarem. Israel television reported that one
trooper suffered moderate to serious burns while the other was
lightly injured.
   The army put a curfew on Tulkarem and started to comb the area.
   At least 14 people were arrested in Abu Tor and Silwan on the
southern outskirts of Jerusalem, and a police crackdown which
started late Tuesday was to continue until Thursday, police and
Israel television said.
   The detainees ``are suspected of participating in stone-throwing
incidents and other disturbances,'' Lapidot said.
   Among those arrested in Jerusalem was Ibrahim Hamde, a preacher
at Al Aqsa mosque, one of the holiest shrines of Islam. Israel
radio called him a radical religious leader and said he was
suspected of distributing underground leaflets.
   Silwan and the Arab sector Abu Tor have been major trouble spots
since the Palestinian uprising began. Both are part of Arab east
Jerusalem, which Israel annexed after the 1967 Middle East war.
   Lapidot said police also were searching for tax evaders in the
two neighborhoods. Underground leaders of the Palestinian uprising
have called on their followers to stop paying taxes to the Israeli
authorities.
   About a dozen Arabs were hustled out of their homes in pajamas
and handed court summonses for tax evasion, reporters at the scene
said.
   Troops shot and wounded nine Arabs, including an 11-year-old boy
and three teen-agers, in clashes in the West Bank city of Nablus,
Arab hospital officials said. One of the wounded, 16-year-old Jihad
Dib, was shot in the head and listed in critical condition at
Mukassad Hospital.
   The military command confirmed five casualties and said it was
investigating the other reports.
   In Balata, news of Hawelah's death sparked a stone-throwing riot
and the army clamped a curfew on the camp's 12,000 residents.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip's Beach refugee camp, soldiers
wounded five Arabs, three of them teenagers, Arab hospital
officials said.
   They said an 18-year-old was hit in the eye by a plastic bullet.
The army said it was checking the reports.
   Israeli troops detained Naela Ayesh, 28, a Palestinian employee
of the U.S.-based Save the Children organization in Gaza City, army
officials said. They gave no reason for the arrest.
   In another development, army Chief of Staff Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron
defended the use of plastic bullets at a closed-door meeting of the
parliamentary Defense and Foreign Affairs Committee, Israel radio
and newspapers reported.
   Shomron was quoted as saying the army was using the bullets to
stop riots before they got out of hand and to prevent fatalities.
   But the figures he presented seemed to contradict his claim.
Shomron told the legislators that in the last three weeks, since
the massive use of plastic bullets began, 11 Palestinians have been
killed and 267 wounded, compared with the previous three weeks in
which 10 Arabs were killed and 137 wounded.
</TEXT>
