<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Lawless-Hostages 1stLd-Writethru a0750 10-05 0792</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lawless-Hostages, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0750,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business Executive Denies Negotiating With Iranians on Hostages</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 16th graf pvs bgng, `Gregg, however,' to
UPDATE with New York Times report on Lawless' CIA job</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Hostages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former State Department employee denied
emphatically Wednesday an Iranian opposition leader's assertion
that he was involved in negotiating a release of American hostages
in Lebanon.
   In a statement released by the co-owner of his trade and
investment consulting firm here, Richard Lawless said: ``I
categorically deny and state for the record that I am involved
either directly or indirectly in any discussions or negotiations''
on the nine hostages.
   Former Iranian President Abolhassan Bani-Sadr said Tuesday in
Paris that Lawless had negotiated in behalf of Vice President
George Bush with a representative of Iranian Parliament Speaker
Hashemi Rafsanjani, in an attempt to get American hostages
liberated.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater and State Department
spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley both denied that anyone had been engaged
in such negotiations with Iranians or Iranian government figures
under U.S. auspices or that Lawless is a government employee.
   ``He's not operating under our instruction or direction or
anything like that,'' Fitzwater said of Lawless. ``What is private
status is, I don't know.''
   Lawless was in his office Wednesday, but Therese Shaheen, a
co-owner of the business, spoke on his behalf in an interview.
   She said they felt Lawless' reputation ``had been harmed'' by
Bani-Sadr's allegations made after hostage Mithileshwar Singh, an
Indian-born U.S. resident, was released from 20 months of captivity
by pro-Iranian forces.
   Lawless said in the statement that ``I have never in my entire
life had any direct or indirect contact with any Iranian government
officials or any Iranian nationals claiming to represent the
Iranian government or any Iranian-related interests.''
   Bani-Sadr had said Lawless was attempting to negotiate the
release of the hostages on Bush's behalf. Last week, an Israeli
newspaper, The Nation, said U.S. government officials were engaged
in secret talks with Iranians in Geneva aimed at setting the
hostages free and improving relations between the United States and
Iran.
   Bani-Sadr also said a shipment of arms furnished by the United
States was destined for Iran.
   ``Those charges are not true,'' Fitzwater said. ``Bani-Sadr is
full of beans.''
   President Reagan and other administration officials have
repeatedly denied that any such direct talks are taking place, or
have taken place.
   Lawless, president of the consulting firm, U.S.-Asia, also said,
``I deny that I have any active relationship with anyone on the
staff of Vice President Bush or the Bush campaign organization
which relates in any way to this or any similar issue.''
   ``I have maintained this position in numerous discussions,'' he
said.
   Lawless worked for the CIA at the U.S. Embassy in Seoul, South
Korea, between 1973 and 1975, the same years that Bush's national
security adviser, Donald Gregg, served for the CIA at that mission,
The Washington Times reported Wednesday.
   Gregg, however, has seen Lawless fewer than a half-dozen times
since 1975, and only in social settings, the newspaper quoted its
sources as saying.
   The New York Times, which also reported Wednesday that Lawless
had served in the U.S. Embassy in South Korea when Gregg was there,
quoted an unidentified former government official that Lawless had
worked in the CIA's operations directorate until several years ago.
   Spokesmen for Bush, the Republican presidential nominee, have
said that Lawless has no relationship with Bush or with the
election campaign.
   ``We never confirm or deny CIA allegations of employment,'' said
Bill Devine, a spokesman for the intelligence agency.
   Ms. Shaheen said that ``we showed Richard's passport, plane
tickets and so forth'' in an attempt to dissuade CBS News from
reporting his purported activities on behalf of the hostages, but
the network broadcast the report earlier this week.
   ``He couldn't possibly have been there'' taking part in any
discussions about the hostages, she said of Lawless. ``So Bani-Sadr
said he (Lawless) knows a couple people in the Bush campaign. ...
It was like, two and two make a thousand. ... We think it is
politically inspired by Iran.''
   Lawless is a former State Department employee, who was described
as an area analyst beginning in June 1972. He went to Seoul in
1973, according to a biographic register published by the
department.
   Ms. Shaheen said Lawless also had assignments at the U.S.
embassies in Vienna and Tokyo before founding the consulting
business.
   ``Primarily our business is in the Far East,'' she said, ``90
percent of it.''
   ``The story here is, why are the Iranians fabricating this
story,'' she said. ``Because that is the story here because they
have nothing to prove'' their allegations.
   ``It's the biggest hoax since ... whatever,'' she said.
</TEXT>
