<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma     10-05 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Looters Reported Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military street patrols killed seven more
looters in Rangoon and Mandalay, bringing the number of people
slain since the Sept. 18 military coup to about 440, the state
radio reported Wednesday.
   Rangoon radio said the shootings occurred Tuesday. It and other
official media have described most of those killed since the coup
as looters or other ``destructive elements.''
   Soldiers are imposing strict rules against public gatherings and
looting. Vendors, gamblers and others who once crowded the
sidewalks of Rangoon have disappeared.
   Civil servants and factory workers reported to their jobs for
the third day but many left by early afternoon, apparently because
of a lack of work in ministries and state enterprises crippled by a
long general strike. All government employees were ordered back to
work Monday under threat of dismissal.
   Two new youth organizations, the People's Youth Federation and
the All Burma United Youth Organizations, registered as political
parties Wednesday with a commission that is to supervise elections.
The political leanings of the two groups were not immediately known.
   Three main opposition political parties have registered _ the
Democracy Party, National League for Democracy and People's
Democracy Party _ but have not said whether they will participate
in the elections.
   Burma's most powerful party, widely believed to be backed by the
new government, has not registered because of its ``complicated
position,'' party sources said Wednesday.
   The National Unity Party, under another name, was the only legal
party for 26 years of repressive military rule and operated with
government funds. It has been ordered to divest itself of
government assets like all other parties.
   Party sources said this would prove difficult because the
organization, formerly called the Burma Socialist Program Party,
had substantial holdings in real estate and other fixed assets
acquired all or in part from government funding.
   Under a Sept. 27 decree, political parties that use state funds,
vehicles and other property cannot apply for registration.
Financing for the Burma Socialist Program Party included $10
million to $13.3 million annually in government funds.
   Western diplomats say Gen. Saw Maung and his new government back
the National Unity Party but are observing legal requirements in an
attempt to quiet anti-government feelings.
</TEXT>
