<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 2048EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FatherShot     10-05 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Father Shot,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>3-year-old Boy Cleared in Shooting Death of Father</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 3-year-old boy who shot and killed his father
as the man beat the child's mother said afterward he would have
done it again.
   ``I killed him,'' the boy reportedly said afterward. ``Now he's
dead. If he would have hit my mother, I would have shot him again.''
   Prosecutors said Tuesday they won't take any legal measures
against the child, who wasn't identified, because he couldn't have
acted intentionally.
   ``We feel that this is an act that a 3-year-old cannot
contemplate,'' Ron Schigur, head of the Wayne County Prosecutor's
Office juvenile division said Tuesday. ``I mean, he can't form any
kind of intent. ...
   ``There just doesn't seem to be any reason to pursue it.''
   The boy's mother, who spoke Tuesday on condition neither she nor
her son be identified, said, ``It was an accident; it just
happened.''
   The boy, now 4, shot and killed Sherwood Cannon, 47, on June 18.
The decision on what to do about the case was delayed pending the
results of toxicology tests, said assistant prosecutor David Wolock.
   The tests showed Cannon had a blood alcohol level of 0.08
percent at the time of the shooting, just above Michigan's legal
level of impairment.
   Detroit homicide detectives at first refused to believe the
youngster could have fired the gun. But they said gunpowder residue
tests showed the child was the only one in the room who did fire a
gun.
   The city's top homicide investigator, Inspector Gerald Stewart,
said it would be unusual for a toddler to have the strength to pull
a trigger. Stewart said detectives gave the boy the weapon
unloaded, asking him to show how he used it.
   ``We checked to see if that was possible,'' Stewart said. ``It
was.''
   According to the police report, Cannon and his 25-year-old
girlfriend, the boy's mother, were having a barbecue at their home
when the woman changed a musical tape Cannon had been playing.
   Cannon became angry, saying she was making a fool out of him,
the report said. He began grabbing and pushing the woman and went
and got a .25-caliber automatic he kept hidden from the children.
   The 3-year-old was among at least four children in the house who
were watching the late-night fight, the report said.
   Cannon walked into the room with the gun, but set it on a table,
saying he didn't need it. He then grabbed his girlfriend, threw her
to the floor and held her down as she yelled he was hurting her.
   A shot was fired and Cannon asked, ``Who got shot?''
   Then, he said, ``It's me.''
   Cannon fell over, mortally wounded in the back.
   Two other adults and three of the children in the room told
police the boy had picked up the gun, aimed it at his father and
fired.
   The boy's mother said Tuesday he had cried a little after the
shooting and then fell asleep for a while. That night at police
headquarters, the boy smiled and posed for a Polaroid photo that
homicide detectives often take of suspects. A detective let the boy
keep one.
   His mother said she considered counseling for her son,
especially after his pre-school teacher said he had been having
crying spells, but she didn't get around to it because the family
moved after the shooting.
</TEXT>
