<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 2116EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Turkey-Kurds     10-05 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-Kurds,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nearly 1,000 Kurdish Refugees Return To Iraq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VEDAT ERDAMAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HABUR, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 1,000 Kurdish refugees returned to
Iraq on Wednesday as the deadline neared for a government amnesty,
two months after they fled to Turkey claiming Iraq dropped chemical
bombs on their settlements.
   The 966 Kurds were taken by bus and truck from a tent city in
Yuksekova to a border post in Habur and then across a bridge over
the Tigris River into Iraq.
   They were among 60,000 Kurds who flocked to five tent cities in
southeastern Turkey last August during an army offensive against
Kurdish rebels in the mountains of northeastern Iraq.
   Regional Gov. Hayri Kozakcioglu told a news conference another
group of Kurdish refugees, numbering 1,500, was due to be
transferred to Iraq Thursday. He said Iraq assured the Turkish
government the refugees will be safely settled back in the villages.
   Iraq on Sept. 6 proclaimed a ``general and comprehensive''
amnesty for the Kurds at the urging of Turkey. Iraq has said that
thousands accepted the amnesty, but only a few were confirmed to
have returned.
   The deadline for the amnesty is Thursday evening. Foreign
Ministry spokesman Inal Batu said Turkey is trying to persuade Iraq
to extend the amnesty period.
   Batu told reporters in Ankara the Kurdish refugees signed papers
saying they were returning home voluntarily under terms of the
amnesty.
   Returning refugees said that when they left their villages, the
danger was very real.
   ``When the Iraqi planes came to our villages dropping chemical
bombs, we had no other chance but to escape,'' said Eyup Seydu, a
38-year-old refugee. ``But I decided to go back after the amnesty.
I am not afraid, I have done nothing wrong.''
   Iraq has denied it used chemical weapons against the Kurds,
though it has acknowledged using such weapons in its 8-year-old war
with Iran.
   Suleyman Fettah, 61, who was returning to his village of Rekani
in northern Iraq with his 14-member family, said he never wanted to
leave his village and that Kurdish guerrillas ``forced us to flee.''
   The Wednesday group included 501 children and 245 women. The
refugees, carrying a few belongings such as blankets or mattresses,
looked exhausted after the 20-hour trip to the border aboard 16
buses and four trucks.
   Turkey initially asked the International Red Cross to supervise
the Kurds' return, but the Red Cross declined after Iraq refused to
grant its request for further guarantees on behalf of the refugees.
   The Kurds, 20 million people living in a region where the
borders of Turkey, Iran and Iraq converge, have been fighting for
independence for the past century.
   The latest rebellion, led by Massoud Barzani, president of the
Kurdish Democratic Party, in alliance with Jamal Talabani's
Patriotic Union of Kurdistan, tried to take advantage of the
Iran-Iraq war.
   But after an Aug. 20 cease-fire in the war, Iraq sent seasoned
troops against the Kurds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
