<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0762,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cold Flows Over Great Lakes, Produces Rain, Hail</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS time element in lede; SUBS 8th graf, `By contrast
... to restore verbs, picks up 9th graf: `Temperatures around ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Canadian air chilled the upper Midwest on Wednesday and brought
wet, blustery weather to the Great Lakes region.
   Cold air flowing from the north over Lake Ontario produced
scattered showers and thunderstorms over western New York state.
Small hail pelted Oswego, and pea-sized hail was reported near
Saratoga Springs.
   Showers fell along the southern shores of Lake Erie in northwest
Pennsylvania and the southern shores of Lake Michigan. Rain showers
mixed with light snow over upper Michigan. Light rain dampened
Oklahoma and southern Kansas.
   Thunderstorms formed over northern Arizona, southern Utah and
southern Nevada, and showers and thunderstorms also were over
central Colorado and along the Atlantic Coast of Florida.
   Heavier rainfall in the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included
nearly half an inch at Tulsa, Okla., and a third of an inch at
Mcconnell Air Force Base, at Wichita, Kan.
   Temperatures dipped to the middle 30s in Illinois Tuesday night,
and were in the 30s Wednesday afternoon in parts of Minnesota,
Kansas and Nebraska.
   Frost or freeze advisories were issued for Wednesday night in
Wisconsin, Illinois, Indiana and Michigan. Ohio and the northern
and central Appalachians were warned to expect a freeze, and
Kentucky frost.
   By contrast, temperatures were in the 70s in the south half of
Texas, the Gulf Coast region, northern Florida, eastern parts of
the southern Atlantic Coast states, inland northern California and
the Great Basin of Nevada and western Utah. Temperatures in the 80s
were recorded in southern Florida.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 37
degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 99 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.
   Several cities had record low temperatures for the date
Wednesday morning, including 31 at Burlington, Iowa; 34 at Calico
Rock, Ark.; 24 at Eau Claire, Wis., 35 at Harrison, Ark.; 34 at
Kansas City, Mo.; 26 at Norfolk, Neb.; 31 at Ottumwa, Iowa; 26 at
Sioux City, Iowa; 24 at Waterloo, Iowa; and 25 at Yankton, S.D.
   Thursday's forecast called for showers scattered in northern
Maine, western New York, eastern Oklahoma and southwest Missouri.
Scattered showers and thunderstorms were expected in southern
Florida, Arizona and Utah. Cloudy skies were predicted in the
middle Mississippi Valley.
   High temperatures were forecast to be in the 40s in the northern
Great Lakes, the lower Great Lakes, most of New York state and
northern New England; the 70s and 80s in southeast Washington,
Oregon, along the Pacific Coast, northern and central California,
the northern and central Intermountain region west of the central
Rockies, the southern Rockies, Texas except the Panhandle, the Gulf
Coast region, Florida and southern Georgia. Temperatures should be
between 90 and 105 degrees in the desert Southwest and inland
valleys of southern California. The remainder of the nation should
have highs in the 50s and 60s.
</TEXT>
