<HEAD>Disabled Kids Abducted, Raped</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VERO BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was in custody Wednesday charged
with abducting and raping two mentally disabled boys whom he took
on a five-day trip around central Florida, tying them to beds to
keep them from escaping.
   The desperate families had been distributing fliers and even
consulting a psychic in their efforts to find the boys, ages 13 and
14.
   ``I was so relieved,'' said the mother of the 13-year-old Port
St. Lucie boy. ``So much time had elapsed. I thought for sure they
were dead.''
   John Halpin, 31, was arrested Tuesday and jailed without bail on
charges of sexual battery and false imprisonment.
   The boys disappeared Sept. 29 after they decided not to ride the
school bus home from their school for mentally disabled children.
   Halpin allegedly picked them up with promises of a motorcycle
and a stereo.
   He released them Monday, according to Indian River County
sheriff's Capt. Larry Tippins.
