<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CadetsStricken     10-05 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cadets Stricken,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cadet Recovering, Investigations Proliferate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRUDY TYNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police recruit who needed a liver
transplant after collapsing during rigorous training was showing
signs of emerging from a coma, his family said Wednesday.
   Pittsfield Mayor Ann Everest Wojtkowski said the family of
Timothy Shepard told her the 25-year-old Pittsfield police cadet
had been able to recognize his mother and pregnant wife and respond
to questions by shaking his head.
   Asked whether he was out of the coma, sister-in-law Becky
Shepard told The Associated Press: ``It's hard to say, it's a slow
process coming out of a coma,'' She added, ``there are signs that
he's coming out though.''
   Spokesmen at the Pittsburgh hospital where Shepard is being
treated would only say that Shepard remains in critical condition
after undergoing a liver transplant last week.
   The mayor said doctors have been able to remove Shepard from a
respirator for brief periods.
   A total of 16 cadets were hospitalized for dehydration and
exhaustion after Shepard collapsed on the first day of training,
Sept. 19.
   The Agawam academy was closed on the third day of training and
classes were moved until the drinking water could be checked. It
was found untainted, and all the cadets except Shepard have since
been released from hospitals.
   State Police Lt. William J. Shea, one of two state troopers who
took over the class this week after the original state police
instructors requested reassignment during the investigations,
described the morale of the cadets as ``pretty good under the
circumstances.'' But he said the classes were constantly being
interrupted by investigators from the attorney general's office.
   A task force assembled by Gov. Michael S. Dukakis also is
preparing to launch an inquiry into training at regional police
academies, as is a special 11-member state House committee.
   John Callahan, a former district attorney and past president of
the Massachusetts Bar Association chosen to head the governor's
board, said his group of legislators, police officials and doctors
would first meet Thursday.
   Callahan said he expected the focus of the inquiry would be the
physical and psychological training given recruits at the Agawam
academy and the state's six other regional police academies.
   State health officials and others have blamed extended exercise
without adequate water for the hospitalization of nearly one-third
of the recruits in the class.
</TEXT>
