<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 2127EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan     10-05 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court Clears Way For November Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court cleared the way
Wednesday for democratic elections to be held in Pakistan on Nov.
16.
   Benazir Bhutto's opposition Pakistan People's Party is widely
expected to win at least a simple majority in any freely held
elections.
   The court removed the last hurdle in the way of scheduled
elections this November by blocking a move to reconvene the
National Assembly dissolved by the late President Mohammad Zia
ul-Haq.
   In a unanimous decision, it upheld a lower court ruling last
week that Zia's move in May was unconstitutional, but also found no
grounds to restore to power the old Muslim League government of
Prime Minister Mohammed Khan Junejo.
   The high court said in a statement that while its findings might
imply that the Junejo government stands revived, ``We are not
unmindful of the fact that the whole nation is geared up for
elections and we do not propose to do anything which makes
confusion ... which would be the result if the vital process of
election is interrupted at this juncture.''
   Mohammed Khan Naqshbandi, a spokesman for the Muslim League,
said Junejo and other party leaders would abide by the decision and
would drop their demands to reinstate the former Cabinet and
reconvene the legislature.
   ``Our position has been vindicated that Zia's decision to
dissolve the National Assembly was unconstitutional, illegal and
uncalled for,'' he said.
   It was the second time this week that the high court ruled
against the late military strongman. Zia and several of his top
generals were killed in a plane crash on Aug. 17.
   The Supreme Court ruled Sunday in favor of a petition by Ms.
Bhutto challenging Zia's July decree that the elections in November
be on a non-party basis. The court said the constitution guaranteed
that candidates could run on party tickets, rather than as
individuals under Zia's plan.
   The last democratic elections, held in 1973, swept Ms. Bhutto's
father, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, into power as Pakistan's first
popularly elected prime minister.
   Bhutto was deposed by Zia in a military coup in 1977. Zia had
him hanged two years later.
   Zia ruled under martial law until 1985, when he allowed
elections on a non-party basis. The opposition boycotted the voting
and candidates favoring the pro-Zia Muslim League swept the
elections.
   Zia shared power with the Junejo government for three years,
then stunned the nation by abruptly firing the prime minister and
his Cabinet on May 29 and dissolving the National Assembly. Zia
accused them of corruption, incompetence and of failing to
implement his program of Islamization.
   Junejo denied the charges and called Zia's move illegal and
``arbitrary.''
   Zia scheduled elections for mid-November on a non-party basis.
   After his death, Zia, Senate chairman Ghulam Ishaq Khan assumed
the presidency and pledged that the elections would proceed on
schedule. He left it to the courts to decide whether the polls
should be open to political parties.
   The Federal Election Commission has announced that voting for
the National Assembly will be held Nov. 16 and for provincial
assemblies three days later.
   The commission estimates that about 46 million of Pakistan's 107
million people are eligible to vote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
