<1ST_LINE>u a AM-O'HareControllers 1stLd-Writethru a0729 10-05 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-O'Hare Controllers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0729,0667</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Incidents at O'Hare Raise New Safety Questions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to UPDATE with FAA plans to reduce air traffic;
INSERTS 2 grafs after 6th graf pvs, `I can't ..., with details;
picking up 6th graf: `The latest ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK PERKISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials acted Wednesday to reduce peak
air traffic at O'Hare International Airport in reaction to a report
that mistakes by controllers there this year are already more than
double the number in 1987.
   Controllers at O'Hare made two errors Friday, another Sunday and
another Tuesday, bringing the number of recorded mistakes at O'Hare
this year to 30, said Don Zochert, a spokesman for the Federal
Aviation Administration in Chicago.
   In all four cases, planes were allowed to get too close to each
other, officials said. No one was injured.
   Atlanta's Hartsfield International Airport has had six errors
this year, and Washington's National Airport two, officials said.
   In 1987, there were 12 errors by air traffic controllers at
O'Hare, which has been the subject of an investigation by the
National Transportation Safety Board, Zochert said. The airport is
one the world's busiest.
   ``I can't explain the reason (for the errors),'' Zochert said.
``That's the question everybody wants the answer to and if there
was an easy solution we'd have it.''
   Late Wednesday, the FAA called a news conference to say flights
to Chicago would sit on the ground in the cities where they
originate when there is too much traffic over O'Hare, spokeswoman
Barbara Dettmer said.
   During peak periods _ usually between 4:45 p.m. and 9:15 p.m. _
the maximum number of planes allowed to depart and land would be
reduced to about 155 per hour from 180, Ms. Dettmer said.
   The latest incidents came just two months after the safety board
issued a report saying that chronic understaffing, mandatory
overtime, outdated equipment and inadequate training had
contributed to mistakes at O'Hare.
   Despite the rise in mistakes, O'Hare remains a safe airport,
Zochert said.
   Michael Benson, a spokesman for the NTSB in Washington, said the
board met with FAA officials Wednesday to discuss the ``new rash of
operational errors. We got a positive feeling the FAA will be
taking steps.''
   In Tuesday's incident, a United Airlines jet and a smaller
Simmons Airlines plane came within 500 feet of each other while
approaching O'Hare, he said.
   On Sunday, two United jets came within 500 feet of each other
after the pilot of one plane apparently followed an order intended
for the other.
   On Friday, two Air Wisconsin jets came near each other when a
controller apparently mistakenly gave one of them an order to
descend, the FAA said.
   In a second incident Friday, an American Airlines jet and a
Delta Air Lines jet came within 400 feet vertically and a mile
horizontally when the pilot of the American jet apparently failed
to repeat an order to reduce speed and the controller did not seek
confirmation, the FAA said.
   The FAA requires airplanes in the area to be separated a minimum
of three miles horizontally and 1,000 feet vertically.
   Joe Bellino, regional representative of the National Air Traffic
Controllers Association, said O'Hare's radar room on Friday was ``a
zoo.''
   With Friday's 3,842 takeoffs and landings _ just below the
all-time record of 3,853 set the day before _ there should have
been 18 journeyman controllers and several ``developmental''
controllers on duty. Developmental controllers have fewer
responsibilities than the journeymen.
   But Bellino said there were only 14 controllers working and the
problem was made worse when the controllers who made the errors
were temporarily relieved of their duties, giving those who
remained even more responsibilities.
   The FAA could not immediately say how many controllers were on
duty Friday, but Zochert said the number of controllers working at
the airport has risen from 87 last year to 94 as of Sept. 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
