<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Medvedev     10-05 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Medvedev,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Chief Ideologist Charts Middle Course In Speech</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new Soviet chief ideologist appeared to chart
a middle course in the first major speech since he was elected to
the ruling Soviet Politburo, voicing support for reform as well as
for strong central authority.
   Vadim A. Medvedev's speech to an international conference on
contemporary socialism was made Tuesday and reprinted Wednesday by
the government newspaper Izvestia. The speech appeared to show some
slight differences from the beliefs of President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
   Medvedev, a political economist, was named a member of the
Politburo on Friday by the policy-making Central Committee. He also
was named to head a party commission on ideology, indicating he
also assumed the ideology portfolio once held by Yegor K. Ligachev.
   Ligachev is widely believed to favor a more conservative
approach to social problems than Gorbachev. Medvedev's speech
appeared to stake out a middle ground, balancing the need for
reform with maintenance of political authority.
   ``We proceed from the fact that the socialist economy is
impossible without the strong role of the center,'' Medvedev, 59,
told the conference.
   He also seemed to say the criticism allowed by Gorbachev's drive
for greater openness, or ``glasnost,'' had gone too far.
   ``Unfortunately, there have been some irresponsible attempts to
cast a shadow over Lenin's inheritance, over the basic values of
socialism,'' Medvedev said.
   ``And how else can those statements appearing in the press be
interpreted that claim that the command-administrative system
resulted from Lenin, those attempts to deny the socialist nature of
our system, that even doubt the rightness of our choice for
socialism?''
   Medvedev did, however, say socialism now faces the need for
``deep qualitative rejuvenation.''
   In his 3{ years since becoming Communist Party chief, Gorbachev
has often mentioned the common interests of the West and the
socialist camp. Medvedev, however, said it was ``outdated'' to
maintain capitalism and socialism were developing on a parallel
course.
   ``Certainly, there could not be any merging, any convergence of
the two systems,'' the new Politburo member said. ``Each will
develop in accordance with its own rules.''
</TEXT>
