<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Obit-Perez 1stLd-Writethru a0755 10-05 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Perez, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0755,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leander Perez Jr. Dies Of Heart Attack</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0755, to restore slugline version section;
INSERTS 1 graf to UPDATE with details on where Perez was stricken;
ADDS 1 graf with survivors.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GRETNA, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leander Perez Jr., the former district
attorney who lost his father's legacy of power in Plaquemines
Parish in fights with his brother, died Wednesday of a heart
attack. He was 68 years old.
   ``He was brought into the Meadowcrest Hospital emergency room by
ambulance in critical condition and he died at the hospital,'' said
hospital spokeswoman Ann Wilder.
   Perez, who lived in New Orleans, apparently suffered the heart
attack during a business meeting at Idlewild Plantation, the family
estate in Belle Chasse, said A.R. Johnson, a close friend of Perez.
   Perez was a son of the fervent segregationist who built one of
the most dominant political machines in Southern history _ ruling
Plaquemines for more than four decades, first as district attorney
and later as Commission Council president.
   Before he died in 1969, Judge Leander Perez _ so known because
he had briefly held an appointed federal judgeship at the start of
his political career _ saw Leander Jr. anointed as district
attorney and his other son, Chalin, as council president.
   Leander Jr., who first became district attorney in 1960, did not
run in 1984. He never announced his decision or said why he made
it. He reportedly had been hospitalized that year for circulation
problems.
   Perez also had serious political troubles since he and Chalin
had begun feuding in the late 1970s, and in 1979 Leander Perez
began investigating the parish council.
   A grand jury indicted Chalin Perez in 1981 on charges of misuse
and abuse of parish property and finances. The panel was dismissed
later that year, just as it was about to indict the district
attorney and the family-owned Delta Development Corp. on charges of
stealing millions of dollars in mineral royalties from parish-owned
lands.
   Perez and former state District Judge Eugene Leon were indicted
on malfeasance charges because of that dismissal, but were
acquitted in February 1986.
   Chalin Perez was ousted as parish president in 1983, the same
year that a lawyer unearthed an old legal document revealing that
Judge Perez had secretly acquired control of parish lands in the
1930s.
   The parish sued the Perezes, but two courts ruled that the
parish had filed its lawsuit 33 years too late.
   Those courts eventually were overruled by the state Supreme
Court, and the parish dropped $80 million in claims against the
family in September 1987 for about $12 million and control of the
oil-rich lands, on which it expects to earn $3 million a year.
   Perez is survived by his wife, Aphra, whom he married after the
death of his first wife, Catherine; four children, and their
children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881005-0222 </DOCNO>
