<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Bank Robbery, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0724,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank Robbery Foiled; Customers Released; Two Suspects Arrested</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs with background of earlier robbery.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS MOCHIS, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two gunmen held at least eight
customers hostage for an hour at a bank in this Pacific coast town
Wednesday but released them when police entered the building, a
state police official said.
   No one was injured and the two would-be robbers were arrested,
said Joel Velazco Flores, a state police commander.
   ``They didn't have time to get the loot,'' Velazco Flores said.
   He said the men, armed with pistols, entered the Banoro bank
shortly after 9 a.m. (noon EDT) and held from eight to 10 of the
customers, ``whoever they wanted,'' next to the vault. An
undetermined number of other people also were in the bank, he said.
   About 50 state, city and federal police and highway patrolmen
surrounded the block where the bank is located, he said. Then 20 to
25 of them entered through different doors, using a megaphone to
urge the assailants not to shoot, he said.
   ``They obeyed,'' Velazco Flores said.
   He identified those arrested as Francisco Lopez, 22, and Paulino
Paredes Quintero, 23, both of Los Mochis.
   In April, six heavily armed men took more than 42 hostages in a
24-hour siege in Los Mochis at a branch of the National Bank of
Mexico. Five people were killed and 15 wounded.
   Unconfirmed reports said those robbers took about $13,000 from
the bank, but officials would not confirm the amount. After
releasing the hostages, the gunmen were allowed to leave in an
armored car but were later arrested.
