<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 2253EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Scholars-FordGrant     10-05 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scholars-Ford Grant,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hungarian Dissident Is First Beneficiary Of Academic Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists, scholars, writers and artists from
countries with restricted freedom of expression will work at 15
American colleges under a program established by the Ford
Foundation, sponsors said Wednesday.
   Miklos Haraszti, a dissident writer from Hungary, arrived at
Bard College in Annandale-on-Hudson in September, becoming the
first fellow of the International Academy for Scholarship and the
Arts.
   The Ford Foundation has given a $100,000 grant to establish the
program, said Leon Botstein, president of Bard College, which will
serve as its administrator.
   The fellows will reside for at least one academic year at the
American colleges, pursuing their work while teaching.
   ``Serious and gifted scholars and artists from all over the
world who need the opportunity to think, study, investigate and
write without restriction will be served,'' said Botstein. ``In
return, our students, faculty and staff can only benefit by their
presence.''
   The sponsors said applicants for the fellowship will most likely
be among three categories:
   _Emigrant artists and intellectuals who are living in Europe or
the United States but who are unemployed or underemployed.
   _Individuals who seek to leave their homeland, perhaps
permanently, as a matter of conscience.
   _Individuals who would like to come to the United States but who
intend to return to their homeland, despite any political or
economic pressures that may await them.
   The program also will include Dartmouth College in Hanover,
N.H.; Davidson College in Davidson, N.C.; Vassar College in
Poughkeepsie, N.Y.; St. Augustine College in Raleigh, N.C.; Lincoln
University in Oxford, Pa.; and nine other schools not yet chosen.
</TEXT>
