<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 2135EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0778 10-05 0931</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0778,900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Calls for Programs to Help Families, Environment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with Bush reaction to opening of debate, INSERTS 1
graf after 10th pvs, editing 11th pvs appropriately, picking up
11th pvs bgng ``Bush also ...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Debate Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush on Wednesday proposed a $3.9 billion
``invest in our children'' plan focusing on school programs and
environmental and quality-of-life issues Bush said will foster
stronger children through ``a family that functions and an
environment that motivates.''
   The package, including some proposals Bush has made before,
would be aimed at helping poor people through tax code revisions
and Medicaid efforts, and would also include anti-crime and
anti-gang sections as well as efforts to remove toxic substances
from school environments.
   A 32-page summary released by the Republican's presidential
campaign also includes proposals to require Medicaid coverage for
poor children and to give the states $10 million for developing
programs against hazardous radon gas.
   Bush called for a national survey of schools in 1990 to detect
and get rid of radon, and also for ``strict standards'' covering
manufacturers who use lead in development of consumer products.
   Although Bush said in a remark at a Arapahoe High School that
``I don't see this problem in terms of money,'' campaign adviser
Deborah Steelman said the entire package would cost about $3.9
billion in federal money for the first year of a five-year plan.
   Included in that figure is a previously announced $2.2 billion
tax credit program for child care. Steelman said the new Medicaid
proposals would amount to some $300 million.
   ``Why are some children still in trouble after 50 years of
liberal programs aimed at helping them?'' Bush asked. ``Because
liberalism didn't help _ it often made the problem worse.''
   The vice president took some time out from his campaign duties
to telephone running mate Dan Quayle and wish him well in his
debate Wednesday night with Democrat Lloyd Bentsen, according to
Bush's chief of staff Craig Fuller.
   During the 10-minute conversation, Bush told Quayle, ``Relax, I
know it will go well.''
   Bush has been favorably impressed with Quayle, Fuller said.
``When the American people get a chance to see the Dan Quayle we
know they will all be favorably impressed,'' Fuller said.
   The vice president watched the debate from Fort Worth, Texas.
   ``He's doing good, good opening, right out of the ball park, the
Canseco of American politics,'' Bush said, referring to Oakland A's
baseball player Jose Canseco in describing Quayle's response to the
first question of the debate to a group of reporters he had invited
to watch the opening of the event. ``He hit it the first answer,
home run.''
   Bush also traveled Wednesday to Oklahoma City, where the oil
industry is struggling through tough times.
   ``You're back,'' Bush told a rally. ``Oklahoma is coming
strong.''
   Promising to decontrol natural gas, Bush said Dukakis is an
opponent of the energy industry but ``is now trying to fool the
American people by acting like he cares about the energy industry.''
   At the high school in the Denver suburb of Littleton, Bush said,
``Our future will be as strong tomorrow as our children are today.
And our children will be as strong as their education allows. Their
eduction will be as strong as their schools. But something more is
required: a family that functions and an environment that
motivates.''
   Included in the plan is a call to phase in affordable Medicaid
coverage for pregnant women and infants with incomes up to 185
percent of the poverty level. Bush also would expand on current
Medicaid coverage for children of families with incomes below the
poverty level by providing health-care education for those families.
   The proposals were an elaboration on Bush's remarks in his first
debate with Democratic rival Michael Dukakis that he wanted to
allow the poor to ``buy into'' Medicaid, said Steelman.
   Bush said he would also expand the Maternal and Child Health
Block Grant program to provide health and Medicaid information for
pregnant women and provide case management ``as an essential
component for high risk in teen-age pregnancies that are likely to
result in low birth weight.''
   He also called for mandatory Medicaid coverage ``of functionally
disabled children who would have to be in a hospital or other
institution without such coverage for home care.''
   In other areas, he called for:
   _ Mandatory child support levels and enforcement, and a
``nationwide parent locator system'' to track down delinquent
parents.
   _ Case management and counseling to teach parents about health
care and nutrition.
   _ Encouraging states to make drug testing a condition of bail,
probation and parole.
   _ A focus on crime in the schools with creation of a Justice
Department anti-gang unit to work with local jurisdictions.
   _ Legislation to give the federal government concurrent
jurisdiction over juveniles committing federal crimes, so that the
federal government can act ``if the state fails to vigorously
prosecute juveniles.''
   _ Housing vouchers to get assistance to low-income families, a
system he said would provide three times as much assistance as
building housing for the same price.
   In giving spending projections for the newly announced programs,
Steelman said the anti-gang unit portion would run about $50
million, new Medicaid for mothers and infants at 185 percent of the
poverty level would be $300 million with another $80 million for
case management in Medicaid.
   The radon and lead programs would cost $30 million, and a
program to help turn over subsudized housing to tenants would cost
$80 million, she said.
</TEXT>
