<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HollywoodTeamsters     10-05 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hollywood Teamsters,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teamster Harassment Blocked by Court Order</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking Hollywood drivers and three
production companies agreed to an order Wednesday barring the
drivers from intimidating studio employees and disrupting film and
television production.
   To stem the increasingly violent atmosphere surrounding the
Teamsters strike, the Cannell Studios, Lorimar Studios and MTM-CBS
Studios joined in a temporary restraining order with the Teamsters
which was approved by Superior Court Judge Kurt Lewin.
   The Teamsters agreed to observe new rules about the size of
picket contingents, how close they can come to studio gates and the
distance between the marchers and the pace at which they walk so as
to not obstruct traffic.
   The restrictions will be considered more fully at hearing Oct.
18. The walkout, affecting 3,200 drivers, laborers and
electricians, began Monday.
   The Cannell Studios closed down production on its shows
``Hunter'' and ``Sonny Spoon'' on Tuesday after a series of reports
of violence, including death threats, physical assaults and slashed
tires.
   Even as the Teamsters and the producers met in court, there were
more reports of confrontations. Location filming on the CBS series
``Murder, She Wrote'' was disrupted Wednesday when pickets
encouraged passing motorists to honk their horns, according to
security guard Charles Loust.
   Loust said that several replacement drivers went home early
because they were being harassed by pickets. Teamster officials did
not respond to interview requests.
   The Teamster drivers transport actors, equipment and props for
television and film producers. Joining the Teamsters on the picket
lines are 1,000 members of two other Basic Crafts unions, the
electricians and the laborers. The Hollywood plasterers and the
plumbers, the remaining Basic Crafts guilds, are not on strike.
   Issues in the strike include overtime rules for weekend work,
salary rates, wages for out-of-town film and television production,
seniority and guidelines for the making of nonunion films. Some
drivers are being asked to take a pay cut from $16.61 to $14 per
hour.
   The producers maintain that the Teamsters must help manage
mounting production costs and increased competition. Overall, the
contract proposal represents an increase in employment and
salaries, the producers say.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
