<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-KoreaFilms     10-05 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Korea Films,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressmen Enter U.S.-Korean Movie Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four members of Congress have called on the
South Korean government to curb violent demonstrations in Seoul
that they charged were instigated ``by militant Korean film
distributors who seek to retain their monopoly on U.S. film
distribution.''
   The demonstrations occurred outside a Seoul cinema where ``Fatal
Attraction,'' a U.S. motion picture hit, was booked through direct
royalty contract with the American exporter, cutting out the South
Korean middlemen, they said in a letter to South Korean Ambassador
Park Tong-jin.
   The letter _ signed by Reps. Sam Gibbons, D-Fla.; Thomas J.
Downey, D-N.Y., Robert T. Matsui, D-Calif., and Frank J. Guarini,
D-N.J., all members of the House Ways and Means trade subcommittee
_ was released Wednesday by the Motion Picture Association of
America, which represents major Hollywood studios.
   ``Menacing crowds'' have blocked access and threatened the lives
of cinema owners and employees of U.S. distribution companies,
broken into cinemas, defaced the screens, spray-painted the seats
and let loose dangerous snakes, the letter said, quoting ``on-site
reports'' from Seoul.
   A Sept. 24 Associated Press dispatch from Seoul said
demonstrations halted operations at two theaters, there were no
clashes or arrests and participants included numerous Korean movie
celebrities protesting U.S. ``economic and cultural invasion.''
   ``These demonstrations are progressing unchecked by your
government,'' the letter said.
   There was no immediate comment from the South Korean Embassy.
   The dispute stems from a 1985 South Korean government agreement
with MPAA's export arm authorizing direct distribution of major
Hollywood productions, with the exporters splitting profits with
the theaters.
   The Motion Picture Export Association of America last month
filed a formal unfair trade complaint with the U.S. government
charging that South Korea and its film industry were violating the
pact with obstructive tactics such as involved censorship
procedures and other bottlenecks making it economically impossible
for U.S. distributors to open their own offices in the country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
