<DOCNO> AP881005-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 2301EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-KillingFields     10-05 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Killing Fields,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Killing Fields' Survivor Assails U.N. For Seating Khmer Rouge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Times photographer Dith Pran, a
survivor of Cambodia's killing fields, denounced the United Nations
on Wednesday for letting the Khmer Rouge be part of the Cambodian
U.N. delegation.
   ``I am still shocked when I see the Khmer Rouge flag on U.N.
territory. How would you feel if you were Jewish and you saw
Hitler's flag flying at the U.N.?'' Dith Pran asked a crowd of
about 250 demonstrators at a vigil outside U.N. Headquarters.
   The Khmer Rouge toppled the U.S.-backed Cambodian government in
1975, trapping Dith Pran in his country. Like most of the
population, he endured famine and forced labor on a collective
farm, but escaped to Thailand in 1979 and from there joined his
family in the United States.
   Dith Pran's ordeal, and that of his people, were the focus of
the film ``The Killing Fields.''
   Cambodia's U.N. delegation called Wednesday for Vietnam's
withdrawal from their country, and said a political solution to the
nation's troubles must be based on national reconciliation among
all parties, including the Khmer Rouge, which ruled until 1979.
   But Son Sann, prime minister of the government-in-exile fighting
the Hanoi-installed government in Phnom Penh, said an international
conference should adopt measures to prevent Vietnam's return or the
``illegal and violent seizure of power by one of the parties,'' a
reference to the Khmer Rouge.
   An estimated 2 million of Cambodia's 8 million people died from
Khmer Rouge executions, famine and civil unrest before Vietnam
invaded the country in late 1978 and ousted Pol Pot's Khmer Rouge
regime.
   Wednesday's vigil to protest the Khmer Rouge presence, organized
by the Oxfam America famine relief agency, coincided with
Cambodia's speech to the 43rd General Assembly.
   Oxfam's executive director John Hammock and several of its
officers began a three-day fast Wednesday to protest Khmer Rouge
membership in the United Nations.
   Dith Pran did not join them.
   ``I starved almost four years already; I did enough myself,'' he
said.
   Oxfam, Dith Pran, and many Cambodians fear that the
Chinese-backed Khmer Rouge, the best armed of the three groups
fighting the current government in Phnom Penh, will seize power.
   Hanoi has said it will withdraw 50,000 of its 120,000 occupation
troops from Cambodia this year, and all will be out by early 1990.
   Among those pessimistic about the future of Cambodia is Dith
Pran's friend, Sydney Schanberg, the Pulitzer Prize-winning former
correspondent for The New York Times.
   Schanberg lingered almost unnoticed at Wednesday's vigil and
declined to be interviewed, saying this was an occasion for the
Cambodians to be heard. But he said he could not believe China
would desert its longtime ally, the Khmer Rouge.
   In the U.N. General Assembly, Son Sann assailed Vietnam's
occupation forces.
   Son Sann's non-communist Khmer People's National Liberation
Front, and forces loyal to former Cambodian head of state Prince
Norodom Sihanouk make up the U.N.-recognized delegation along with
the Khmer Rouge.
   Under the U.N. Charter and international law, the United Nations
says it cannot recognize a government imposed on a country by
outside force, such as the present Cambodian government installed
by Hanoi.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881005-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 2301EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Brazil     10-05 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bells Peal Across Brasilia As Brazil Enacts Eighth Constitution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JORGE MEDEROS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church bells rang in this modernistic
capital Wednesday as Brazil enacted its eighth constitution,
consolidating the switchover from military rule to civilian
government that began in 1985.
   The 559 legislators, who for 19 months battled over the
245-article document, cheered and shouted ``Brazil is changing!''
as the president of the Constituent Assembly, Ulysses Guimaraes,
declared law the new document.
   ``I declare enacted the constitution of liberty, of dignity, of
democracy and social justice,'' Guimaraes, 72, said in a voice that
struggled above thunderous applause. ``May God help us enforce it.''
   Brazil's new democratic charter leaves behind the old
authoritarian document that was handed down by military generals in
1969.
   The enactment was the last step in Brazil's return to fully
democratic rule begun in March 1985, when Jose Sarney became
Brazil's first civilian president since a 1964 right-wing military
coup.
   ``We have created a new Brazil, a new social and economic
order,'' Dante de Oliveira of the governing Democratic Movement
Party said after the ceremony. ``We have taught the world an
important lesson, peacefully overturning an authoritarian regime.''
   The new document, a mixture of left-leaning, conservative and
nationalistic articles that touch almost all aspects of life from
land reform to interest rates, granted none of the arbitrary powers
used by the repressive military government during 21 years to rule
the country.
   The new charter bans censorship, removes the president's power
to simply decree law and outlaws torture, which in the past was
used against the military government's political opponents.
   But many of the articles were confusing. Several such as a
reduced work week, more maternity leave and extra pay for overtime
immediately became law; 154 would need complimentary legislation to
become effective.
   One such confusing article limited ``real'' interest rates to 12
percent though no one knows what ``real'' interest rates in
inflation-ridden Brazil are. Inflation in Brazil is averaging more
than 350 percent over the last 12 months.
   One of the most controversial articles fought over by
legislators, who shouted each other down in day-long debates and
often resorted to physical violence, set presidential elections in
November 1989. Brazilians haven't voted for president since 1960.
   Representatives from 21 Latin American and Portuguese-speaking
nations watched legislators enact Brazil's eighth constitution
since the country gained independence from Portugal in 1822.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881005-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 2302EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BoyChase     10-05 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boy Chase,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Boy Kills Self After Crime Spree</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASHLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 14-year-old boy fleeing police in a
stolen car apparently shot himself in the head early Wednesday
after he crashed into a ditch, police said.
   Timothy Dale Wilson of Ashland was found dead in the driver's
seat, and a .38-caliber revolver car reported stolen Tuesday from
an Ashland home was found in the car, police said.
   Police said Wilson was born in Vietnam and adopted as an infant,
but had been living with foster parents since early last summer
after stealing his father's car.
   The chase began at 12:50 a.m. when Ashland police spotted a car
that had been reported stolen Tuesday morning. Police from Ashland,
Talent and Phoenix were following Wilson when the car crashed on
Highway 99 in Phoenix.
   Police Chief Vic Lively said the car had been stolen sometime
Monday night in Ashland. The revolver and two knives, reported
stolen Tuesday from a house in Ashland, were found in the car with
Wilson, police said.
   Police said a young man with a gun tried to rob a waiter at a
Medford restaurant Tuesday night. The waiter later identified
Wilson as the gunman.
   News of Wilson's death stunned officials at Ashland High School,
where he was a freshman.
   ``He was bubbly, he was outgoing,'' said Randy Rogney, a school
counselor. ``He was fun to be around. The kids here are in shock.''
   Vice Principal Jeff Schlecht said he never had any trouble with
Wilson.
   ``He had a ready smile, you could kid him and he'd kid back,'
Schlecht said.
   Wilson's father said the boy's adoptive mother died when he was
six. ``I don't know what his basic mental problem was that
triggered him off,'' Bob Wilson said. ``He was a good son.''
</TEXT>
