<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Chambers-GrandJury     10-05 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chambers-Grand Jury,0680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Wife: Chambers Killed Bean During Fight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KEENE, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Marlow police chief Robert Chambers
killed his drinking buddy with a hatchet when the man tried to
protect Chambers' estranged wife, she said in an interview
published Wednesday.
   As he lay dying outside Chambers' home on Sept. 15, 1978,
Russell Bean, then 25, looked at Deborah Wentworth, told her to
take care of his children, and said he loved his wife, Sylvia,
Wentworth told The Keene Sentinel.
   Chambers declined to comment on the account, referring the
Sentinel's questions to his lawyer, Mark Sisti, who also declined
to comment.
   Since Bean's skeletal remains were unearthed in March in
Chambers' front yard, Chambers, 36, has said only six words
publicly about the case: ``I did not kill Russ Bean.'' He was
arrested April 15.
   Sisti tried to bar the state from presenting Wentworth's
testimony to a grand jury in May, questioning her competence and
citing a history of psychiatric treatment.
   Wentworth testified to the grand jury that prosecutors asked to
issue a murder indictment. The grand jury, whose proceedings are
secret, returned no indictment, leaving Chambers a free man.
   He is living with a policeman-friend in Hinsdale and working as
a logger, the job he held 10 years ago. Phones calls to the
residence went unanswered.
   Wentworth also could not be reached.
   Police, acting on tips from Chambers' relatives, began digging
in his front yard on March 11. They told police that Robert
Chambers' father, Clifton, told them Chambers came to him one night
10 years ago and said he had accidentally killed Bean in a fight,
and that father and son had buried the body with a backhoe. Clifton
Chambers died of a cerebral hemorrhage March 9.
   Bean's body was uncovered on March 14 and an autopsy indicated
he was struck with something, but authorities have never said what.
When Chambers' relatives told them Bean was killed with a hatchet
that was thrown into a quarry, police later drained the quarry, but
found nothing.
   Chambers has resigned as Marlow's part-time police chief, a job
he held three years.
   The Sentinel said it interviewed Wentworth, 36, as well as
investigators whom it did not identify and many of the people
interviewed by police in their investigation.
   Not long after Bean's death, his wife Sylvia and her three
children moved in with Chambers, whom Wentworth had left several
months earlier with Chambers' two sons. Sylvia Bean and Chambers
subsequently married, though she moved out and filed for divorce
after Bean's body was dug up.
   According to the paper, Sylvia _ then married to Bean _ said
Robert Chambers and her husband went out drinking and partying
constantly until she finally told Bean it had to stop. She said he
agreed, but that on Sept. 15, 1978, Bean left with Chambers around
6 p.m.
   According to Wentworth and sources familiar with her grand jury
testimony, Wentworth hitchhiked with suitcases to Chambers' rural
home that evening. Chambers and Bean arrived a few minutes later,
and when Chambers saw her, he got angry and called her vulgar names.
   Bean tried to come to her defense, she told the paper, but
Chambers pushed her toward Bean, saying he could have her, an
apparent reference to an affair Bean and Wentworth had had earlier.
   Wentworth told the paper that when Bean stepped between her and
Chambers, Chambers picked up a hatchet and hit Bean several times
in the head and once in the chest.
   She told the Sentinel that Chambers then forced her into his
truck, threw her suitcases in back, and drove her the short
distance to Newell Pond, where he beat her again, threatened her
and left. Again a motorist picked her up.
   ``If I can find whoever picked her up, I hope (Wentworth) told
them something,'' Sgt. Richard Rondo, chief state police
investigator in the case, told the Sentinel.
   Police investigated Bean's disappearance, but closed the case,
assuming Bean abandoned his family.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881005-0245 </DOCNO>
