<1ST_LINE>u p AM-VeepDebate-Color 1stLd-Writethru   10-05 0785</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Veep Debate-Color, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0614,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Organizers Reject Criticism of Debate Staging as `Nonsense'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES to show debate held, new material; DELETES outdated
material.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Organizers scorned criticism of the staging
of Wednesday night's debate between Dan Quayle and Lloyd Bentsen as
``a lot of nonsense'' which ignores the reality that the event is
essentially a television show.
   Ed Fouhy, executive producer of the 90-minute confrontation
between the two vice presidential candidates, says it's his
business to fret about such seemingly trivial details as camera
angles and the height of lecterns on the stage of the Omaha Civic
Auditorium.
   ``This is a television program, and we've got some of the best
production people in the world doing it,'' Fouhy said.
   Sharing Fouhy's concerns are the Democratic and Republican
contenders' campaign managers, who were eager to exploit the TV
format to best advantage. In the past week of mock debates and
briefings for the candidates, the medium was truly the message.
   Bentsen, for example, who is accustomed to the leisurely pace of
Senate debate, spent days struggling _ with limited success _ to
distill his debating points into those punchy, quotable ``sound
bites'' that TV demands.
   About an hour into their debate, Bentsen unleashed what he had
learned. When Quayle summoned up the name of former President John
Kennedy, Bentsen stared and him and said sternly: ``You're no Jack
Kennedy.''
   The two warmed up with mild-by-comparison jabs over campaign
finances, but in general the two candidates stuck to carefully
scripted performances from the moment they strode onto the red,
white and blue decorated stage.
   Mike McCurry, press secretary for the 67-year-old Democratic
senator from Texas, said before the debate that Bentsen was having
trouble observing the strict time limits specified for the debate _
two-minute answers to questions and one-minute rebuttals.
   ``The red light goes off frequently,'' McCurry said.
   Quayle, 41, seems more comfortable in a TV setting, has been
coached by GOP nominee George Bush's media mastermind, Roger Ailes.
Deflecting reporters' questions about his debate strategy, the
Indiana senator said confidently that they should ``tune in and
find out.''
   During the debate, Quayle stood casually with one foot propped
on the podium, his face occasionally tightening when the audience
laughed at a defense of his environmental record and during several
tough questions tossed at him by panelists.
   The League of Women Voters withdrew as sponsors of the second
scheduled debate between Bush and Democratic nominee Michael
Dukakis in Los Angeles in mid-October, complaining that campaign
strategists had turned the event into a ``charade'' by grabbing
tight control of the mechanics of TV coverage.
   Fouhy told reporters that restrictions demanded by the two
campaigns were minor. He said the biggest was the decision not to
show the audience of 2,000 people in the hall during the debate,
except for fuzzy, ``over the shoulder'' shots.
   `A lot of nonsense has been spoken and written about the
shots,'' Fouhy said. ``That's simply wrong. You direct a television
program so people watching at home have a good idea what's
happening.''
   Janet Brown, executive director of the bipartisan debate
commission sponsoring the Quayle-Bentsen clash, said it's natural
that both sides will fight hard for any advantage in a closely
fought presidential race.
   `I'm very pleased with all the arrangements,'' Ms. Brown said.
``It's been a helpful exchange, a productive exchange, it's been a
very honest exchange from all three parties.''
   Fouhy noted that the first Bush-Dukakis debate on Sept. 25 was
viewed by an estimated 35 million households. He said details of
the staging are crucial because ``millions of people are going to
watch this debate on television.''
   The intense interest in this year's campaign has put the
smallest details of the debates under scrutiny. Debate rules, for
example, allow only a three-inch variation in the height of the
candidates' lecterns. The final decision is made after each
candidate makes his allotted one-hour visit to the hall, closed to
reporters, a few hours before the debate begins.
   Little appearing on camera has been left to chance. Even the
journalists on the debate panel _ NBC's Tom Brokaw, Jon Margolis of
the Chicago Tribune and ABC's Britt Hume _ drew lots to determine
the order in which they asked questions.
   Fouhy said moderator Judy Woodruff of public broadcasting's
MacNeil@Lehrer NewsHour will use gentle persuasion rather than
cutting off the microphones of any candidate who talks beyond his
time limit.
   Though the main floor of the Civic Auditorium was turned into a
large TV studio for the debate, the scene was much more informal
one level below, where most of the 1,500 reporters covering the
debate could watch on TV monitors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
