<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 2320EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0742 10-05 0869</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0742,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Assails Bush On Furloughs; Says Campaign Turning His Way</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, `The Democratic,' with 5 grafs new to
UPDATE with Dukakis comment on the debate; picks up 3rd graf pvs,
`Our campaign.'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Debate Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis on Wednesday accused George Bush
of politically exploiting one ``tragic'' case involving a
Massachusetts furlough program, said campaign momentum has shifted
to him and promised ``five long, tough, aggressive weeks'' up to
the election.
   The Democratic presidential nominee also praised the performance
of his running mate, Lloyd Bentsen, in the vice presidential
nominee's debate Wednesday night with Republican Dan Quayle.
   ``The most important qualification for the vice president is
that he's ready at a moment's notice to assume the presidency of
the United States,'' Dukakis told a rowdy rally with supporters
shortly after the debate. ``Tonight Lloyd Bentsen demonstrated that
he was the only one on that stage who's ready.''
   Dukakis, who spoke to Bentsen immediately after the debate, said
the Democrat's performance should tell the American people ``about
how I make presidential decisions and the way George Bush makes
presidential decisions.''
   ``Tonight that was no contest,'' he said.
   Earlier, Dukakis used the debate to joke about the beginning of
the American League playoff series between the Boston Red Sox and
the Oakland Athletics.
   ``Our campaign is picking up steam,'' Dukakis told a news
conference at the Massachusetts Statehouse, where he spent a day
off the campaign trail catching up on gubernatorial duties. ``You
can sense it. You can feel it. And I think it's because the
American people want to move forward.''
   Republican nominee Bush has made his criticism of a
Massachusetts furlough program a staple of his campaign and on
Wednesday night aired a new television ad accusing Dukakis of
running a ``revolving door'' prison system. At the center of Bush's
attacks is a case in which an inmate on furlough raped a Maryland
woman and assaulted her fiance.
   Dukakis, who earlier this year signed legislation tightening
eligibility requirements for the program, said Bush was exploiting
that case despite a comparable federal program.
   ``The vice president's record on crime and the fight against
drugs is pathetic,'' Dukakis said. ``It's been a failure and in my
judgment this is an effort to use the one case with a tragic
occurrence for political reasons. The vice president knows that the
federal government has a very extensive furlough program, knows
that Governor Reagan in California in the 70s had a very extensive
furlough program and tragedies as a result of that.''
   That answer came in response a question about suggestions by
Texas Democrats that Dukakis was trailing in that key state despite
have a Texan running mate because he had not responded forcefully
enough to Bush's attacks on crime, gun control and other issues.
   Dukakis promised he would return the salvos soon, and aides said
they would come as soon as Thursday, when Dukakis planned to visit
Texas with Bentsen.
   ``We have five, long, tough, aggressive weeks to go and believe
me we'll be tough and aggressive in Texas and across this country
and I think we're going to beat them in Texas,'' Dukakis said.
   Dukakis also defended his new ads portraying Bush as an
issue-less candidate controlled by advisers.
   ``I wanted to express the very strong feeling that I have and
that I think many have that the Bush campaign is essentially a
packaged candidacy and it's important for people to understand
that,'' said Dukakis.
   A new set of 30-second ads to be aired nationally starting
Wednesday made a more direct attack on Bush and his record on drug
enforcement, education, the environment and Social Security. The
four ads said the administration dealt secretly with Manuel Antonio
Noriega, ``the Panamanian drug lord,'' Bush ``personally'' weakened
environmental regulations, ``personally'' cast the tie-breaking
vote to cut Social Security'' and ``sat by while college loans for
working families were cut.''
   The governor also rejected assertions by a former Iranian
official that the Democratic nominee had an emissary seeking to
establish a line of communication with Iran and said he hoped the
former official's assertion that Bush had an aide involved in
hostage negotiations was untrue.
   ``I would hope that, and I believe, that these efforts to
release the hostages have nothing to do with this campaign,''
Dukakis said. ``These families and these hostages have been through
too much pain and too much agony and too much tragedy as it is. ...
Certainly nobody representing me or someone authorized by me is
engaged in those kind of discussions.''
   As for the debate, Dukakis opened his news conference by saying
it was a day ``that we've been waiting a long time for.''
   Dukakis, seemingly discussing the debate, said he was ``a little
nervous'' and that he had been told by aides to try to lower
expectations.
   ``I'm rejecting the advice of my staff,'' Dukakis said as
reporters leaned forward for his prediction. ``The Red Sox are
going to win.''
   His prediction proved wrong. The Red Sox lost 2-1.
   On a more serious note, Dukakis said he expected Bentsen to ``do
himself and the Democratic ticket proud.''

</TEXT>
