<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0689,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor Receives Another Transfusion, Temperature Remains High</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with another transfusion, temperature still above
100. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito's temperature remained well above
normal early Thursday and doctors gave him another blood
transfusion to counteract internal bleeding, palace officials said.
   The 87-year-old Hirohito, who fell ill when he vomited blood
Sept. 19, received four-tenths of a pint of blood in the
transfusion Thursday morning, officials said.
   He received 0.63 pints of blood from two transfusions Wednesday,
said Kenji Maeda, head of the general affairs department of the
Imperial Household Agency. The world's longest-reigning living
monarch has received 11.98 pints since falling ill.
   Maeda told reporters the emperor's temperature was 100.58
Thursday morning. Wednesday morning his fever was 98.6 and
increased to 100.94 in the afternoon.
   Hirohito has not been able to consume solid food except for a
few spoonfuls of porridge. He is being fed intravenously.
   Crown Prince Akihito, Princess Michiko, and their two sons
visited Hirohito at his palace home Wednesday. Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita visited Akihito at his Togu Palace.
   The emperor has no political power but serves as a symbol of
Japan.
</TEXT>
