<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-Simon&Simon ADV06   10-05 0742</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Simon & Simon, ADV 06,0754</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs PMs, Oct. 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Unsinkable `Simon & Simon' Back on the Air</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Since 1981, CBS' ``Simon & Simon'' has led a
charmed life, or a star-crossed one, depending on how you look at
it.
   It's the eighth season for this odd-couple detective series. The
show's been up, down and around. It was a flop its first time out,
and CBS renewed it only at the eleventh hour. Then it became a hit,
until it ran into ``The Cosby Show'' and NBC's Thursday night
juggernaut.
   There was even a brouhaha a few years ago when CBS tried to move
the show's locale from San Diego to Los Angeles. San Diego, still
smarting over the loss of ``Harry O.,'' mounted a postcard campaign
that caused CBS to back down.
   ``They've been beating on us for eight years,'' said Gerald
McRaney, who co-stars with Jameson Parker as brother detectives.
``They can't get us down for the count. I think the show has
survived for the most part because we've got good scripts. And we
don't take ourselves too seriously.
   ``The relationship between the brothers and the notion of a
family make it work. That would have worked in Elizabethan theater.
Loyalty and integrity. People like to see those values reaffirmed.''
   ``Simon & Simon,'' which returns Saturday, tells the story of
two brothers who are unalike, yet supportive of each other. McRaney
is Rick, rough, eccentric, laid back, who'd rather pluck his guitar
and have fun. Parker is A.J., conservative, a snappy dresser, whose
ambition and hard work keeps their detective agency on track.
   ``A lot of detective shows steer clear of comedy,'' said
McRaney. ``That makes us one of the few one-hour comedy shows on
the air. We do a few serious episodes. But we have a sibling
rivalry, and that's what makes it fun.
   ``From the beginning, Jameson and I participated in shaping the
show. We weren't just hired help. The creator, Philip DeGuere,
wanted us to be a part of it. I've directed five shows and written
one. We read through the scripts every week and our suggestions are
listened to seriously.''
   The show was originally set in Florida and was called ``Pirate's
Key.'' That was before ``Miami Vice,'' and neither Universal
Television nor CBS was too keen on filming it in Florida. The
locale was changed to San Diego, although most of the show is
filmed in Los Angeles.
   Mary Carver, who plays mother to the pair, is still with the
series. But other cast members have come and gone as the show has
changed through the years. Jeannie Wilson and Eddie Barth from the
original cast have left, as has Tim Reid, who was Detective
Downtown Brown. Reid stars in ``Frank's Place'' on CBS.
   This summer, McRaney worked on two TV movies. ``The People
Across the Lake,'' a Gothic mystery co-starring Valerie Harper, was
shown on NBC this past Monday.
   He also took a small role in the CBS movie ``Where the Hell's
the Gold?'' so he could spend some time with his fiancee, Delta
Burke of ``Designing Women.'' The Western comedy also stars Willie
Nelson and Jack Elam.
   ``We shot it in southern Colorado and northern New Mexico,''
said McRaney, who has a second home in Telluride, Colo. ``We used a
narrow-gauge railroad which runs through some beautiful country. My
ambition is to rob the Durango & Silverton Railroad from horseback.
My partner and I want to take a dollar from the engineer.''
   McRaney is also at work creating a new comedy series for himself
for that day when ``Simon & Simon'' finally does come to an end. He
also has a script for himself and Miss Burke for a lighthearted
mystery set in New Orleans. They spent a month in New Orleans this
summer and spent a week on the Mississippi Queen riverboat.
   Wedding plans are indefinite, but Miss Burke, who's from
Florida, and McRaney, from Mississippi, do want to tie the knot in
an old Southern plantation house.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   MOSCOW PILOT _ Mathias Rust, the young German pilot recently
freed after a prison stint in the Soviet Union, will tell the story
of his intrusion into Russian air space and landing his small plane
in Red Square on ABC's ``Incredible Sunday'' Oct. 16.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thurs PMs, Oct. 6</NOTE>
