<1ST_LINE>s p BC-Election-Economy-Glance ADV09   10-05 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Election-Economy-Glance, ADV 09,0186</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv09</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 9</NOTE>
<HEAD>With BC-Election-Economy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here in brief are some 1988
presidential-election predictions by economists and other
academics, and how they came up with them:
   Data Resources Inc., an economic consulting firm in Lexington,
Mass., predicts Bush will win the election with 55 percent of the
vote. The DRI model studies economic growth and inflation in the 12
months before the election.
   Ray Fair, economics professor, Yale University, predicts Bush
will win with 51.8 percent of the vote. His model focuses on the
inflation rate for the two years before the election and per capita
economic growth for six to nine months before the election.
   Allan Lichtman, history professor, American University, predicts
a Bush victory based on answers to 13 yes-no questions on the
economy, the candidates' charisma and the record of the incumbent
party.
   Harold Zullow, psychology professor, University of Pennsylvania,
predicts a 5 percent victory margin for Dukakis. His model is based
on how optimistically the candidates address problems in their
acceptance speeches at the political conventions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
