<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Fiat-Chrysler     10-05 0150</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Fiat-Chrysler,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fiat, Chrysler Discuss Distribution Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TURIN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fiat, Italy's largest auto maker, on
Wednesday confirmed printed reports that it is holding preliminary
talks with Chrysler Corp. aimed at exploiting the U.S. automaker's
extensive distribution network.
   Fiat officials emphasized that the commercial agreement being
considered would boost sales of Alfa Romeo models.
   Alfa Romeo, taken over by Fiat in January 1987, sells about
6,000 of its sportscars in the United States each year. It hopes to
sell 60,000 of its brand-new 164 sedan on the U.S. market by the
end of 1990.
   A Fiat spokesman denied the talks included any possible joint
venture to produce components. He also ruled out a possible
exchange of shares between the two companies.
   Fiat's relationship with Chrysler dates back to a number of
years. Chrysler was one of the first companies to install robots
supplied by a Fiat automation unit.
</TEXT>
