<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 0057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   10-05 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0574</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House narrowly has sustained President
Reagan's veto of a bill that would have tightened curbs on imports
of textiles and apparel.
   The House on Tuesday fell 11 votes short of the two-thirds
necessary to override the veto and turn the bill into law.
   Supporters said the measure would save jobs, but opponents said
it would mean price increases amounting to a fresh tax on consumers.
   The bill would have frozen 1988 textile, non-rubber footwear and
apparel imports at last year's level. It would have allowed a 1
percent annual increase in imports of footwear and apparel
beginning in January.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Automakers say they have completed their
third-best sales year ever, with sales of 15.6 million cars and
light trucks in the 1988 model year.
   Sales were up 0.7 percent from the 1987 model year, when 15.5
million were sold. The 1988 total does not include a few of the
small-volume foreign makers, which were scheduled to release
figures Wednesday.
   Expectations were that sales would be flat or down slightly,
said analyst Mary Anne Sudol of Fitch Investors Service Inc. of New
York. 1986 was the biggest sales year, followed by 1985.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The investment firm of Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &
Co. has raised its takeover offer for Kroger Co. to $5.03 billion,
rivaling a planned $4.6 billion defensive restructuring announced
by the grocery giant last month.
   Kohlberg Kravis said Tuesday that based on its assessment of the
restructuring proposal, it was willing to pay $64 in cash and
securities for each of Kroger's 78.6 million shares outstanding. It
had offered $58.50 in cash and securities previously.
   Cincinnati-based Kroger said it was reviewing the new offer and
had no other comment late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co.'s stock skyrocketed after
Britain's Grand Metropolitan PLC launched a surprise $5.17 billion
tender offer that some experts say the food conglomerate may be
forced to accept.
   The offer, which caught the nation's fourth largest food company
off guard, would pay Pillsbury stockholders $60 in cash for each of
the 86.2 million common shares outstanding.
   Pillsbury soared $18.37{ a share to $57.37{ Tuesday in heavy
trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Metropolitan PLC says its $5.17 billion
tender offer for Pillsbury Co. is part of a larger strategy to
focus on foods, liquor and retailing, and to expand those
businesses abroad.
   Grand Metropolitan's products include J & B Scotch whisky,
Smirnoff vodka, Alpo pet foods and Pearle vision care centers.
   A takeover of Pillsbury would be the largest foreign acquisition
by a British company outside the oil industry. The offer was made
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scandinavian Airlines System and Texas Air Corp.
have reached a cooperative agreement under which SAS will pay $50
million to lease airport gates in the New York area and have the
option to buy up to 10 percent of Texas Air's stock.
   The companies will also coordinate advertising, reservations and
scheduling and establish a joint training program for airline
personnel, they said Tuesday.
   Texas Air, the largest U.S. airline company, owns Continental
Airlines and Eastern Airlines, which have been hurt by financial
losses, labor problems and complaints about service.
</TEXT>
