<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC's coverage of the Summer Olympics dominated
two weeks of prime time but concluded Sunday with an average rating
below the guarantee NBC gave advertisers, and that will cost the
network millions.
   NBC, which paid more than $300 million for the rights to the
Olympics, will not comment on the loss.
   The Wall Street Journal reported Tuesday the network will have
to give as much as $70 million in commercial time to advertisers
who didn't get as high a rating as they were promised.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's government has ordered the Kuwait
Investment Office to slash its 21.68 percent stake in British
Petroleum Co. PLC by more than half.
   The government said Tuesday the holding could conflict with the
public interest and gave the Kuwaiti concern a year to reduce its
stake to no more than 9.9 percent.
   The reduction is likely to result in a huge loss for the
London-based investment arm of the Kuwaiti government, which said
it was ``extremely dissatisfied'' with the decision.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The people who engineered a seven-year boycott
against Nestle SA to fight the promotion of infant formula in Third
World nations want to resume the battle.
   Douglas A. Johnson, chairman of Action for Corporate
Accountability, called Tuesday for a renewal of the boycott,
arguing Nestle has failed to live up to the agreements it signed in
1984 that ended the original action.
   This time, said Johnson, the group is expanding the boycott to
American Home Products Corp., which it said is the second largest
distributor of infant formula in developing nations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank of New York Co. has won another legal
battle in its yearlong $1.2 billion bid to acquire Irving Bank Corp.
   An appeals court Tuesday struck down a key provision of Irving's
``poison pill'' anti-takeover defense.
   But Irving said it would ask the state's highest court, the
Court of Appeals, to review the ruling from the New York State
Supreme Court's appellate division.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Banking Committee has voted in favor
of abolishing the much-criticized federal agency created to manage
and dispose of the assets of insolvent savings institutions.
   The Federal Asset Disposition Association was formed by the
Federal Home Loan Bank Board in 1985 to assist the Federal Savings
and Loan Insurance Corp. in the management of acquired assets.
   FADA has been accused by members of Congress of favoritism,
conflicts of interest and mismanagement of the $3.9 billion in
loans and real estate in its care. The committee voted Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market declined for the third consecutive session
Tuesday. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 3.20
points to 2,102.06.
   The dollar and gold finished mixed.
   Bond prices were unchanged to slightly lower.
   Crude oil futures prices steadied, while grain and soybean
futures rallied.
