<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     10-05 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Steady, But Outlook Remains Bearish</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Analysts say the outlook for crude oil futures
prices remains negative, despite recent stability.
   The November contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
U.S. crude, rose 1 cent Tuesday to settle at $13.07 a barrel on the
New York Mercantile Exchange.
   The contract skidded 86 cents over Friday and Monday to $13.06 a
barrel, the lowest close for a near-term WTI contract since August
1986.
   Concerns about oversupply of crude have brought prices down by
about $2 a barrel over the past five weeks. Those concerns were
heightened Monday by Saudi Arabia's threat to step up its crude
output unless other members of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries abide by their OPEC production quotas.
   Oil prices opened higher Tuesday amid rumors that OPEC would
move its ministerial meeting, scheduled for November, up to later
this month, said John Azarow, a trader with Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc.
   An early meeting raises speculation over the prospect of an
agreement among OPEC members to rein in the cartel's production.
   But the rally, which analysts said was based on technical
factors, soon ran out of steam. The November crude contract went as
high as $13.30 a barrel before slipping back.
   ``We're still in a bear market,'' said Jim Fiedler, a trader
with E.D.&F. Man International Futures Inc. ``The market was
expecting a rally of up to the $13.70 level and they haven't been
able to get it.''
   Besides OPEC rumors, there was no news to affect trading,
analysts said.
   ``The main thing goes back to the concerns about the Saudi
overproduction,'' Fiedler said.
   Among refined products traded on the Mercantile Exchange, the
November contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline fell 0.87 cent to
41.11 cents a gallon, while home heating oil rose 0.39 cent to
38.17 cents a gallon.
   Azarow said some of the movement in refined products was due to
seasonal factors, such as a decline in driving that lowers demand
for gas and the onset of cooler weather that increases heating oil
use.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881005-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 0011EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Kroger Bjt   10-05 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kroger, Bjt,0676</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kohlberg Raises Offer for Supermarket Chain to $5.03 Billion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lede prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL MENEZES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. hasn't yet
launched a formal hostile takeover of Kroger Co., but in sweetening
its buyout proposal for the supermarket giant it has outlined plans
to keep stepping up the buyout pressure.
   Kohlberg Kravis late Tuesday offered to pay $64 a share in cash
and securities for each of Kroger's 78.6 million outstanding
shares, an indicated total of $5.03 billion, and repeated its
request to meet with the Kroger board.
   The amount of the latest proposal topped not only the buyout
firm's previous offer of $58.50 a share, or about $4.6 billion, but
also the proposed $4.6 billion restructuring plan that Kroger's
board of directors approved last month to thwart any outside
takeover.
   Furthermore, Kohlberg Kravis indicated that if Kroger decided to
go through with the restructuring, the firm was willing to buy the
surviving company _ and it hinted Kohlberg also might be willing to
take its offer directly to Kroger shareholders.
   ``We have come forth with what we believe is an exceptional
offer for your company's shareholders and we are confident that, if
given the opportunity, your shareholders would embrace it,''
Kohlberg Kravis said in a letter to the board of Cincinnati-based
Kroger.
   Kohlberg Kravis announced its sweetened offer after the close of
stock trading Tuesday in New York. Kroger shares dipped 87{ cents
to $55.37{ a share in heavy trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
   ``The Kroger Company's management, legal and financial advisers
are reviewing the second unsolicited proposal from KKR,'' Paul
Bernish, a spokesman for Kroger, said late Tuesday. He said the
company had no further comment.
   Kroger has been resisting overtures from Kohlberg Kravis and the
Haft family of Maryland, which had offered $4.32 billion, or $55 a
share, for Kroger.
   Kohlberg Kravis specializes in leveraged buyouts _ purchases
made with mostly borrowed money that is repaid with funds from the
target company's operations or the sale of its assets.
   The firm rarely has engaged in an outright hostile takeover,
partly because the success of its deals often depends on having
existing management remain with the target company.
   But as its coffers have bulged with money from investors anxious
to participate in buyouts _ Kohlberg Kravis has an estimated $5.6
billion warchest that can be used as equity to leverage about seven
times that amount _ pressure has mounted for the firm to be more
aggressive in creating deals.
   Kohlberg Kravis' sweetened offer includes $50 in cash, $11 in
debt securities and $3 in stock of the new company that Kohlberg
Kravis would create from Kroger. The investment firm's earlier
offer contained the same cash portion of $50 but only $8.50 in
securities.
   Kroger's restructuring announced Sept. 13 would pay stockholders
a special dividend of $40 a share in cash, securities valued at $8
plus stock in the surviving company, valued at $5 to $10 a share.
   Kohlberg Kravis said that if Kroger undertook the plan, Kohlberg
would be willing to acquire the stock in the restructured company
for $13.50 a share _ $10 in cash and $3.50 a share in debentures.
As such, Kroger stockholders would realize a total of $61.50 a
share in cash and securities from both parties.
   The investment firm noted the alternative, post-retructuring
buyout would be for $2.50 a share less than its up-front offer, and
said the difference reflected its estimates of financing fees
Kroger would have to pay under the restructuring plan, plus
Kohlberg's added costs in financing Kroger debt incurred in the
restructuring.
   Kroger's restructuring also includes layoffs and the sale of
operations, in order to streamline the company and cut costs.
   Kroger operates more than 1,300 supermarkets, 935 convenience
stores and 15 membership warehouses in 29 states. The company also
processes food products for sale in its stores and to outside
customers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
