<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 0113EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Pillsbury Bjt   10-05 0674</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pillsbury, Bjt,0699</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pillsbury Fighting Takeover Bid From Britain's Grand Met</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED STYCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In launching a $5.17 billion bid for
Pillsbury Co., Britain's Grand Metropolitan PLC is proposing to
strip Pillsbury of a division that has helped make the company
vulnerable to a takeover.
   Grand Metropolitan said in a filing with the Securities and
Exchange Commission that if its $60-a-share bid begun Tuesday
succeeds, it would sell Pillsbury's Steak & Ale and Bennigan's
restaurant operations.
   The under-performing full-service restaurant division was
restructured in January, resulting in a $91 million charge that has
dragged down earnings. The restructuring also precipitated
management changes, including the hiring of former General Foods
Corp. chairman Philip L. Smith as its own new chairman in July.
   Grand Metropolitan indicated it would sell Steak & Ale and
Bennigan's because of state laws prohibiting a company from owning
both alcoholic beverage makers and retailers.
   Pillsbury is using that issue to challenge the takeover bid,
although by Tuesday it had not actually or approved of the offer.
   In a statement issued late Tuesday, Smith said Pillsbury had
sued to block the acquisition in 13 states, contending a buyout by
Grand Met would violate liquor laws prohibiting producers from
owning liquor retailers.
   Courts in Texas, Oklahoma, New Mexico, Michigan, Kansas,
Pennsylvania and Missouri have issued temporary restraining orders
enjoining Grand Met from acquiring any Pillsbury stock, and a
Delaware court has rejected Grand Met's effort to stop those
actions, Pillsbury said.
   Grand Met, a $10 billion a year diversified company, is one of
the world's biggest wine and spirit makers, with brands that
include Smirnoff Vodka, J&B Scotch, Gilbey's Gin, Watney and Ushers
ale and Almaden wines.
   In a separate statement, Pillsbury said that its board would
review the offer ``at an appropriate time.''
   Smith said at the company's annual shareholders' meeting in
September that one of his chief goals was keeping the company
independent. But on Tuesday, industry analysts doubted Pillsbury
could defend itself against the takeover bid and remain independent.
   Pillsbury stock soared by $18.50 a share to $57.50 on the New
York Stock Exchange Tuesday, the first trading session after Grand
Met made its offer.
   ``It's going to be a bid that Pillsbury management is going to
have difficulty defending against,'' said John M. McMillen, an
analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York. ``I think
they'll fight it initially _ attempt to fight it _ but I think it's
a losing battle.''
   Ian A. Martin, Grand Metropolitan's chief executive for U.S.
operations, said Tuesday in Minneapolis that he is ``very
interested in doing this thing in a gentlemanly manner.''
   Pillsbury's struggling restaurant division, which includes the
Burger King fast-food chain, provides about half Pillsbury's $6.2
billion in annual revenue. Martin said Grand Metropolitan would
keep Burger King but would sell Distron, Pillsbury's in-house
distribution system for Burger King.
   London-based Grand Metropolitan also owns hotels, the Alpo pet
food company, Pearle vision centers, and a chain of betting offices
in England and Ireland.
   Analysts speculated Grand Metropolitan was most interested in
Pillsbury for its Green Giant vegetable, Haagen-Dazs ice cream and
Van de Kamp's frozen fish operations.
   Martin said there were good prospects for marketing Pillsbury's
food products overseas, especially its microwavable foods. Further,
Grand Metropolitan proposed in a letter to Smith that Minneapolis
become the headquarters of a Grand Met international foods group.
   Martin, who met with a number of state officials while waiting
for a response from Pillsbury, said Grand Metropolitan decided to
move aggressively with a tender offer because Pillsbury officials
had indicated that ``if anyone came near the drawbridge, they would
have a real cat-and-dog fight.''
   Grand Metropolitan filed suit on Monday in Delaware Chancery
Court to invalidate Pillsbury's ``poison pill'' takeover defense,
which would make a hostile merger prohibitively expensive.
Pillsbury is incorporated in Delaware.
   Pillsbury also might seek protection from Minnesota lawmakers,
who met in special session last year to pass legislation protecting
Minneapolis-based Dayton Hudson Corp. from a possible hostile
takeover bid by the Haft family.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881005-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 0117EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-LTVSteel-Sale     10-05 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LTV Steel-Sale,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LTV Corp. Putting Steel Bar Division Up For Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LTV Steel Co. of Cleveland, a subsidiary of
Dallas-based LTV Corp., plans to sell its Ohio-based steel bar
division as part of the parent company's reorganization under
federal bankruptcy laws.
   ``The company had indicated several months ago that it did not
intend to reorganize with what it considered marginally profitable
operations,'' said Joseph Coyle, director of the United Steel
Workers of America District 27.
   LTV Corp. has hired Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. to help find a
qualified buyer for the division.
   Shearson also recently helped LTV Steel find a buyer _ Warren
Consolidated Industries Inc. _ for its Warren mill and its Republic
Drainage Products plant in Canton.
   LTV Steel's bar division employs about 5,400 salaried or hourly
workers, and the union represents about 4,200, with 3,200 at Ohio
operations in Canton and Massillon.
   Company representatives met Tuesday in Canton with public and
union officials.
   ``There's always uncertainty and some apprehension. The company
assured us it's their intention to sell to a purchaser with a
commitment to keep it profitable and more profitable in the
future,'' Coyle said.
   J. Peter Kelly, LTV Steel executive vice president, said at a
news conference following the meeting there was no deadline set for
a sale.
   ``The process will necessarily take a considerable period of
time,'' Kelly said. ``Precisely what that will be is impossible for
us to forecast, but it is nothing that is going to happen tonight,
next week or even next month.''
   Separate management, marketing, sales, customer service,
engineering and research operations already exist in the bar
division, LTV Steel President David H. Hoag said in a statement.
   ``The bar division is well positioned and prepared to operate
apart from LTV Steel,'' Hoag said. He described the division as a
leading producer of high quality carbon and alloy steel bars.
   Raymond A. Hay, LTV chairman and chief executive officer, said
the steel segment is trying to focus on flat-rolled and tubular
products.
   ``We have concluded that LTV Steel must focus its resources on
its large, modern flat-rolled facilities in order to maintain a
leadership position in production of high-quality, value-added
steels for critical engineering applications,'' Hay said in a
statement issued from Dallas.
</TEXT>
