<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 0809EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NBCBuyouts     10-05 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NBC Buyouts,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Network To Offer Buyouts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE ANDERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC says it will offer buyouts to as many as 140
engineers and technicians in an effort to trim at least 40
employees from its work force.
   Dom Giofre, a spokesman for the television network, said the
buyout offer was prompted by the recent sale of NBC's radio
operation and by the winding down of 1988 political coverage.
   ``I don't think this really comes as a real surprise to
anyone,'' said Michael Sherlock, NBC President of Operations and
Technical Services.
   He said only employees in New York are involved.
   NBC has has dramatically reduced its payroll since it was
acquired by General Electric Co. two years ago.
   About 400 people in the news division have lost their jobs and
another 110 are scheduled to go before the end of the year.
   The engineers and technicians were scheduled to be notified
beginning today in a series of meetings with supervisors.
   ``If all 140 people accept, they will pay it, although they are
aiming to cut only 40 positions,'' said Paul McElroy, a spokesman
for Local 11 of the National Association of Broadcast Employees and
Technicians.
   Workers will have until Nov. 10 to accept the voluntary offer.
   Those who accept will continue to receive regular paychecks as
well as health and other benefits through the end of the year. The
balance of the severance would be paid in a lump sum on Jan. 2,
Sherlock said.
   Currently, NBC employs about 1,000 technicians, down by 300
since a 118-day strike in 1987.
</TEXT>
