<2ND_LINE>BC-Clark Oil,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bidding War Expected For Oil Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Getty Petroleum Corp. executive says a bidding
war has erupted over bankrupt Clark Oil & Refining Corp., a leading
Midwest discount gasoline marketer.
   Stephen Salzman, Getty's senior vice president, said Tuesday
that his company plans to submit a bid for Clark and other assets
of Apex Oil Co. that will top the $650 million offered by
Toronto-based Horsham Corp.
   Salzman said Getty's proposal will be filed in U.S. Bankruptcy
Court in St. Louis by late Monday. Getty is based in Jericho, N.Y.
   Bruce Walter, a Horsham vice president, promised a battle for
the company.
   ``It had been our intention to acquire Clark Oil,'' he said.
``We've invested a significant amount of time and money in
developing and structuring this transaction,'' he said. ``We will
not give up the fight easily.''
   Clark, acquired by Clayton, Mo.-based Apex Oil in 1981, owns
about 958 gas stations in 12 states as well as a dozen fuel
terminals and two small factories in Illinois.
   Under terms of a plan submitted in bankruptcy court five weeks
ago, a Horsham subsidiary would acquire Clark and other Apex
properties, including a Colorado ski resort, for cash and the
assumption of debt at a discount.
   Among Horsham's partners in the deal is Samuel Zell, the Chicago
investor whose burgeoning business empire includes Itel Corp.
   Zell said recently that he and Horsham want Clark because they
believe the refining and marketing business will be a steady
money-maker during a period of anticipated low oil prices.
   Under the timetable set by the bankruptcy court, the rival bids
will be reviewed next week. A full hearing on the purchase will be
held Oct. 31, when the judge could approve one of the proposals.
</TEXT>
