<HEAD>McKesson Drops Plans to Acquire Alco, Northwestern</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McKesson Corp., the nation's largest drug
distributor, has called off its proposed acquisition of Alco Health
Services Corp., the nation's third largest drug wholesaler.
   In Tuesday's announcement, the companies sited a decision by the
Federal Trade Commission to move to block the merger.
   McKesson offered $500 million in June for Alco, based in Valley
Forge, Pa., and extended the offer five times when the companies
couldn't agree on the price.
   The FTC on Monday authorized its staff to seek a preliminary
injunction against the plan.
   McKesson also said on Tuesday it will abandon plans to buy
Northwestern Drug Co. of Auburn, Wash. McKesson offered about $200
million for the drug wholesaler.
   The National Association of Retail Druggists contends the
McKesson-Alco merger would give the companies 50 percent of the
drug distribution market in the United States, according to Tim
Feagans, an attorney for Alco.
   The commission said both the acquisition of Alco and
Northwestern could significantly reduce competition.
</TEXT>
