<1ST_LINE>u f PM-SAS-TexasAir 2ndLd-Writethru   10-05 0805</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAS-Texas Air, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0831</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SAS, Texas Air Sign Cooperation Pact</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS new 4th graf to UPDATE with no comment from Texas Air;
picks up 4th graf pvs bg'ng, Some say ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new $50 million agreement between Scandinavian
Airlines System and Texas Air Corp. is designed to strengthen the
competitive positions of both companies, officials say.
   Separately, a report published today said Texas Air is holding
discussions to sell its East Coast air shuttle to developer Donald
Trump. According to unidentified sources quoted by The Wall Street
Journal, the pricetag on the three-city shuttle is in the $200
million range.
   As evidence the shuttle is up for sale, Journal sources noted
that planes and lounge areas have been refurbished, and attendants
are getting new uniforms. The service is run by Eastern Airlines.
   Texas Air declined comment on the Journal report, said Mark
Johnson, a spokesman for the airline company. Representatives of
Trump weren't immediately available for comment.
   Some say Trump might use the shuttle, which operates between
Washington, New York and Boston, to help draw people to his hotel
and casino properties in Atlantic City, N.J.
   Trump already operates a helicopter service between New York and
Atlantic City.
   Under Texas Air's agreement with SAS, the Scandinavian airline
will lease airport gates in the New York area and have the right to
buy up to 10 percent of Texas Air's stock on the open market.
   The accord, signed Tuesday, also includes provisions for
coordinating marketing, reservations and scheduling, and the
companies will establish a joint training program for airline
workers.
   Texas Air, the largest U.S. airline company, owns Continental
Airlines and Eastern Airlines, which have been hurt by financial
losses, labor problems and complaints about service.
   SAS, renowned for service but weak in scheduling connections to
the United States, has been seeking ways of positioning itself to
exploit the era of European deregulation that will begin in 1992.
   ``Our aim is to maximize efficiency and provide the best
professional service to business travelers anywhere in the world,''
Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo told reporters at a New York press
briefing.
   Under the agreement, SAS will pay Continental $15 million to
lease three gates at Newark International Airport in New Jersey,
beginning next spring. SAS will pay Eastern $10 million for a
similar lease arrangement at New York's John F. Kennedy
International Airport in 1991.
   SAS also will pay Texas Air $25 million.
   SAS will have the right to buy up to 10 percent of Texas Air's
stock on the open market, and SAS officials said they intended to
make the purchases within six months.
   Texas Air stock was the most actively traded issue Tuesday on
the American Stock Exchange, declining 12{ cents to $14.25. The
company has 39.9 million shares outstanding.
   Jan Carlzon, SAS president and chief executive officer, will
become a member of Texas Air's board of directors.
   The marriage of a financially pressed U.S. airline company and a
service-oriented European carrier makes sense for both, analysts
said.
   SAS will get the access to U.S. routes that it is seeking while
Texas Air will get cash that it needs, noted Anthony Hatch, an
analyst for Argus Research Corp.
   The agreement is not unprecedented, but it combines elements of
existing arrangements in a new way. United Airlines, the biggest
U.S. carrier, signed an agreement with British Airways late last
year setting up a worldwide marketing partnership.
   But unlike the accord between SAS and Texas Air, the
United-British Airways combination doesn't include an equity stake.
SAS' equity stake in Texas Air ``helps them cement the alliance,''
Hatch said.
   As European deregulation approaches, similar accords between
major airlines in the United States and Europe are likely to crop
up, said Andrew Geller, an airline analyst for Provident National
Bank in Philadelphia.
   In another case, Ansett Transport Industries Ltd., an Australian
conglomerate owned 50-50 by media tycoon Rupert Murdoch and
transportation company TNT Ltd., has a 20 percent stake in America
West Airlines, based in Tempe, Ariz. The two do not have a
cooperative agreement.
   Officials of SAS and Texas Air said they began discussions for
such an alliance about nine months ago, at Lorenzo's initiative.
SAS has similar arrangements with Thai International Airways of
Thailand, and recently purchased a stake in Argentina's national
carrier.
   Continental currently has services from Newark International
Airport to London and Paris, and from Miami to London. SAS, heavily
used by business travelers, flies between Scandinavia and four U.S.
cities: New York, Chicago, Los Angeles and Seattle.
   The Scandinavian flag carrier, 50 percent owned by the
governments of Sweden, Denmark and Norway, has tried to develop
what its management calls a ``global axis'' strategy to provide
travelers with the most convenient connections through a network of
cooperation pacts with other carriers.
</TEXT>
