<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-Boeing     10-05 0147</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Boeing,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's Second-Largest Airline To Buy Six Boeing 747s</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All Nippon Airways, Japan's second largest airline,
said Wednesday it will buy six Boeing 747-400 jumbo jets at a total
cost of $720 million.
   ANA spokesman Takayuki Shimada said the company will sign the
contract soon with Boeing Co., the giant U.S. aircraft manufacturer.
   He said ANA chose the 370-seat aircraft, which uses a two-man
cockpit crew, because it is fuel efficient and can fly farther than
current models.
   Shimada said the planes would be used on the Tokyo-Washington
and Tokyo-London routes.
   The first of the six aicraft will be delivered in May 1990,
Shimada said.
   Japan Air Lines, the nation's largest airline, has ordered 20 of
the 747-400 aircraft from the Seattle-based company.
   ANA, which flies mostly domestic routes, has 75 Boeing aircraft,
11 Lockheed Tristar jetliners and 16 Japanese-made YS-11 airplanes.
</TEXT>
