<1ST_LINE>r f BC-UnionCarbide     10-05 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Union Carbide,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Carbide Sues Seven Japanese Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union Carbide Corp.'s legal charges that
seven Japanese companies manipulated the price of a raw material
for computer chips are ``utterly baseless,'' one of the defendants
claims.
   Union Carbide sued Monday in U.S. District Court, asking for a
jury trial and an order prohibiting the seven from fixing prices
and controlling the export to Japan of polysilicon, the raw
material for silicon wafers.
   The lawsuit seeks damages for the losses Union Carbide suffered
as a result of the alleged conspiracy.
   The defendants are Komatsu Electronic Metals Co.; its parent
firm, Komatsu Ltd.; Mitsubishi Metal Co. Ltd.; Mitsubishi
subsidiary Nippon Silicon Co. Ltd.; Osaka Titanium Co. Ltd.;
Shinetsu Handotai Co. Ltd.; and Tokuyama Soda Co. Ltd.
   Komatsu Electronic Metals Co., together with its parent, Komatsu
Ltd., issued a joint statement calling the charges baseless.
   ``Although Union Carbide calls it an antitrust suit, its
complaint is really part of an ongoing contract dispute with KEM,
arising out of UCC's unfounded interpretation of its contract with
KEM,'' it said.
   The statements said Union Carbide is trying to recoup
``self-inflicted losses resulting from its own flawed business
decisions at the expense of a Japanese company that has adhered
fully to the letter and the spirit of its contractual obligations.''
   The suit by Danbury, Conn.-based Union Carbide claimed Komatsu
Electronic and other companies that purchased the material and
produced silicon wafers formed a ``polysilicon buyers' cartel'' in
1983.
   According to the lawsuit, the Japanese companies arranged to
``deplete inventories, to refrain from bidding against one another
for fixed supplies in order to minimize open market price increases
and otherwise set purchase prices.''
   Union Carbide said several U.S. polysilicon manufacturers have
been forced to exit the merchant market because of the defendants'
action.
   The defendants and other Japanese companies banded together and
pose as a silicon-wafer industry study group. However, they
secretly exchanged information about business costs, pricing,
supply and demand and strategic plans to the detriment of
non-Japanese companies, the suit said.
</TEXT>
