<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-PatentLaw     10-05 0126</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Patent Law,0131</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Urges Standardized Biotechnology Patent Laws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community
Commission Wednesday proposed EEC-wide patent legislation to
protect biotechnology inventions in the 12-nation trade bloc.
   National patent laws differ so much from one EEC nation to the
next that ``lack of legal certainty and lack of sufficient
protection is commonplace in the Community in this field,'' the
commission said.
   EEC scientists are at a disadvantage compared to their
colleagues in the United States and Japan, whose laws offer
``considerably more protection through patentability that is
currently available in Europe,'' the commission said.
   The U.S. Patent and Trademark Office has already granted a
patent on a man-made mouse from Harvard University. Japan is
expected to grant similar patents shortly.
</TEXT>
