<1ST_LINE>r f AM-DroughtInsurance     10-05 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Insurance,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Farmers Get Drought Insurance Checks; Others Battle Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Illinois farmers who received
controversial drought insurance coverage have begun to receive
payments, but for those involuntarily left without policies, the
legal fight continues, officials said Wednesday.
   Richard Carlson, assistant director of the state Insurance
Department, said the Chubb Group has mailed checks for more than $5
million to Illinois farmers who received the insurance coverage.
   Chubb, a New Jersey-based insurance group, has estimated that
1,058 Illinois farmers applied for coverage but only 263 of them
received drought insurance policies. Another 715 farmers accepted
the company's double-premium refund offer.
   Agents in the drought-stricken Cornbelt advertised the insurance
and accepted premium payments late this spring _ when many farmers
already suspected it would be a very dry growing season.
   When underwriters realized that 10 times the $30 million
intended issue had been sold, they raised the issue to $40 million
and issued policies only if applications were made by June 15.
   Those who received insurance coverage were guaranteed payments
if the rainfall in their counties from June through August was
below certain levels.
   Carlson said most payments to Illinois farmers are in the
$8,000-20,000 range. However, he said two farmers at Sheldon in
Iroquois County received $128,000 and $177,000 respectively.
   Carlson said Chubb so far has made drought insurance payments to
five farmers in Ford County, 29 in Iroquois County, 32 in Kankakee
County, 54 in Livingston County and one each in Champaign and
McLean counties.
   But many other farmers still hope to receive the drought
insurance they thought they purchased _ and the payments that would
boost their income significantly.
   One farm family told the Champaign-Urbana News-Gazette that they
paid an $18,000 premium but did not receive a policy. Instead, they
said Chubb refunded twice that amount as a ``goodwill'' gesture.
   However, the family said what they want is the insurance and the
payment they would be due under the coverage _ more than $160,000.
   Farmers who paid premiums all over the country are party to a
class-action suit in federal court in Cincinnati that seeks to
force Chubb to extend the coverage to anyone who paid a premium and
still wants the insurance.
   The state Insurance Department is trying to determine how many
Illinois farmers paid premiums and did not receive policies, so it
can calculate how much Chubb would owe to farmers in the state.
   Carlson said his department then is likely to file charges
against Chubb, focusing on the fact that the company did not clear
the policy with state officials before offering it for sale.
   ``Our bottom-line interest is protecting state farmers and
forcing the company to satisfy our farmers,'' said Carlson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
