<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneySurvey Bjt   10-05 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Survey, Bjt,0711</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Magazine: Americans Expect Economic Problems, But Not at Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than two-thirds of Americans surveyed want
to see the rich pay more taxes, while an increasing number of
people are growing disenchanted with the new tax law, according to
a poll released Wednesday.
   The sixth annual Money magazine survey on Americans and their
money also found many respondents expect the economy to run into
problems in the coming months. But those surveyed don't expect to
see their own financial situations worsen.
   The findings of the survey, conducted by Lieberman Research
Inc., were based on questionnaires completed by 2,370 adults
nationwide. The survey has a margin of error of plus or minus 3
percentage points.
   The survey, conducted last spring, was the first taken after
taxpayers had their initial encounter with filing returns under the
new tax law.
   Thirty-five percent of the respondents said the new law was less
fair than the old statute, while 17 percent said it was more fair,
15 percent said it was as fair, and 33 percent said they did not
know.
   In contrast, in a poll taken in October 1986, 22 percent of the
respondents said the new law was less fair, while 30 percent said
it was more fair, 11 percent said it was as fair and 37 percent did
not know.
   Asked whether they thought they would pay more or less taxes
under the new law, 37 percent said they thought they would pay more
taxes, 14 expected to pay less and 26 percent said they thought
their taxes would remain the same. Twenty-three percent said they
did not know.
   The survey indicated that most Americans want to see the wealthy
taxed more heavily.
   Sixty-nine percent of the respondents said they would be more
likely to vote in this election year for a candidate who supported
higher taxes for people earning more than $100,000 a year. Nine
percent said they would be less likely to vote for such a
candidate, while 22 percent said this campaign stance would not
affect their vote.
   Respondents were generally not sure over whether they thought
they would be better off financially under a Republican or
Democratic administration.
   Nearly half of those surveyed _ 46 percent _ had no opinion on
the matter. Twenty-eight percent said they would be better off
under a Democratic administration, while 26 percent said they would
be better off under the GOP.
   A majority of respondents expected the economy to run into
obstacles such as double-digit inflation, unemployment and a
serious recession.
   Fifty-three percent of those surveyed said they expected the
United States to have serious economic problems during the next
year, while 47 percent said they do not expect the economy to have
serious troubles.
   But most of the respondents did not expect economic problems to
worsen their own financial situations. Forty-seven percent expected
their financial situations to be better in one year's time.
Forty-three percent said they expected their financial situations
to be the same, while 10 percent expected their situations to get
worse.
   Asked how comfortable their standard of living was, 59 percent
of respondents said their standard of living was comfortable, while
41 percent said their standard of living was not comfortable. That
breakdown was unchanged from the 1987 and 1985 surveys, and little
different from the 1986 poll.
   Respondents' view of their standard of living increased along
with their income levels. For example, 83 percent of respondents in
upper income households said their standard of living was
comfortable, compared with 27 percent of those in lower-income
households.
   Upper-income households were defined as those with annual
incomes over $50,000, while lower-income households earned under
$15,000 a year.
   The survey was taken more than six months after the October 1987
stock market crash.
   As a result of the crash, 28 percent of the total respondents
and 48 percent of the stockholders said they had made changes in
the way they handle their finances, such as making more
conservative investments or saving more.
   Seventy-two percent of the total sample and 52 percent of the
stockholders said they had made no changes.
</TEXT>
