<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Royal-Carnival     10-05 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Royal-Carnival,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Partner Buys Royal Admiral to Stave Off Carnival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bid to merge two of the nation's largest cruise
lines was thwarted Wednesday when a Norwegian partner in Royal
Admiral Cruises Ltd. bought 70 percent of the company's stock for
$561 million, heading off a similar offer by Carnival Cruise Lines
Inc.
   The surprise announcement was made in Oslo, Norway, by Royal
Admiral minority stockholder Arne Wilhelmsen. He divulged that his
company, the Anders Wilhelmsen & Co. group, has exercised its right
of first refusal to purchase the balance of Royal Admiral's shares.
   ``This transaction will give Royal Admiral the flexibility and
opportunity to boldly move ahead with Royal Admiral's expansion
plans,'' Wilhelmsen said.
   He also announced his company is negotiating the formation of a
joint venture with an entity related to the Pritzker family, the
owner of the Hyatt and Hyatt International chain of 144 hotels.
   Royal Admiral's Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Richard D.
Fain said that under the proposed deal with the Pritzkers,
Wilhelmsen would turn around and sell them 50 percent of the cruise
company's stock.
   ``I think we're pleased that the situation has been clarified
and the uncertainty has been eliminated,'' Fain said. .
   Wilhelmsen's decision to exercise his right of first refusal
ended Carnival's identical $561 million offer for the 70 percent of
Royal Admiral's stock not already owned by Wilhelmsen. The two
cruise lines are based in Miami.
   Carnival President Micky Arison was cautious about the
announcement, saying only that ``we understand Wilhelmsen now has
30 days in which to close the transaction.''
   Carnival spokesman Tim Gallagher said the company would have no
further comment until it had studied the deal.
   Royal Admiral is the holding company for both Royal Caribbean
Cruise Lines and Admiral Cruises.
   Royal Admiral has eight large cruise ships, including the
world's largest, the 2,300-passenger Sovereign of the Seas, and is
building a new 1,600-passenger vessel in France. Carnival has about
the same number of ships, RCCL spokesman Rich Steck said.
   ``Pretty soon we're going to be announcing that we are building
one or two sister ships for Sovereign Of The Seas,'' Steck added.
   Wilhelmsen beat a deadline of October 10 to exercise his option
and in the past month has arranged for financing for the purchase
through Christiania Bank og Kreditkasse and Bank of Nova Scotia.
   Wilhelmsen was one of the three original partners in RCCL when
it was founded in 1970. Earlier this year he and another partner
formed Royal Admiral by joining it with Admiral Cruises, Steck said.
</TEXT>
