<1ST_LINE>u f AM-FoodPrices 1stLd-Writethru f0139 10-05 0697</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Food Prices, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0139,0715</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Food Prices Top Drought Related Levels, Investigators Report</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th and 7th grafs, The fierce, to CORRECT spelling of
``durum.''</NOTE>
<HEAD>Laserphoto WX15</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some food prices climbed above levels
explainable by the summer drought but no widespread price gouging
of grocery shoppers has been found thus far, congressional
investigators said Wednesday.
   ``Some price increases do appear higher than warranted by the
drought alone,'' Senate Agriculture Chairman Patrick J. Leahy,
D-Vt., said after receiving the report from the General Accounting
Office.
   After weighing the congressional investigative agency's
findings, however, he told a hearing of the committee that ``in
general, there do not seem to have been excessive price increases
across a broad range of products that use the drought as an
excuse.''
   Retail pasta prices increased 10.4 percent, cereal 7.1 percent
and white bread 8.2 percent from January through June, GAO
officials told the Agriculture Committee. They said 43 percent of
the pasta and cereal price rise and 57 percent of that for white
bread came before June.
   Pasta, cereal and white bread prices rose more between June and
August than they did in the same period last year, the GAO said.
   The fierce summer heat and shortage of rainfall, which surfaced
as an urgent problem in June, wrought some of its worst damage in
the northern Grain Belt where durum wheat used to manufacture pasta
is produced.
   Farm prices for durum as well as hard red spring wheat, a
primary ingredient in white bread, did increase this year in
contrast to 1987 but alone would not have explained the rise at the
retail level.
   As drought scorched feed and pasture lands, livestock producers
increasingly sold cattle for slaughter, creating a buyers market
and driving down prices. The decrease, however, was not reflected
in any savings for consumers at the supermarket, the investigators
said.
   Just why some prices rose beyond levels explainable as a
byproduct of the drought remains something of a mystery, GAO
officials said.
   It may have been because ``prices of packaging of food products
went up significantly this year,'' Mary Kenney of the GAO told the
committee.
   ``There could have been some labor cost increases ... we don't
know if there were,'' said John W. Harman, associate director of
the GAO's resources, community and economic development division.
   Senators said it would be unjust to put the blame for
unwarranted price increases on farmers, who receive only a minor
portion of the price that consumers pay for food.
   The price of farm commodities accounted for 30 percent of the
price of all food products last year. The bulk of the price tag
reflects transportation, processing, packaging, advertising and
other marketing expenses.
   After hearing the data, Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, said that
``conclusive evidence of price gouging has not been found but there
are some indications out there'' that the problem could develop
next year.
   The Agriculture Department has been trying to calm concerns
about unwarranted price increases. It estimates that the drought
will tack 1 percent onto the consumer price index for food this
year and perhaps 2 percent next year. Prices would be affected next
year because the drought has reduced stockpiled surpluses of some
crops, which drives up their prices.
   Sen. Kent Conrad, D-N.D., said he did not rule out that price
increases prior to June were related to the drought. He said he had
been expecting ``a hot dry summer'' and that the food industry,
``with its excellent sources of intelligence,'' might have done the
same.
   Steven D. Maurer, director of the Ohio Department of
Agriculture, appealed to the committee not to condemn farmers for
any increases.
   ``The farmer's share of the food market dollar has remained
relatively constant,'' he said.
   Food wholesaler-retailer Richard F. Bondareff, president of
Bonfeld Inc., said that his Virginia-based food stores have fought
to hold the line on prices, and in some cases kept them level
despite increases charged by suppliers for fear that higher price
tags would give competitors an edge.
   ``We try to do the right thing because of the competitive nature
of the business,'' he told the committee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881005-0297 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 1508EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   10-05 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0272</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices edged downward
while wheat prices advanced Wednesday at the Chicago Board of Trade
in a sluggish market under the influence of good harvesting
conditions and limited demand.
   Profit-taking among corn and soybean traders after Tuesday's
rallies pressured prices, held down by an outlook for favorable
harvesting weather for the next several days in the Corn Belt.
   An anticipated overnight frost in southern Missouri and other
key soybean-growing regions that would have threatened crops failed
to materialize and helped keep the lid on buying enthusiasm in the
bean pit, said Cathy Leow, assistant vice president at Thompson
McKinnon Securities, Inc. in New York.
   Wheat gained support from continued expectations that signing of
the U.S.-Soviet grain pact is near, she said.
   ``Anticipation is that once the U.S.-Russian agreement is
signed, the Soviets are likely to be given credit, and once they
get their credit, they'll be in the market to buy,'' Ms. Leow said.
   But, she said, activity in the grain and soybean pits remained
slow.
   ``When you've got good harvesting conditions and limited demand,
the market's going to be pretty sluggish,'' she said.
   At the close, wheat was 3 cents to 4 cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.26 a bushel; corn was {
cent to 2\ cents lower with December at $2.93\ a bushel; oats were
1 cent to 2{ cents lower, with December at $2.46} a bushel; and
soybeans were 3{ cents to 8{ cents lower, with November at $8.24 a
bushel.
</TEXT>
