<2ND_LINE>AM-Plant Walkout, 1st Ld-Writethru,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stalled Contract Talks Spur Strike by Chrysler Workers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with new information</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FENTON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 3,500 members of the United Auto
Workers union walked off their jobs Wednesday at a Chrysler Corp.
assembly plant when negotiators failed to meet a contract deadline.
   ``We worked through the night trying to resolve the issues but
were unable to reach an agreement,'' Chrysler spokesman Lloyd
Northard said in Highland Park, Mich., following the 10 a.m. CDT
walkout. ``Our labor relations people are still there trying to
reach an agreement.''
   Northard declined to specify the issues keeping the two sides
apart. A national agreement between Chrysler and the UAW was
reached in May.
   Chrysler's working agreements with 138 UAW locals expired at
midnight Sept. 14, but had been extended on day-to-day bases,
Northard said. Although many local agreements have been reached,
UAW Local 110 in Fenton notified the company last week it was
imposing Wednesday's deadline.
   A strike authorization vote was taken several months ago by
Local 110. Its members gave 88 percent approval last week to
extending the strike deadline beyond a Sept. 30 date that had been
set.
   Local president George Burr said negotiations were ongoing.
   ``We're prepared to go around the clock,'' Burr said. ``I'm not
going to break (them) off if we're getting somewhere.''
   Long-wheelbase minivans are assembled at the plant, where a
five-week walkout to protest stalled contract talks was staged by
UAW Local 110 members in 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
