<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SAS-Protest     10-05 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAS-Protest,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SAS Employees Denounce Texas Air Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employees of Scandinavian Airlines
System in Denmark reacted angrily when they heard that SAS had
signed a cooperation deal with Houston-based Texas Air Corp.,
newspaper reports said Wednesday.
   ``Texas Air Corp. is owned and managed by Francisco Lorenzo, who
is notorious in the aviation world. The entire existence of the
company is based on a poor product and unethical and often illegal
treatment of the employees,'' SAS' unions said in a statement.
   The labor groups branded Texas Air Chairman Lorenzo a ``union
buster'' and a strongly anti-union employer, the Copenhagen
newspaper Berlingske Tidende said.
   In the deal announced in New York Tuesday, SAS will get leases
on airport gates in the New York area and the right to buy up to 10
percent of Texas Air's stock on the open market.
   SAS will pay Texas Air $50 million under the accord, which also
includes provisions for coordinating marketing, reservations and
scheduling as well as training of airline personnel.
   ``Of all partners, (SAS President Jan) Carlzon has chosen the
worst possible,'' flight attendants union Chairman Per Espersen was
quoted as saying in the tabloid Ekstra Bladet.
   Lorenzo is a ``bandit whose contempt for humanity in this world
was exceeded only by (former Ugandan dictator) Idi Amin,'' Espersen
was quoted as saying.
   ``The allegations against Frank Lorenzo and Texas Air are no
doubt correct, but our Danish employees should realize that
American trade unionism has a completely different style than it
does here,'' SAS Vice President Frede Eriksen was quoted as saying.
   SAS, which is 50 percent owned by the governments of Sweden,
Denmark and Norway, has tried to develop what its management calls
a ``global axis'' strategy to provide travelers with the most
convenient connections through a network of cooperation pacts with
other carriers.
</TEXT>
