<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   10-05 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0523</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Takeover news and rumors dominated the action
Wednesday as the stock market posted a small gain.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which had fallen 10.85
points Monday and Tuesday, recovered 4.45 to 2,106.51.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 3 to 2 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
864 up, 576 down and 506 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 175.13 million
shares, up from 157.76 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 211.44 million shares.
   Analysts said nothing had taken place to stir the market out of
its recent lethargy.
   Traders have been leery of making big commitments for several
days now, awaiting Friday's report from the Labor Department on the
employment situation for September.
   Many analysts are projecting that the figures will show strong
job growth, which would presumably revive concerns at the Federal
Reserve and elsewhere about inflation.
   Given that uncertainty, many traders focussed their attention of
takeover news and speculation.
   Kroger rose 3[ to 58] in active trading. The investment firm of
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. sweetened its buyout bid for the
company.
   Pillsbury, target of a $60-a-share takeover bid by Grand
Metropolitan PLC, led the active list and gained 1[ to 58[.
   Irving Bank Corp. rose 3} to 73{, and Bank of New York dropped }
to 34[. After a long battle, Irving agreed to be acquired by Bank
of New York.
   Rumors and conjecture over possible future takeover candidates
sparked activity in such other stocks as Pennwalt, which rose 5 to
94{; Kimberly-Clark, which gained 3} to 62], and Rorer, which was
up 2} at 40{.
   On the downside, Goodyear Tire & Rubber tumbled 3| to 53|. The
company estimated sharply lower third-quarter earnings from
continuing operations.
   Another prominent loser was Digital Equipment, a stock with a
wide following among investing institutions. It fell 3} to 88{,
trading at new 52-week lows.
   American depositary receipts of Japanese companies were also
broadly lower. Matsushita Electrical lost 5\ to 177{; Honda Motor
5\ to 151{; TDK 3\ to 61}, and Kyocera 2\ to 73{.
   DCNY dropped 1} to 23[. The company, whose main business is
dealing in government securities, said it had a net loss of $2.39
million in the third quarter.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $10.79 billion, or
0.40 percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks added
.69 to 153.62.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index rose 1.48 to 311.90, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index was up 1.24 at 271.86.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market edged
up .32 to 384.52. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 299.97, up .35.
