<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 1750EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Pillsbury     10-05 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pillsbury,0641</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Leaders Don't Fear Grand Metropolitan As They Did Dart</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED STYCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Metropolitan PLC, the British company
bidding to take over Pillsbury Co., isn't terrifying state
officials, lawmakers and charitable organizations as Dart Group
Corp. did when it tried to seize Dayton Hudson Corp. last year.
   ``I think it's certainly not a similar situation in many
respects,'' Senate Minority Leader Duane Benson, IR-Lanesboro, said
Wednesday.
   ``It doesn't appear to be a situation in which (Grand
Metropolitan) may come into the community, plunder and leave when
they're done.''
   Both Pillsbury and Dayton Hudson are Minneapolis-based companies
that have earned favorite-son status for their high levels of
charitable giving and general community do-gooding.
   Last year, Minnesotans were horrified when Dart, controlled by
the Haft family of Maryland, tried to acquire Dayton Hudson in a
hostile takeover.
   The Hafts, with a reputation as corporate raiders who made
millions from profits on the sale of stock acquired from companies
they tried to take over, were considered poor corporate citizens.
   The Minnesota Legislature rode to the rescue and swiftly acted
on Dayton Hudson's request to pass tough anti-takeover legislation
in a one-day special session.
   But because Pillsbury is incorporated in Delaware, the new
Minnesota anti-takeover laws offer no help to the food conglomerate.
   And, because Grand Metropolitan has quickly presented itself as
a responsible company that would do little to upset the status quo,
Benson said, the state may not be as hasty to help Pillsbury as it
was to help Dayton Hudson.
   ``It's going to be tough to do for them (Pillsbury), because
they're incorporated in Delaware, not here,'' Benson said. ``It
would have to be pretty specific legislation.''
   House Speaker Robert Vanasek, DFL-New Prague, agreed.
   ``I'm not too excited about seeing a Minnesota-based company
being taken over by one that's headquartered outside the United
States, but I don't think there's really anything we could do about
it,'' Vanasek said.
   Still, he said, ``The Dart group has a terrible reputation when
it comes to being raiders, and at least Grand Met seems to be a
pretty solid company.''
   Vanasek, Benson and other state leaders, including Gov. Rudy
Perpich, met with Grand Metropolitan officials Tuesday, the day
they officially made their $5.17 billion bid for Pillsbury.
   Ian Martin, chief executive of Grand Metropolitan's U.S.
operations, who had asked for the meeting, said the company wasn't
seeking political favors, only a ``level playing field'' in dealing
with Pillsbury.
   ``I thought after having gone through the whole Dayton Hudson
situation, this was strange,'' Benson said. ``It was a reversal.
Dart certainly didn't come to talk to us.''
   But Benson thought the presentation was helpful.
   ``I think it certainly gave us a chance to understand their
point of view and what their attempts are,'' he said.
   ``I got the impression that they're not a corporate raider. If
they're successful at taking Pillsbury over, they'll keep that high
community identity.''
   State Commerce Commissioner Michael Hatch said corporate
takeovers have changed since the Dayton Hudson deal. Now, companies
like Grand Metropolitan quickly approach politicians and the news
media to fend off negative publicity.
   ``What they (Grand Metropolitan) were trying to do was to
communicate the sincerity of their offer and that they do have a
background as a good corporate citizen,'' said Hatch, who also
attended Tuesday's meeting.
   Not only has Grand Metropolitan handled the situation
differently than Dart, Hatch said, but Pillsbury has handled it
differently than Dayton Hudson, which acted immediately after Dart
started its takeover attempt.
   Pillsbury, in a statement Tuesday, said its board would review
the Grand Met offer ``at an appropriate time.'' Company officials
refused to make further comment on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
