<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Rafts     10-05 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rafts,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Switches Raft Contract Amid Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy said Wednesday it is rejecting life
rafts made by a West Virginia company and has hired B.F. Goodrich
Co. to finish the job.
   Allegations were made earlier this summer about the quality and
reliability of Mark 6 rafts produced by Rubber Crafters Inc. of
Grantsville, W.Va., said Navy spokesman Lt. Ken Ross.
   ``In light of these allegations, we are in the process of
testing the Rubber Crafters rafts we have in the fleet to make sure
there are no defective rafts there,'' he said.
   The Navy signed a $9.9 million contract with Goodrich to produce
850 of the same type of life rafts that are the subject of an
investigation, according to Ross. The new contract calls for the
rafts to be delivered to the Navy by April 1990, although they may
be ready sooner.
   Rubber Crafters had been building the Mark 6 rafts since 1984,
he said. The company is being investigated by the Defense
Department and the FBI.
   Federal agents raided the company's plant and offices Aug. 8,
according to The Pittsburgh Press.
   ``We have stopped accepting rafts from Rubber Crafters. We have
a need for additional rafts in the fleet, so we let the contract to
BF Goodrich,'' Ross said.
   Rubber Crafters had delivered 2,200 rafts and was under contract
to deliver another 1,300, he said. The company won the contract by
outbidding Goodrich.
   The Press quoted a federal affidavit as saying Rubber Crafters
used inferior materials, covered up defects, falsified test results
and altered boat serial numbers.
</TEXT>
