<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 2027EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-TridentContract     10-05 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trident Contract,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Dynamics Gets Smaller Sub Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy on Wednesday awarded the General
Dynamics Corp. a $617.4 million contract for a new Trident missile
submarine, slashing more than $26.6 million off the price it paid
last year.
   Navy officials said the award demonstrated they had been right
in pressing a Virginia shipyard to compete against General Dynamics
more than a year ago, even if General Dynamics ultimately succeeded
in protecting its monopoly on the huge subs.
   ``It shows the benefits of competition,'' said Lt. Ken Ross, a
Navy spokesman. ``That previous competition ... is still bearing
fruit.''
   The contract awarded Wednesday represents the first of two
options in a contract initially awarded by the Navy in January
after competitive bidding between General Dynamics and the Newport
News Shipbuilding & Drydock Co.
   The award to General Dynamics' Electric Boat Division in Groton,
Conn., covers the one Trident submarine authorized by Congress in
the fiscal 1989 budget and will be the 16th in the line.
   The fixed-price contract specifies the Trident should be
delivered by October 1994. The Navy has said it wants to order at
least 20 Tridents and possibly more.
   With the exception of nuclear-powered aircraft carriers, the
Trident program was the last major Navy shipbuilding program to be
opened to competition. Newport News Shipbuilding, a division of
Tenneco Inc., enjoys a monopoly on the construction of aircraft
carriers, in part because no other shipyard has the massive
facilities required to build that type of ship.
   In November 1987, Newport News accepted a Navy request that it
compete against General Dynamics in the Trident program. It
submitted a bid for the fiscal 1988 sub as well as option bids on
the two additional boats expected to be purchased in fiscal 1989
and fiscal 1990.
   General Dynamics did the same, and last Jan. 5 the Navy
announced General Dynamics had succeeded in preserving its monopoly
by underbidding Newport News. The Navy awarded the firm a $644
million contract for the fiscal 1988 submarine, without revealing
what either company had bid for the two option years.
   Ross said Wednesday the Navy believes it will save roughly $100
million over the life of the contract if the second option is also
exercised.
   The spokesman said the latest award reverses what has been a
spiraling price for the huge vessels. The fiscal 1986 submarine
cost the Navy about $587 million. The price climbed to $615 million
in fiscal 1987, then rose again in January to $644 million.
   ``This contract is cutting more than $26 million off that fiscal
1988 buy,'' Ross said.
   The 560-foot Trident submarines _ also known as the Ohio class _
are considered the most survivable leg of America's nuclear
arsenal. Each of the vessels can carry 24 long-range, multi-warhead
nuclear missiles and remain submerged for months at a time.
   Each of the subs, when completely outfitted with nuclear
reactors and government-furnished equipment, cost more than $1.4
billion. Eight of the submarines are already commissioned on active
duty and a ninth _ the USS Tennessee _ will soon join them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881005-0311 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 2035EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Eastern     10-05 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Recalls 300 Furloughed Flight Attendants Effective Oct. 21</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines on Wednesday announced the recall
of 300 furloughed flight attendants, which follows the recent
layoffs of more than 3,000 employees to streamline the money-losing
carrier's operations.
   The furloughed flight attendants are being recalled effective
Oct. 21 because of the popularity of a long-term leave of absence
program, said Eastern spokesman Robin Matell.
   The program was offered as ``a way of minimizing the impact of
furloughs,'' and more volunteers were attracted than had been
anticipated, Matell said. More than 500 flight attendants took the
leave offer.
   Now 300 fired flight attendants will be recalled on the basis of
seniority, Matell said.
   Last week, a federal appeals court in Washington struck down a
lower court judge who had barred Eastern from carrying out the
furloughs. The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals rejected the union's
contention that the layoffs were part of a union-busting campaign
by Eastern's parent, Texas Air Corp. and its Chairman Frank Lorenzo.
   Along with the furloughs, which took effect Sept. 10 and
represented Eastern's largest layoff plans in its 60-year history,
the carrier eliminated service to 14 cities and closed its Kansas
City hub.
   Eastern's recall coincides with a seasonal increase in flights
to core markets along the East Coast and into the Caribbean and
Latin America.
   Matell said additional employees also may be recalled.
   ``We have to evaluate staffing needs and determine what's
what,'' he said.
</TEXT>
