<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 2129EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-UN-DebtCrisis     10-05 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-UN-Debt Crisis,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNCTAD Chief Executive Welcomes Reaction To Reduction Proposals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior U.N. official said Wednesday he is
pleased with the initial response from the international community
to a proposal that commercial lenders write off 30 percent of their
loans to 15 highly indebted Third World countries.
   But Kenneth Dadzie, Secretary General of the U.N. Conference on
Trade and Development, made clear that consensus on how to cope
with the debt crisis is far away.
   In a press statement, however, he voiced confidence that the
proposal, outlined in UNCTAD's 1988 report last month, ``served as
a catalyst for a rethinking of positions and will continue to do
so.''
   The countries targeted by the UNCTAD plan account for about 60
percent of Third World debt totaling some $500 billion. They are
Argentina, Bolivia, Brazil, Chile, Colombia, Ivory Coast, Ecuador,
Mexico, Morocco, Nigeria, Peru, the Philippines, Uruguay,
Venezuela, and Yugoslavia.
   Dadzie said that while the plan called for 30-percent cut of
commercial bank debt, ``our calculations can (perhaps) be improved
in either and upoward or downward direction.''
   He saiid it is increasingly obvious that large-scale debt
reduction ``cannot be accomplished by credit markets acting on
their own'' but that it required concerted action by creditors.
   Dadzie said recent statements by France, Japan and the director
oof the International Monetary Fund suggest ''that the need for
official action is gaining acceptance.''
   ``The form of the support, however, remains unclear,'' he added,
speaking of a ``highly complex situation.'' Dadzie's statement was
issued at the end of a two-week session of UNCTAD's 131-nation
governing body, the Trade and Development Board.
</TEXT>
