<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Zenith-Brookhurst     10-05 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zenith-Brookhurst,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zenith Gives List Of Stockholders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zenith Electronics Corp. agreed to hand
over a list of its stockholders to a group of dissident
shareholders Wednesday and said the group's attempt to wage a proxy
fight against Zenith management would not trigger the company's
takeover defense.
   Zenith agreed to give the list to Brookhurst Partners just
before a hearing in Delaware Chancery Court over the group's
attempt to wage a proxy battle to pressure the company into putting
itself up for sale.
   Just 20 minutes into the hearing, Zenith also surrendered on the
issue at stake in the proceeding: whether Brookhurst's proxy
solicitation would trigger Zenith's ``poison pill'' takeover
defense.
   Stephen Herrmann, Zenith's attorney, declared that the consent
solicitation of Sept. 14 would not trigger the rights plan, even if
15 percent of the shareholders' proxies were obtained by Brookhurst
Partners.
   This means Brookhurst is now free to solicit shareholder support
in its efforts to replace some company directors and sell Zenith.
   Brookhurst, which owns 6.1 percent of Zenith's stock, is
proposing to reduce the board from 10 members to six and replace
three of the six with its own candidates.
   Zenith, the only remaining U.S. television maker, is
incorporated in Delaware, but based in Glenview, Ill., north of
Chicago.
   The company has indicated its desire to remain independent, and
until Wednesday had resisted giving the shareholder list to
Brookhurst.
   Zenith has been fighting a losing battle against low-priced
imported televisions. Despite the success of its highly regarded
computers, Zenith suffered losses over the past three years,
including a $19.1 million loss last year on sales of $2.36 billion.
</TEXT>
