<DOCNO> AP881005-0316 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 2255EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Eastern-Trump 1stLd-Writethru f0230 10-05 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern-Trump, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0230,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Pilots Threaten To Block Reported Sale of Shuttle to Trump</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 new grafs after 5th graf pvs Texas Air... to UPDATE
with Trump comments to newspaper. Picks up 6th graf pvs, The
report...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unions at Eastern Airlines reacted angrily
Wednesday to a report that Texas Air Corp. was discussing the
possible sale of its East Coast air shuttle to developer Donald
Trump.
   The pilots union warned it would seek a court order to block any
such deal, and the head of the machinists union suggested his union
would do the same.
   The unions successfully blocked an attempt earlier this year by
Texas Air to transfer the shuttle operation from Eastern to a new
subisidiary.
   According to unidentified sources quoted by the Wall Street
Journal, the pricetag on the three-city shuttle was in the range of
$200 million.
   Texas Air spokesman Mark Johnson said the company had no comment
on the Journal report. Trump and his representatives also declined
comment.
   The New York Times, in its Thursday editions, quoted Trump as
saying he was close to agreement on a deal, and a contract could be
signed by next week. The newspaper also quoted unidentified
executives it said were close to the deal as saying Trump would pay
more than $300 million cash for the shuttle.
   Trump was dealing directly with Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo
in the deal, the Times quoted its sources as saying.
   The report came a day after Texas Air signed an agreement with
Scandinavian Airlines System giving the European carrier leases on
airport gates in the New York area and the right to buy up to 10
percent of Texas Air's stock on the open market.
   SAS will pay Texas Air $50 million under the accord, which also
includes provisions for coordinating marketing, reservations and
scheduling as well as training of airline personnel.
   In Miami, Eastern pilots union spokesman Ron Cole said the union
``will take whatever steps are necessary to legally protect Eastern
from the sale or transfer of any more of its assets.''
   The leader of the Machinists union said Eastern employees
probably would challenge any sale of the shuttle.
   ``We stopped the spinoff to Texas Air. It's something we will
have to look at as it relates to our ongoing litigation,'' said
Charles E. Bryan, head of the Machinists union at Eastern.
   The Machinists filed a federal suit earlier this year to block
the plan to make Eastern's shuttle a separate subsidiary of Texas
Air. Texas Air later dropped that effort.
   While stressing they did not know if the report was true, some
Wall Street analysts said Trump might use the shuttle, which
operates between Washington, New York and Boston, to help draw
people to his hotel and casino properties in Atlantic City, N.J.
Others expressed skepticism.
   ``I think it makes some eminent sense,'' said Julius Maldutis,
an airline analyst for Salomon Brothers Inc.
   One skeptic, John Pincavage of PaineWebber Inc., suggested it
would be difficult for Trump to revamp the shuttle to accommodate
traffic to Atlantic City. The shuttle service, one of the most
profitable operations of ailing Eastern, is mainly geared toward
business passengers.
   Texas Air would more likely sell aircraft or routes to raise
cash, rather than a lucrative shuttle operation, Pincavage said. He
suggested that discussions with Trump could be a way of putting a
pricetag on the shuttle in case Eastern declared bankruptcy and it
had to be sold.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
